a specially equipped van that can churn out more than 7,000 slices of pizza a day for hungry muscovites was unveiled in preparation for its shipment to the soviet union
the mobile pizzeria, conceived by two new jersey entrepreneurs, will be put aboard an container ship early next week for the two-week trip to helsinki, finland, astro pizza ltd. inc. officials said friday in this new york harbor city
company operations manager patrick ferrante said he would drive the van 750 miles to moscow, and that muscovites should be munching on american-style pizza within a month
they're going to love it. who doesn't love pizza?'' said louis piancone sr., president of roma food enterprises inc. in piscataway, which is participating in the joint venture
pizza will be made every seven minutes and will cost about 70 cents a slice, piancone said. a 16-inch cheese pie will go for $5.50, or seven rubles
the 36-foot-by-11-foot van has an oven, refrigerators, freezers and a machine that presses dough in three seconds. it several hundred thousand dollars to design and build, officials said
all the pizza ingredients will come from the united states, said piancone
piancone and partner shelley m. ziegler, who operates a trenton real estate and import firm, said they intend to follow the mobile pizzeria with up to 25 stores to serve pizzas and italian dishes to moscow residents and tourists
pizza is served in the soviet union but ``the concept is totally different from in america and that's unfortunate,'' piancone said
piancone and ziegler set up astro pizza after signing an agreement with moscow officials who visited new jersey last october
officials credited soviet leader mikhail gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness, with permitting their business to move ahead
piancone, who plans a later trip to the soviet union, said he hopes to serve pizza to gorbachev
to teach soviet employees the secret of making delicious pizza, several technicians from roma, which supplies pizza makers in 33 u.s. states with everything from pans to sauce, will accompany piancone
if the soviet venture succeeds, astro pizza outlets in spain, japan, china and italy may not be far behind, he said
the woman who resigned as head of gallaudet university after angry student protests says officials didn't foresee that having a deaf president would become ``a national civil rights matter.''
elisabeth ann zinser, who can hear and does not know sign language, said a week of outcry over her appointment at the school for the deaf made her see that deaf people as a group must ``take their place in society and this had become the time.''
i have responded to this extraordinary social movement of deaf people, not to the demands of the students and protesters,'' she said
as the search progressed and as we got to the point of actually making the offer to me, the situation was becoming more intense, but they still did not perceive that it would end up becoming a national civil rights matter,'' she said
she said she resigned when she realized how deeply the deaf community felt about the gallaudet presidency as a symbol
i eventually began to really believe what was being said here on the part of that community,'' she said
the 124-year-old school is the only liberal arts university for the deaf in the world, but has never had a deaf president
about 2,500 students and supporters rallied at the capitol after zinser resigned, claiming victory, but insisting that they would not stop until their demand for a deaf president is met
the students say they want the president chosen from the two deaf finalists from sunday
the students want jane bassett spilman, chairwoman of the board to resign, a deaf majority on the board, and guarantees that there would be no reprisals against any of the demonstrators
virtually all 2,200 graduate and undergraduate students at gallaudet participated in the week-long protests
we're still winning. we're still winning,'' said student leader jerry covell. he said he was pleased that zinser had resigned, but he urged the students to continue their battle
gary olsen, executive director of the national association of the deaf, told the students their protests had helped the cause of deaf people nationwide
truman stelle, a gallaudet faculty member, said, ``it is long past time that gallaudet had a deaf president, as testimony that deaf people are capable of leading themselves.''
stelle said the ouster of spilman was important because ``she clearly sees herself as owner of the gallaudet plantation, answerable to no one.''
at a news conference earlier friday, spilman criticized the ``external interests of people who perhaps are not as interested or involved in the day-to-day operations of gallaudet and not as well informed as the board and the administration.'' she did not elaborate
zinser, who was vice chancellor of the university of north carolina at greensboro, had never formally submitted her resignation there, and university of north carolina system president c.d. spangler said she would be welcome back
the house education and labor committee's subcommittee on select education, which has jurisdiction over funding for gallaudet, has scheduled hearings for tuesday to review the makeup of the board and the controversy over the presidential selection. three-quarters of the school's $76 million operating budget comes from the federal government
and john banzhaff, george washington university law professor and founder of the national center for law and the deaf, has filed a complaint with the district of columbia office of human rights charging the board with unlawful discrimination for never hiring a deaf president. up 3rd graf pvs, ``there were ...</note>
two car bombs exploded in the fashionable ``pink zone'' strip of restaurants and night clubs friday, injuring one boy and scattering dinner customers, witnesses said
the explosions occurred about 9:30 p.m., several hours after about 400 union activists marched through the capital to demand that the salvadoran government free a detained labor leader
the car bombs damaged five private cars and shattered windows in three businesses, the witnesses said
the boy had minor head and arm injuries but did not appear to be seriously hurt
no group immediately claimed responsibility for the explosions
leftist guerrillas assumed responsibility for a machine-gun attack in the same district june 19, 1985, in which 13 people, including four off-duty u.s. embassy marine guards and two american businessmen, were killed
in the march earlier friday, one demonstrator was wounded by a gunshot in the leg when other demonstrators identified an undercover security agent in their ranks and confronted him. the man pulled a pistol, shot a demonstrator and ran off
there were no confrontations with police or soldiers along the five-mile march route. uniformed security forces were not in sight
the demonstrators, many of whom carried nail-studded wooden clubs and iron bars, asked passengers to get off about 10 buses along the march route, then deflated the bus tires so the vehicles blocked side streets
a pickup truck was set afire near the u.s. embassy, where the marchers stopped for 30 minutes to denounce u.s. support for the salvadoran government
protesters painted the walls around the embassy with anti-american slogans, and set a stack of tires afire
the demonstrators demanded the release of humberto centeno, the leader of the telecommunications workers union, who was arrested thursday night
the union members alleged centeno was badly beaten by the troops who arrested him, and that he was hospitalized
the government acknowledged centeno's arrest but claimed he tried to attack a member of the security forces. it made no mention of his condition
centeno was arrested after about 50 union members occupied the labor ministry for nine hours thursday, demanding higher pay and reinstatement of fired workers
several metal boxes containing telephone line connections were pried open during friday's march, doused with gasoline, and set ablaze, leaving dozens of city blocks without phone service
take trend-setting princess diana, mix in a fashion collection that's cheeky and classic, long and short, and british designers hope to have the perfect ingredients for a smashing autumn season
conscious of the lingering effects of the october stock market crash and britain's soaring pound, london's top designers have abandoned the silly and unsaleable for a massive dose of realism _ what alastair blair calls ``just adult grown-up clothes.''
there is still plenty of individuality and a little zaniness _ vivian westwood's mini-crinoline skirt topped with a peplum and under-bust waistcoat _ but overall the fall collections launched friday were eminently wearable
the four-day london show attracting more than 6,000 buyers has become a regular stop on the international fashion circuit, sandwiched between the milan and paris shows. the clothing and textile industry is britain's third-largest export earner, with clothing exports alone totaling $2.4 billion
princess diana, one of the industry's biggest boosters, hopes to give britain's designers an edge over foreign rivals with a reception monday night at her home in kensington palace for 200 buyers, designers and fashion journalists
edina ronay, a favorite designer of the princess and her sister-in-law, the duchess of york, said: ``it's one-up on any other country that doesn't have a royal family that the whole world knows about.''
blair, another royal favorite, said of the princess: ``i think she's 98 percent responsible for the revival of interest in british fashion and i think what she's doing is terrific.''
like the italians, britain's designers couldn't decide whether hems should be long or short so they offered both with plenty of trousers, mainly wide, as well as some slimmer jodhpurs, breeches and dickensian stovepipes
several british designers also picked up on the italian fascination with ``ecological furs.'' arabella pollen, who did a circus theme, had fake leopard and zebra mini-suits and antony price did brocade suits and frock coats trimmed in fake mink
ronay's designs went edwardian. wendy dagworthy also explored ``retro themes of edwardian and late forties'' and betty jackson did hourglass edwardian jackets in a collection she called ``a complete mix-up ... which i love.''
the new realism of british fashion, the designers said, means choice, quality and price-consciousness
i think it's luxury dressing ... it's beautiful fabrics, it's opulent,'' said david sassoon of belville sassoon
and then there's a contradiction, well almost, with lots of trousers _ they're suddenly important again and they don't pose a length problem. women who don't know whether to go long or short will opt for pants,'' he said
betty jackson's collection was nearly all pants, wide and slim. rifat ozbek designed a clinging wool jersey jumpsuit with a tiny draped mini-skirt over it. bruce oldfield said shapes were more important than lengths _ and he's doing bell skirts
benny ong, who showed silks with short bell skirts as well as long tubular dresses, said: ``i think women want to look younger but without looking silly. give them a choice, but maintain their integrity.''
blair echoed that view, showing long and short skirts. ``i think women who do spend money on clothes are fed up that they have to look like 18-year-olds. you have to give people a choice.'' he said
with flounces and full skirts outmoded, blair said he was able to use less fabric and cut the cost of his daywear by 25 percent and his evening gowns by 17 percent _ a plus in the current financial climate
gina fratini, whose black velvet cocktail dresses with ruffles and dashes of hot pink, electric blue and turquoise were an instant seller, said the stock market crash had made the designers ``come out fighting.''
i think the stock market crash, if anything, has brought the fun clothes back because we want to cheer ourselves up,'' she said
a 30-year-old man slit his throat with a razor blade outside a judge's chambers shortly after being convicted of sexually abusing a 7-year-old girl and repeatedly burning her with a cigarette, authorities said
albert john lang of new derry was in serious condition today at westmoreland hospital in this western pennsylvania city, said a nursing supervisor who refused to give her name
the incident occurred friday after westmoreland county judge daniel ackerman excused the jury that convicted lang, said district attorney john driscoll
lang was handing his personal belongings to his wife when he suddenly charged toward ackerman's door, driscoll said. deputy sheriffs quickly locked the door
lang then sliced his throat with a razor blade and was subdued by the deputy sheriffs,'' driscoll said
lang was convicted of several counts of molestation and a charge of wounding the girl 90 times with a cigarette, according to driscoll
an agriculture department export program is helping alaska promote salmon in western europe and japan, two lucrative u.s. farm markets where competition is rising
the department's targeted export assistance program, popularly called tea, has allocated $1.95 million this fiscal year for the alaska seafood marketing institute, a quasi-independent commission of the state's department of commerce and economic development
according to a usda list of trade organizations sharing in the program, the only other comparable group is the catfish farmers of america, which was allocated $50,000
department officials said each tea plan is negotiated with the sponsoring group. some put up money to match or exceed the federal contribution, while others contribute less than tea provides
total funding of tea, which was authorized by the food security act of 1985, was pegged at a minimum of $110 million annually. about 40 different commodities, including alaskan seafood, share in the program
as directed by congress, the purpose of tea is to finance promotional activities for u.s. agricultural products that have been put to a disadvantage by subsidies and unfair trade policies of competitor nations
the institute is ready to pit alaska salmon against pen-raised salmon from norway being promoted in france and japan, according to roberta graham of evans-kraft bean, an anchorage public relations firm representing the institute
alaska processors also are attending trade fairs and food shows in tokyo and paris to promote salmon, ms. graham said this week (thursday) during a visit to washington
you have the corn belt and the wheat belt,'' she said. ``i choose to call alaska the fish belt.''
the importance of fishing to the alaskan economy cannot be understated, she said. it's second only to the oil, generating $900 million for the state's economy last year
in the first year of the tea program, the alaskans got $1.5 million from usda. the 1988 allocation, according to march 1 figures by the department's foreign agricultural service, is $1.95 million, making a two-year total of $3.45 million
but no matter how important fishing is to alaska, the state's tea allocation is a small part of the program's overall budget for the fiscal year that began on oct. 1. some other commodities qualified for much higher shares
the largest single tea allocation this year is $10.5 million to promote citrus from arizona and california. the american soybean association followed with $9.8 million. the u.s. feed grains council got $2.4 million, and u.s. wheat associates, $1.2 million
california, the nation's leading producer of agricultural products in terms of value, qualifies for the largest share of tea money. the 1988 allocations, for example, include six different california state commissions and boards affecting: avocados, $450,000; cling peaches, $5.7 million; kiwifruit, $500,000; prunes, $5.5 million; raisins, $9.8 million; and table grapes, $750,000
as the main producer of almonds, california also benefits from $6.5 million of tea money allocated for that crop this year. the walnut marketing board gets $6.5 million to promote walnuts overseas, another california crop
the keynote speaker for the agriculture department's conference on quality of farm products will be u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter
the meeting will be held in st. louis, mo., june 29 through july 1, said assistant secretary kenneth a. gilles
gilles said friday that the conference ``will focus on maintaining a quality advantage for american agriculture in the highly competitive domestic and international marketplace.''
subject matter will include cereals, oilseeds, fruits and nuts, vegetables, red meat, poultry, industrial crops, dairy, tobacco, cotton, wool, horticulture and forage crops
the major audience for this conference is farm organizations, farm market development organizations, agribusiness, wholesalers, retailers, trade associations, agriculturally related industries, and the agricultural higher-education community,'' he said
the agriculture department is adding the simbrah association to its list of registered cattle breeds so owners can qualify for higher federal payments when animals are slaughtered under the department's brucellosis eradication program
brucellosis is a highly contagious disease, said james w. glosser, acting administrator of the department's animal and plant health inspection service
our experience has shown that indemnities encourage owners to remove infected animals from their herds to prevent the spread of the disease.''
brucellosis can be passed on to humans _ where it is known as undulant fever _ through raw milk from infected cows
simbrah cattle are a cross between simmental and brahman, the department said. approximately 2,200 u.s. producers own registered simbrah cattle
to receive federal indemnities for registered cattle, the owner must present a certificate of registration as proof that the animal belonged to one of the 61 usda-listed breed associations
the indemnity rate for all dairy cattle, and registered beef cattle and bison is $250 per animal, while the payment for non-registered beef and bison is $50 per animal
officials said the new rule goes into effect on april 11. leasing plan</head>
local environmental groups from new england to florida to the pacific northwest are joining forces against the reagan administration's five-year plan for offshore oil and gas leasing
no longer will the fight to block the administration's leasing plan be a series of pitched battles,'' lynn davidson of greenpeace said friday
coalition organizers said at a news conference following three days of meetings in washington that they will consider joint public education campaigns, lobbying efforts and perhaps an advertising campaign
this is not a state, local or regional issue, it is a national issue,'' said rachael binah of the ocean sanctuary coordinating committee. ``we want americans to see the bigger picture
if the department of interior is allowed to continue with its five-year leasing plan, the coastline of the united states will be systematically destroyed,' she said
environmental leaders said they will focus on federal legislation for sensitive coastal areas in new england, florida and california that would block or defer implementation of the five-year leasing plan, which was unveiled last year by interior secretary donald hodel
the most sensitive parts of georges bank, a fishing-rich area off the new england coast, already are protected under a congressional moratorium. rep. gerry e. studds, d-mass., vowed last week to fight for the georges bank ban again this year
ann whitfield of the florida public interest research group said hodel, because of the five-year plan, makes former interior secretary james watt ``look like an environmentalist.'' watt and his policies were constantly under attack by the environmental community during his tenure early in the reagan administration
richard charter, who represents some cities and counties in the offshore leasing controversy in california, said the coalition also wants to force the leasing issue into the presidential campaign
we're here to send a message that america cares about its coastline,'' he said
he said all the democratic presidential aspirants have vowed to either oppose or modify hodel's plan, which outlines the areas open for leasing and creates a timetable for the leasing of tracts
the republican candidates have not answered issue inquiries sent by the activists, charter said
regional activists said they are fighting proposals to lease tracts off the coasts of california, florida, new england, the gulf and the pacific northwest
a group of environmentalists in august sued the interior department to halt the interior department's leasing plan. that suit is pending in the u.s. court of appeals
congressional analysts are challenging president reagan's contention that a capital-gains tax cut would reduce the federal budget deficit
although boosting the tax rate probably would produce less revenue, the congressional budget office concluded that most evidence indicates that a lower rate would also result in a revenue loss. the study estimated that loss at $3.9 billion to $7.8 billion a year if the top rate on long-term capital gains were lowered from 33 percent to 15 percent
some advocates estimate the government would collect as much as $15 billion a year more under a 15 percent cut because the lower rate would encourage people to sell long-held assets
cbo researchers cautioned against putting too much faith in any prediction of how taxpayers might react to changes. there are so many uncertainties, the study said, ``that one cannot reject the possibility that a 15 percent rate might increase revenues.'' but the cbo said that is unlikely
as part of the massive revision of federal income taxes in 1986, congress eliminated the long-time preferential treatment accorded capital gains, which are profits from the sale of stocks, real estate and other assets owned more than six months. that action raised the top rate on capital gains from 20 percent to 33 percent
in a written message to congress on jan. 25, reagan said: ``the most important piece of unfinished (tax) business is to reduce the capital-gains tax rate to the level that will generate the savings and investment necessary for future economic growth. past experience demonstrates that lowering the capital-gains tax rate will mean increased realizations of capital gains upon which taxes are paid
reducing the capital-gains tax rate to an agreed-upon optimum should be a cornerstone of tax reform for the 1990s,'' reagan wrote
the president did not say how deeply the rate should be cut, but the level mentioned most often by congressional advocates is 15 percent
there is considerable support in congress for reducing the maximum capital-gains rate. advocates say this not only would raise revenue _ by encouraging the sale of long-held assets _ but also would encourage new investment
opponents, noting that eliminating the capital-gains benefit was a major factor in getting the 1986 tax law enacted, contend restoring it would threaten that entire package
most benefits of a capital-gains reduction would go to the wealthiest americans. the internal revenue service estimates that taxpayers with incomes of $100,000 or more account for 55 percent of all capital gains but only 9 percent of other income
in a report to chairman william gray, d-pa., of the house budget committee, the cbo concluded that any increase in capital-gains realizations _ the sale of assets _ was not likely to generate enough revenue to offset a cut in the tax rate
in addition, the study said, restoring preferential treatment to capital gains might reduce other forms of taxable income, such as interest and dividends, because investments that created capital gains would be made more attractive than other types
teamsters president jackie presser's attorney says he's pleased with a ruling that prosecutors improperly obtained statements from an fbi agent charged with lying about his role in handling presser as an informant
we look forward to a similar result in the jackie presser case,'' attorney john climaco said in an interview in cleveland friday after an appeals court in washington suppressed statements that former cleveland fbi agent robert s. friedrick allegedly made to government prosecutors in early 1986
friedrick was indicted in may 1986 on five counts of making false statements that forced the government to delay for nearly a year its planned prosecution of presser
presser, who has headed the 1.6 million-member teamsters union since 1983, was also indicted in may 1986. a grand jury in cleveland charged him with two counts of labor racketeering, one count of embezzlement and two counts of filing false reports with the government. his trial is set for july
friedrick orginally said presser had been authorized by his fbi handlers to hire ``ghost employees'' at a cleveland teamsters union local who did no work
the justice department wanted to prosecute presser for the alleged ghost hirings, but abandoned the investigation after friedrick's assertions
however, friedrick admitted during the ensuing fbi-justice department inquiry that his statements about authorizing the illegal acts were false, according to tapes and transcripts provided by the justice department. his alleged admissions revived the teamsters probe, which resulted in the indictment of presser
friedrick's attorney, william beyer, said friday's appeals court decision eliminates the only evidence prosecutors have against his client
i don't know of any other evidence that they have to support their claim,'' beyer said in a telephone interview from cleveland
but friedrick, who was fired from the fbi last august, succeeded in having his alleged admissions suppressed as evidence by u.s. district judge george revercomb on grounds that the justice department interrogators had not advised him of his constitutional right to remain silent
clendon lee, spokesman for the u.s. attorney's office in washington, declined comment
it was unclear what effect the decision would have on the government's case against presser
stephen jigger, head of the fbi strike force in cleveland and prosecutor in the presser case, declined comment, saying he had not yet received a copy of the court decision
during a june 26, 1985, interview at fbi headquarters in washington, friedrick signed an fbi form that said he was required to answer questions, but that the government could not use his statements against him in a criminal prosecution as long as they were true
during interviews the following january, friedrick made statements contradicting his previous assertion that presser had been authorized to put ghost employees on the local's payroll. the next day he failed a lie detector test
the appellate court upheld revercomb's finding that friedrick was not warned during the interview that statements he made could be used against him
the prosecutors ``made a conscious decision prior to the interview not to furnish friedrick with or even mention (the fbi form); indeed they hoped that friedrick would make incriminating statements that they could use against him in a subsequent prosecution,'' the court said in an opinion by judge kenneth starr
a sore jaw from a bout in the dentist's chair has put gov. mario cuomo out of action for a couple of days and will probably cause him to skip a gridiron-style dinner, his press secretary says
the governor's dental work friday was nothing serious but was enough for him to be told to ``lay low'' through today, said gary fryer
as a result, cuomo will probably skip an appearance tonight at the annual inner circle dinner, a satirical look at new york city politics and government staged by reporters, fryer said
fryer said he wasn't certain of the exact nature of the dental work, but said cuomo might have to return for more
baseball player steve kiefer says he's lucky to be alive after getting smacked with a beer bottle that cut his neck
kiefer, an infielder with the milwaukee brewers, suffered cuts that required nearly 200 stitches after the incident thursday night at a night spot here
the doctor told me it was one-sixteenth of an inch from the carotid artery,'' said kiefer, 27. ``if it would have cut that, it would have killed me. i feel lucky to be alive.''
delfino neira, 28, of bakersfield, calif., was charged friday with aggravated assault. police said there was an argument over a woman's belt before neira left the bar, and he returned later and hit kiefer with the bottle
kiefer said he found a belt on the floor of the nightclub and gave it to a woman who said it was hers
shortly after that, kiefer said, neira ``came by and nudged me. i didn't accost him. i just said `excuse me.' '' neira apparently left the bar but returned about 45 minutes later
i don't recall any argument,'' kiefer said. ``the police said he was a friend of the girl who the belt belonged to. but i don't see what that had to do with it, because i gave it back to her.''
kiefer was expected to return to team workouts sunday
