the 8-pound, 9-ounce baby, alexandra lawford pender, is the 14th great-grandchild of matriarch rose kennedy. she was born friday at georgetown university hospital, the senator's office said
mrs. pender, 29, is a daughter of pat kennedy lawford and the late actor peter lawford. her husband, robert, is a washington attorney
both mother and child are doing well, officials said
lotfi mansouri has quit as general director of the canadian opera company with a parting shot to the local establishment, saying he would accept a similar post with the san francisco opera
the iranian-born mansouri, who has had the toronto post for 12 years, said he leaves the city with ``great sadness,'' but added, ``i am sick and tired of trying to justify the art form (here).''
at a news conference friday, he again expressed regret that the canadian company is not better supported by government funds and that there still is no definite word on a proposed new opera-ballet house in toronto
he will take up his new post in january 1989, succeeding general director terence mcewen, who is retiring for health reasons. both men are 58
the san francisco opera, second in size on the continent to new york's metropolitan opera, has a budget of $25 million, twice that of the canadian opera company
rosa l. parks, the 75-year-old heroine of the civil rights movement, left johns hopkins hospital with a new pacemaker
ms. parks, a detroit resident, received a pacemaker tuesday and was discharged friday, said hospital spokesman phil kibak
nearly 33 years ago, ms. parks refused to give up her seat to a white man on a segregated bus in montgomery, ala. she was arrested, and the black community retaliated by boycotting the buses
a national celebration in her honor is scheduled here in june
designer oscar de la renta will receive the first joslyn art museum fashion award
the joslyn women's association will give de la renta a crystal award inscribed with the joslyn insignia at a fund-raising luncheon june 13. plans for the award were announced thursday
the award will be given periodically to leading designers who show creativity and support the arts
president reagan says he is prepared to take additional steps against panama's government if a new series of economic sanctions does not force military strongman manuel antonio noriega from power
as expected, reagan announced friday that the united states will withhold a $6.5 million payment due to panama next tuesday for operations relating to the panama canal. he took other measures designed to make panmanian products less competitive in u.s. markets
until such time as a democratic government is restored in panama, the u.s. cannot proceed on a business as usual basis,'' reagan said in a statement
panama's ambassador, juan b. sosa, praised reagan's announcement. he told a news conference late friday that the sanctions, combined with anti-government actions by the panamanian people, will be enough to bring noriega down
sosa has refused to recognize the two-week old regime in panama, sharing reagan's view that it took power by unconstitutional means and is therefore illegitimate. sosa has declined to turn over the embassy to a new envoy named by noriega
rep. jack fields, r-texas, the ranking minority member of a house subcommittee that deals with the panama canal, said he was ``ecstatic'' over reagan's announcement. he predicted the sanctions will hasten noriega's departure
reagan said that noriega, under federal indictment on drug trafficking charges, would best serve panama by relinquishing his post as commander of panama's defense forces
reagan's announcement came two weeks after president eric arturo delvalle attempted to fire noriega but was instead ousted hours later in a move that had all the the earmarks of a military coup
the president said his decision to withhold the $6.5 million payment and place it in escrow was not in violation of u.s. obligations under the panama canal treaties
i am prepared to take additional steps, if necessary, to deny the transfer of funds to the noriega regime from other sources in the u.s.,'' reagan said
reagan also said that panamanian exports subject to u.s. tariffs will no longer be admitted at the lowest possible rates. secretary of state george p. shultz said the amount of annual trade affected by the decision is $96 million
in addition, reagan announced the suspension of panamanian participation in the caribbean basin initiative, under which some products are allowed duty-free entry into the united states
he also ordered stepped-up inspection of people and goods entering the united states from panama in order to apprehend drug traffickers and money launderers
shultz said there was no need to impose an additional sanction relating to the fees panama receives from alaskan oil shipments transferred to u.s. east coast ports through a panamanian pipeline
shultz said those fees already have been frozen based on earlier court action. estimates of the revenues panama receives from the pipeline range from $80 million to $120 million annually
the aim of the sanctions is to aggravate an existing cash-flow crisis in panama. panamanian newspapers said friday paychecks for government workers may have to be delayed because of the cash shortage
also on friday, abc news quoted diplomatic sources as saying the government of spain was prepared to offer asylum to noriega
the two countries most mentioned by opposition leaders as possible asylum sites are paraguay and the dominican republic. opposition leaders say they have sounded out the dominican republic and that noriega sent two military colleagues to paraguay this past week, possibly to discuss asylum prospects. saying fire might last four days, other quotes, color, smoke seen in fort-worth-dallas, val verde county fire, edits to tighten. no pickup.</note>
firefighters begged for help from neighboring counties friday in battling grass fires that seared a 60-mile swath across west texas ranch land
the fire is out of control on all fronts,'' the shackelford county sheriff's office reported. ``we're pulling all our forces back in to protect homes.''
the fire killed an undetermined number of cattle, set hunting camps ablaze, and destroyed at least one mobile home. some of the 500 firefighters suffered minor burns and were overcome by smoke, but no serious injuries were reported
the fire was reported within two or three miles of albany, a town of about 2,500 people, but evacuations were not immediately ordered. firefighters earlier burned ground near the town to divert the main fire
it's just an inferno in the pastures. and with winds of 35 mph, a horse couldn't outrun it,'' said albany resident liston f. todd, who was helping build firebreaks to detour the blaze
the fire, which began thursday, covered an area 60 miles long and 25 miles wide over three counties, with at least a 20-mile wide portion of the blaze out of control, officials said
joe fox, the texas forest service official overseeing the firefighting, said it could take four more days to finally put out the fire. smoke and haze reached the fort worth-dallas area, more than 120 miles east of the blaze
a u.s. forest service aircraft tanker was scheduled to fly over the area saturday morning, dumping up to 2,000 gallons of fire-extinguishing chemicals
shifting winds made it difficult to determine where the fire would spread, and in some cases firefighters were nearly surrounded by the swift flames
at least one firefighting bulldozer was caught and destroyed by the fire. a tv news team was momentarily threatened by a line of fire that suddenly changed course
twenty volunteer fire departments sent men and equipment to the area on friday, a day after gov. bill clements ordered 100 national guardsmen to help
they joined nearly two dozen forest service firefighters and the crews of 15 fire deparments. police radios crackled with pleas for more equipment and manpower to battle the blazes
texas forest service spokesman sam logan said there had been speculation that trash fires may have sparked the blazes when humidity dipped to 7 percent thursday. ``we consider anything below 30 percent is really dangerous.''
meanwhile, a blaze broke out in val verde county about 200 miles away, blackening 125,000 acres of ranchland about 60 miles north of the mexican border
no injuries were reported. a shift in the wind was expected to help the fire burn itself out, officials. est</note>
jesse jackson was hoping to win a clear majority of delegates today in south carolina's democratic presidential caucuses, while tennessee sen. albert gore jr. insisted he was a strong contender
if you believe it we're going to win this nomination,'' jackson told members of the south carolina education association friday
jackson said half the states have held primaries or caucuses and he has finished first or second in all but a few of them. ``in south carolina ... i want to win another gold medal.''
the caucus meetings at 1,788 precincts were scheduled to begin in the late afternoon
jackson came into south carolina second to massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in delegates overall, and jackson predicted that after today's caucuses and the primary tuesday in his second home, illinois, he would be the delegate leader
illinois sen. paul simon has virtually ignored south carolina recently and his state campaign coordinator, dan king, said friday that the campaign was asking simon supporters to remain uncommitted in the caucuses today but to work to become delegates to the county conventions later in the month
missouri rep. richard gephardt campaigned two days in the state this week and also is looking for a share of the 44 delegates at stake
gore, who toured the state's major cities friday, said he expected to do ``extremely well'' today and said he was the candidate with the momentum. he told a crowd of a few hundred supporters at the statehouse that his strong showing on super tuesday surprised everyone
i believe that momentum is going to continue right through the convention in atlanta and right through november,'' he said. ``i'm excited about the possibility of victory.''
john dukakis said friday he believed his father would get some support because of his front-runner status and his vision for economic growth
we would like to pick up some delegates,'' he said. ``but we're realistic and know it's going to be difficult. we understand that we're up against two strong favorite sons and that they are going to do well.''
a construction company facing lawsuits and fines over a building collapse in bridgeport, conn., that killed 28 workmen filed friday for reorganization under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code
texstar construction corp. and its subsidiary continental lift slab corp. took the step so that any litigation can be heard in texas rather than the unfriendly judicial environment of bridgeport, said corporate counsel david t. turlington
it acted after a federal judge in bridgeport approved a $187 million lien against company assets to cover any damages that might result from a suit filed over the april 1987 collapse of the l'ambiance plaza apartment complex by victims and families
you basically have convicted the guy and taken his assets, and he still hasn't had the right to a trial,'' said turlington. ``we are concerned about the political and judicial atmosphere in connecticut, which has been attempting to ban the lift-slab method.''
san antonio-based texstar was the primary subcontractor on the l'ambiance plaza. it was constructed using the lift-slab method, in which concrete floors are poured on the ground, then lifted by jacks to their proper height along vertical steel columns
the occupational safety and health administration fined texstar $2.52 million for 238 instances of alleged willful violations. texstar also has been referred to the justice department for possible prosecution
on march 2, victims and families of victims filed suit in u.s. district court in bridgeport against texstar. judge warren eginton on march 2 gave the plaintiffs permission to attach $187 million of texstar's assets
texstar listed unsecured debts of almost $190 million and assets of about $1.3 million. continental lift slab listed unsecured debts of $150,449 and assets of $327,709
chapter 11 allows a company to hold off its creditors while it undergoes a financial reorganization
in a statement, texstar said friday that it has not been given the opportunity ``to a fair and impartial trial or hearing'' and that bankruptcy court would provide a forum to answer the allegations
we are certainly not going to stop the presses just because texstar has filed chapter 11,'' said bridgeport attorney richard beider, lead counsel for the victims' families
bieder called the action ``unfortunate because it is another blow to the families of the victims that comes on the heels of the tragedy itself and on the heels of laws that are like hurdles that the families have to overcome to receive just compensation.''
associations representing city and county governments are ``virtually certain'' to appeal a court ruling that is permitting the reagan administration to withhold $180 million in revenue sharing funds, an attorney says
a three-judge panel of the u.s. court of appeals for the district of columbia circuit on friday reversed a lower court ruling and said the administration did not have to distribute the money to local governments
i think it's virtually certain we'll ask the court to reconsider its decision,'' said david c. vladek, a lawyer for the national association of counties, the national league of cities, the u.s. conference of mayors and 10 city and county governments
my sense is the court did not fully comprehend the nature of our legal arguments,'' he said
the dispute involves president reagan's feb. 1, 1986, order under the gramm-rudman law that set aside 4.3 percent of budget items, including $180 million from that year's $4.2 billion appropriation to the revenue sharing trust fund
the local governments argued that the law provided that 1986 budget money that had been sequestered should remain in government trust funds and be paid out in 1987. they argued that even though congress had abolished revenue sharing after 1986, it intended that any money remaining in the trust fund be distributed
revenue sharing, begun under the nixon administration, provided nearly all local governments with unrestricted federal grants
u.s. district judge joyce hens green on july 28 ruled in favor of the local governments and said treasury secretary james a. baker iii had illegally transferred the revenue sharing money from the trust fund to the general fund
however, judge john r. gibson, who wrote the appeals panel's decision reversing green, said congress' intent with the gramm-rudman law was clearly to reduce the federal budget deficit
merely freezing (the monies in 1986) and resuscitating them (in 1987) would not result in any meaningful deficit reduction and could be characterized by critics to be a sham,'' said gibson, who was joined by judges patricia m. wald and david santelle
the result in this case may be harsh, but we believe it is consistent with congressional intent,'' wrote gibson, who was designated to the case from the u.s. court of appeals for the eighth circuit in st. louis
among the plaintiffs are new york city; kansas city, mo.; milwaukee county, wis.; and cuyahoga county, ohio, which includes cleveland
the u.s. conference of mayors, at the time of the original district court decision last summer, had estimated that new york would receive $10 million; chicago, $2.6 million; los angeles, $2.2 million; and detroit $1.3 million of the money
other estimates were $606,000 for new orleans; $554,000 for indianapolis; $677,000 for washington d.c.; $440,000 for denver and $104,000 for des moines, iowa. estimates for other cities were not provided
here is a transcript of gary hart's statement withdrawing friday from the race for the democratic presidential nomination
thank you very much
thank you all very much
i want to, first of all, introduce my wife, lee, our son, john
i want also to acknowledge the presence of some very good friends and great party leaders here today: the governor of the state of colorado, roy romer. our good personal friends and more than worthy successor to me in the united states senate, tim and wren wirth. and the chairman of the colorado state democratic party, and also a very good friend of ours, buie seawell
we want to thank each and every one of you for being here
few people have had the good fortune that i've had; good fortune measured in terms of my family and a far-flung network of friends and supporters around the country, and in the opportunities that i have been given to serve my country
fewer americans, still, have had the opportunity to run for president of the united states, and i've had that chance twice
the people are the strength of this country
i said i wanted them to decide about my candidacy
i got a fair hearing
and the people have decided
and now i clearly should not go forward
my candidacy represented a more complicated and difficult choice than in 1984
a choice beyond the scope of traditional politics, and i fully understood that
i also had a more far-reaching and complex economic, defense, and foreign policy agenda
that was difficult to reduce to slogans and sound bites
nonetheless, i did get a chance, particularly in the debates, to get my message of fundamental change and reform on the record, and to draw distinctions between my ideas and those of the other democratic candidates
for that, i want to thank all those, especially the young people who came to my speeches
and i want to thank members of the press and media who were fair, balanced and professional
lee and i want to congratulate mike and kitty dukakis, jesse and jackie jackson, and al and tipper gore, for their very impressive achievements last tuesday and before
they've all worked extremely hard, and they deserve every bit of the credit they have received
i also want to thank paul simon, along with the others, for his gentlemanliness towards me in the debates, and wish him well in his home state primary
while disagreeing with him strongly on trade and international economics, i've been extremely impressed with dick gephardt's thoughtfulness and his equanimity under harsh attack
despite his lack of political success, all of us gained great respect for bruce babbitt, as truth-teller and prophet on our national budget and fiscal policy
win or lose, each of these candidates has grown in stature and deserves to be considered as genuine national leaders
but win or lose, we also face an unhappy reality
the democratic party has won only one national election since 1964
the struggle in our party is not between the left and the right, it's between the past and the future
and those who cling to the past too often mask their lack of vision and direction with caution and vagueness and platitudes
we can only win if we are prepared to govern
and we can only be prepared to govern if we challenge the future with bold, specific new policies to make our economy productive once again, and to conduct a serious foreign policy in an increasingly complex world
the remaining candidates should forgo the bitter personal attacks so favored by political insiders, and, instead, show their concern for the national interest by seriously debating the issues that are threatening our country
instead of canceling or running from debates, now that there are fewer candidates, there should be more debates
a presidential campaign really is a debate over differences among the candidates
and that's what it ought to be
the remaining candidates should put out budget proposals to reduce reagan deficits and show how they would pay for their programs
this would demonstrate competence and show honesty on the tax issue
i encourage these candidates to learn the principles and philosophy of military reform, because that represents the best defense policy for our country
and they should spell out a foreign policy framework that's specific on issues such as third world debt and the use of military force to avoid the continuing pitfalls of ad hoc response of crisis after crisis
we should challenge our young people to help eliminate illiteracy and poverty and pollution, to give something back to their country through a voluntary national service
so now is the time that the candidates should welcome serious debates, not about personalities, but about policies for this country's future
the reason i got back in the race was to help stimulate that debate about the future, to challenge caution and narrow-interest politics of the past, and to lead the cause of reform
and i intend to continue that leadership for reform, because it is the best hope for our country
it's a cause that lives on beyond any campaign
i hope those who share that cause will help me continue the center for a new democracy, which we began in 1984
through the center, through speeches, through writing and symposiums around the country, we can provide a voice for those who know our policies must be fundamentally restructured to keep the torch of democracy and idealism and hope alive
most of all, i want to say that no one has ever been more blessed with family and friends than i have
my friends and supporters around the country have given the word ``loyalty'' new meaning
they've toiled tirelessly in an uphill fight, understanding the odds throughout, and having as their only reward the knowledge that they had done their very best to move our country forward
to all of you everywhere, particularly the young people, my very warmest thanks and deepest gratitude, and i promise that i'll find some way in years to come to repay your commitment and loyalty to the cause which we shared
public words, of course, are insufficient to express my feelings towards lee and andrea and john, each of whom has demonstrated in his or her own way inexhaustible courage and fortitude and conviction in that same cause
they're owed more than i can ever possibly repay
and to those of you in and out of politics who may face setbacks, failures, or defeats, who are told to give up, accommodate, or compromise, i hope you'll simply say, as i do, ``hell, no.''
preserve your integrity, study time and patience, and never give up
as i have before, i leave with you these words:
no great cause is ever lost or ever won. the battle must always be renewed and the creed restated, for some things are universal, catholic, and undying. they do not age or pass out of fashion, for they symbolize eternal things. they are the guardians of the freedom of the human spirit, the proof of what our mortal frailty can achieve.''
thank you all
god bless you
here is a brief chronology of the life of former national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane, particularly events related to his involvement in the iran-contra affair:
july 12 _ born in washington, d.c., the son of william doddrige mcfarlane, a new deal democratic congressman. grows up in graham, texas
receives a b.s. degree in electrical engineering from the u.s. naval academy in annapolis, md. commissioned as a second lieutenant in the u.s. marine corps. four days after graduation, marries his wife, jonda
serves with the marines in the far east, including a combat tour in vietnam
works as white house fellow in the nixon administration
named military assistant to henry a. kissinger, who was then national security adviser to president nixon
becomes special assistant for national security affairs to president ford
frustrated with the policies of the carter administration, he resigns commission as lieutenant colonel in the marine corps. he serves as assistant to sen. john tower, r-texas, on the senate armed services committee
january _ named a counselor in the state department, under then secretary of state alexander haig
january _ becomes chief deputy to william p. clark, who was president reagan's national security adviser, and ran the day-to-day operations of the national security council
july _ named special envoy to the middle east, succeeding philip habib, at a time when israel was occupying a large part of lebanon
october _ chosen by president reagan to succeed clark as national security adviser. soft-spoken and shunning publicity, he gains a reputation for working 80-hour weeks
may _ mcfarlane meets with bandar bin sultan of saudi arabia to discuss the needs of the nicaraguan contra rebels
july _ israeli official suggests to mcfarlane that a transfer of arms to iran could lead to the release of u.s. hostages in lebanon. mcfarlane takes the message to reagan
aug. 30 _ first plane load of u.s.-made weapons sent from israel to tehran. mcfarlane and white house chief of staff donald regan later disagree over whether the president approved the shipment. mcfarlane says yes, regan says no
dec. 4 _ mcfarlane resigns as national security adviser and is succeeded by rear adm. john poindexter. sources say mcfarlane's rivalry with regan led to the resignation
he joins the center for strategic and international studies, a washington policy study center, but later continues working for the national security council as a consultant
may 25 _ mcfarlane and national security council aide oliver north fly to tehran with a shipment of military equipment, expecting hostages to be freed. they take a cake shaped like a key and a bible signed by president reagan. the negotiations fail and they fly home
dec. 1-3 _ he testifies to the senate intelligence committee in the initial congressional inquiry into the iran-contra affair
dec. 8 _ mcfarlane falsely tells the house foreign affairs committee that he did not know about solicitation of donations to the contras from an unidentified foreign country, later revealed to be saudi arabia
feb. 9 _ mcfarlane is hospitalized after taking an overdose of valium in a suicide attempt. he is hospitalized for two weeks. he says later in an interview, ``what really drove me to despair was a sense of having failed the country.''
may 11 _ mcfarlane begins four days of testimony before the congressional iran-contra committees. he tells committee members, ``shoot your best shot.''
in the testimony, mcfarlane says the president instructed his staff in 1984 to find ways around the congressional ban on military aid to the contras. he denies that he, north and poindexter concocted a cover-up story in november 1986
march 11 _ mcfarlane pleads guilty to misdemeanor charges that he misled congress in december 1986. he avoids the more serious charge of perjury and pledges to cooperate with the independent counsel investigating the iran-contra affair
the charges involve assurances that mcfarlane made in three 1985 letters that the administration was not secretly aiding the contras and a fourth statement in testimony before the house foreign affairs committee on dec. 8, 1986
following is the text of robert c. mcfarlane's statement to reporters after his guilty plea to misdemeanor charges of misleading congress in the iran-contra affair
i should say at the outset that from the beginning, judge walsh and all of his staff have dealt with me in a thoroughly professional way. as judge walsh has said, on the occasions that were cited inside, i did indeed withhold information from the congress. i believe strongly that throughout, my actions were motivated by what i believed was in the best foreign policy interests of the united states
from the first moment when the iran-contra disclosures were made in november of '86, i felt a profound personal obligation to testify fully and voluntarily before the bodies that were formally established to investigate this matter _ that includes the tower commission, the joint committee of the congress, and the independent counsel. i have done so, in more than 200 hours of public and private testimony, without access to my records, or with any request for or promise of immunity. i've told all that i know, and it's on the public record for everyone to see. and i intend to remain available to repeat it for as long as it's necessary to bring this matter to a conclusion
i do think that it's unfortunate that the fundamental issue here, that is, why congressional-executive relations broke down so tragically, has not been and apparently cannot be dealt with by the congress or the courts. it seems to me important _ indeed, imperative _ that an in-depth exploration of how to forge a better working relationship is essential if the united states _ and i mean by that the president and the congress _ is to shoulder its global leadership responsibility in the years ahead
and finally, i intend to do what i can to contribute to that continuing effort
here is a text of the statement president reagan released friday announcing a series of sanctions against the government of panama:
the united states has had a long and mutually productive relationship with panama. the people of the united states consider the people of panama to be near neighbors and friends. the historic panama canal treaties exemplify the close cooperation that has traditionally characterized the friendship between the two countries which created one of the great engineering works of the human race
out of concern for our friendship, we have been saddened and increasingly worried in recent years as panama's political crisis deepened. our policy with respect to the situation in panama is clear. we strongly favor a rapid restoration of democracy and the resumption by the panamanian defense forces of a role consistent with constitutional democracy
in the present circumstances, i believe that general noriega would best serve his country by complying with the instruction of president delvalle to relinquish his post. in so doing, general noriega would contribute very substantially to reducing political tensions and set the stage for a prompt transition to democracy in panama
until such a time as democratic government is restored in panama, the u.s. cannot proceed on a `business as usual' basis. today, therefore, i have taken a number of steps against the illegitimate noriega regime that will contribute significantly to the goal of a democratic, stable and prosperous panama
i have directed that actions be taken to suspend trade preferences available to panama under the generalized system of preferences and the caribbean basin initiative. further, in keeping with the spirit of our war against drugs, i have ordered that panama be subject to intensified scrutiny by our immigration and customs services in order to apprehend drug traffickers and money launderers
moreover, because we recognize president delvalle as the lawful head of government in panama, i have directed that all departments and agencies inventory all sources of funds due or payable to the republic of panama from the u.s. government for purposes of determining those that should be placed in escrow for the delvalle government on behalf of the panamanian people. in that light, i have directed that certain payments due to panama from the panama canal commission be placed in escrow immediately. this step is in complete compliance with our obligations under the terms of the panama canal treaties
i am prepared to take additional steps, if necessary, to deny the transfer of funds to the noriega regime from other sources in the u.s
we have welcomed the recent statements issued by president delvalle, the political parties and the civilian crusade of panama calling for a government of national reconciliation. we support their goal of restoring democratic government and constitutional order. once panamanians achieve this goal, the united states is fully prepared to work with the government of panama to help quickly restore panama's economic health
the united states has been, and remains, committed to fulfilling faithfully its obligations under the panama canal treaties. we are also prepared to resume our close working relationships with the panamanian defense forces once civilian government and constitutional democracy are re-established
here in brief are the sanctions imposed by president reagan against panama on friday:
monthly payments of about $6.6 million for operations relating to the panama canal will be held in escrow instead of being paid to the government. panama receives about $80 million from the canal annually
reagan also ordered all u.s. government agencies to inventory payments due panama ``for the purposes of determining those that should be placed in escrow for the delvalle government on behalf of the panamanian people.''
trade preferences available to panama under the generalized system of preferences, a special system for third world countries, and the caribbean basin initiative, were suspended. secretary of state george p. shultz said the action affects $96 million worth of trade a year
panama will be subject to intensified scrutiny by immigration and customs service officials ``to apprehend drug traffickers and money launderers.''
there was widespread speculation that reagan would order american companies to stop using a pipeline across panama, which generated revenue for the government. however, shultz said those funds already are frozen under a temporary restraining order issued by u.s. courts
shultz said ``if there are further steps needed ... he will take them.'' he refused to elaborate, saying, ``i think it's better to leave that a little uncertain.''
here are some of the latest comments by candidates for the presidency:

bob dole, seeking to save a candidacy he says is ``hanging by our fingernails'' and maintaining many voters are still undecided: ``it's like last-minute christmas shoppers. some people don't even know what they're going to buy until the last 24 hours and then they buy whatever is left. we don't want that to happen.''

george bush, declining a one-on-one confrontation with dole, recalling that he tried that with ronald reagan in 1980 and probably lost the gop nomination that year because of it: ``i may be older, but i'm a lot smarter now, too.''

michael dukakis, dining in chicago's ``greektown'' section and commenting on whether he is trying to build an ethnic coalition: ``we want to put together a coalition of people all over this country, whether they're first-generation or second-generation americans.''

albert gore, continuing to attack dukakis: ``his complete lack of experience in foreign policy is, i think, a major issue at a time when the next president must be prepared to seize the opportunities for a new relationship with the soviets.''

pat robertson, saying he will campaign all the way to the republican national convention: ``i'm in it until new orleans.''

gary hart, abandoning his presidential bid: ``the people are the strength of this country. i said i wanted them to decide about my candidacy. i got a fair hearing. and the people have decided. and now i clearly should not go forward.''

richard gephardt, complaining about negative television ads in the south: ``i feel like dukakis and gore have mugged me in an alley. they are borrowing my rhetoric, but they don't have any substance behind it.''

jesse jackson, urging blacks and whites in south carolina to unite around him: ``it's not so much black versus white as it is barracudas eating us small fish. they don't eat fish by color. they eat fish by size.''

paul simon, asking educators to help him win tuesday's illinois primary: ``we want to send a message to the nation from illinois. part of that message is that for people who need quality education, this administration has been out to lunch.''
a former top aide to gov. evan mecham acknowledged that he told the governor an alleged death threat by a state official was a ``frivolous matter'' mecham should forget about
max hawkins, former head of the department of administration, testified friday at the republican governor's impeachment trial that he thought the alleged threat was ``a matter that would probably go away by itself.''
mecham is accused of trying to thwart the attorney general's investigation of the threat, allegedly made against a witness testifying before a state grand jury that was investigating the governor's campaign finances
earlier friday, another former state official, sam steiger, testified the governor believed some of his decisions were ``divinely inspired.''
steiger had been asked by sen. john mawhinney whether mecham, a devout mormon, ``could and would make decisions on specific pieces of legislation through, he believed, some divine inspiration.''
asked by a reporter about steiger's testimony, mecham said only, ``sam, he's a little off the wall in some of his comments, too.''
mormon doctrine holds that faithful christians may receive guidance from god regarding worldly endeavors, including their occupations
the day marked the end of the second week of mecham's senate trial. in addition to the death threat allegation, he is accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
former state prison construction chief lee watkins is accused of threatening the life of former top mecham aide donna carlson in a conversation with peggy griffith, head of the governor's office of women's services
hawkins testified that he spoke on nov. 13 with watkins and mrs. griffith and that he did not believe an actual death threat was made
instead, hawkins said he felt that watkins had said that ms. carlson should keep her mouth shut and ``there are a lot of people out there who are excitable and she could have harm come to her.''
hawkins said that when he told watkins that mrs. griffith had reported the matter to others, ``he laughed and thought that it was absurd'' that she was telling anyone about it
hawkins said he met with mecham later that day and told the governor that he had found ``that it was a little spat, a frivolous matter'' and that mecham should forget about it
watkins has denied threatening ms. carlson's life. he is scheduled to return to the stand monday. mecham could testify late next week, said defense lawyer fred craft
steiger blamed many of mecham's troubles on attorney general bob corbin, a republican
steiger said mecham resented corbin because the governor took the political heat for canceling a martin luther king holiday for state workers when it was corbin who first said the holiday was illegally created through an executive proclamation by mecham's predecessor, bruce babbitt
steiger faces an extortion charge brought by corbin's office on an unrelated matter
corbin, contacted for comment on steiger's testimony, said, ``just remember the position he is in with regard to our office and you can draw your own conclusions.''
mecham also faces a may 17 recall election and an april 21 criminal trial on charges of concealing the $350,000 loan
he is the first u.s. governor impeached in six decades and the first ever in arizona. a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict him, and lawmakers also could bar him from holding any future public office
mushers in the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race traded rolling hills for the flat expanse of the frozen yukon river as they tried to catch 70-year-old joe redington, who's led since tuesday
redington arrived at ruby, a yukon village 653 miles from the race's start in anchorage and the first checkpoint on the river, at 12:30 p.m. friday and left six hours later
his closest rival, martin buser of big lake, pulled in at 5:05 p.m. in third was herbie nayokpuk of shishmaref, who arrived in ruby at 6:20 p.m
four-time iditarod champion rick swenson of two rivers was running fourth. he checked out of cripple, 120 miles back, at 7:25 p.m. thursday. joe garnie of teller followed swenson out at 8:45 p.m., and defending champion susan butcher of manley left at 9:50 p.m
jerry austin of st. michael, running in eighth place, said he and several mushers near him are still strong contenders in a race that won't reach the finish line in nome until later next week
don't write off anybody that's three or six hours off the pace right now,'' he said in cripple. ``we're just inching our way up. we're steadily gaining on them.''
butcher noted that redington and nayokpuk took their mandatory 24-hour layovers early in the race, an advantage because the leaders later got bogged down in new snow. but that advantage may be wearing thin, she said
it was a break for them in the beginning, but now they've been going with no real long rest for a while. i think our dogs are fresher,'' she said
but nayokpuk, who couldn't keep up with redington between cripple and ruby, said butcher and swenson may have trouble catching redington
i tried to travel with joe redington from cripple, but he disappeared in a hurry,'' a tired nayokpuk said as he sat on the porch of a house in ruby and changed his boots. ``i never saw him again. he has the dogs. if he gets those dogs running to nome, he's going to be a hard one to beat.''
redington is known as the father of the iditarod for helping found the race 16 years ago
the race started march 5 in anchorage. after ruby, mushers race 146 miles downriver to the village of kaltag, then cross to the bering sea coast for a final dash to nome
the winner will collect $30,000 of a $150,000 purse; the next 19 finishers will split the rest. two of the 52 teams that started the race have dropped out
the arrest of two men is believed to have solved 21 bank stick-ups committed in the last two months by a motorcycle bandit and a robber dubbed ``the old man,'' police said
mark macadoo, 22, of san pedro, was arrested thursday by fbi agents and officers of the city police department's bank team while awaiting a bus
macadoo was held in connection with 10 robberies in which the bandit escaped on a motorcycle with a total of about $6,000, police lt. bruce meyer said friday
the second man, howard bonner, 59, nicknamed ``the old man'' because of his appearance, was arrested at a party thursday night, meyer said. ``the old man'' stole about $20,000 in cash in 11 robberies, meyer said
panamanians who have been unable to cash their checks for 10 days faced cuts in public services today as washington increased economic pressure on the government to force panama's strongman to resign
president reagan on friday froze millions of dollars in panamanian assets in the united states and again called on gen. manuel antonio noriega to step down as chief of the 15,000-member defense forces
panama's new chief executive, manuel solis palma, met with his cabinet in an emergency session friday
he was to meet with the cabinet again today, ``to work out a total package plan to deal with the crisis, especially a payment plan for public employees who must be paid by march 15,'' said an official, speaking on condition of anonymity
the government reportedly was considering delaying or reducing payments due tuesday to nearly 150,000 government employees
banks closed march 1 because of the lack of currency, leaving panamanians holding checks they cannot cash. panama's currency is the u.s. dollar
solis palma, ordered reductions in public services friday as the government's coffers ran low
the government ordered cutbacks in electricity and fuel consumption, telephone and public vehicles use. it also announced a two-hour reduction in working hours for government offices
reagan said the united states will place fees due to panama this month from the panama canal into escrow until a government led by ousted president eric arturo delvalle can claim them. a $6.6 million payment of canal fees is due tuesday
pro-noriega legislators ousted delvalle from the presidency feb. 26, a day after delvalle tried to fire noriega. solis palma was named to replace delvalle, who has been in hiding since
the united states continues to recognize delvalle as panama's legitimate president
reagan also suspended trade preferences granted panama and ordered increased scrutiny of the country by u.s. immigration and customs service officials to ``apprehend drug traffickers and money launderers.''
i believe that gen. noriega would best serve his country by complying with the instruction of president delvalle to relinquish his post,'' reagan said, calling noriega's regime illegitimate
noriega was indicted last month in the united states on drug trafficking and money laundering charges
boris moreno, a panamanian government spokesman, said the u.s. actions created a ``state of war'' and set a dangerous precedent
this means that if the united states government does not like the government of another country, it can withhold any funds deposited in the united states,'' he said
noriega made no comment on reagan's new sanctions. an official statement by the foreign ministry on the u.s. actions was expected
riot police firing tear gas grenades and spraying a stinging, acrid liquid from canisters prevented opposition parties from holding a demonstration in the central banking district friday
three journalists were injured when police sprayed tear gas in their faces at close range. they were: lucia annunziata, a reporter with the newspaper la repubblica of rome; david walters, a photographer with the miami herald; and manolo iscala, a cameraman for spanish television
the u.s. sanctions were expected to deepen a cash-flow crisis that has forced panamanian banks to close for 10 consecutive days. attorneys for delvalle have tied up an estimated $50 million in official panamanian funds in private u.s. banks
the government on friday asked owners of four supermarket chains, a department store and a pharmacy chain to act as check-cashing houses for government employees. the owners refused, saying it was up to the central bank to guarantee government checks
businesses have not been accepting credit cards or checks for purchases, only cash
more than 200 air ontario pilots walked off the job today over a wage dispute, shutting down the regional commuter services that handles 60,000 passengers monthly
company spokesman paul mcknicht said friday that the pilots agreed to continue flying air ontario air ambulances during the strike
the bulk of our flight operations will be curtailed but management personnel will be operating a few essential services in remote communities of northern ontario,'' mcknight said
those communities, north of timmins, depend on the airline to fly in commodities such as food and fuel, he said
negotiations between air ontario and the canadian air line pilots association broke off thursday over pay. the pilots walked off the job at 12:01 a.m. today
union spokesman roger burgess-webb said union officials have told the airline they would be willing to resume talks but no further discussions have been scheduled
neither side would predict how long the strike would last, but mcknight said it would be ``very very expensive.''
the airline acts as a feeder for air canada flights from london, where it is based, and 47 other communities around ontario
air ontario inc was created last may when air ontario ltd. merged with austin airways of timmins. air canada owns 75 percent of air ontario
air ontario has flights to winnipeg and montreal in canada, and to hartford, conn., and cleveland, ohio. mounts</head>
three intelligence operatives who say the fbi and cia asked them to infiltrate lyndon larouche's political operation repeatedly tried to involve him in illegal activities, a larouche attorney told a judge
defense lawyer michael reilly on friday urged u.s. district judge robert e. keeton to halt testimony in larouche's fraud and conspiracy trial until prosecutors finish searching government records for references to the operatives and evidence of infiltration of larouche groups
keeton canceled testimony for monday, and said he would decide then if a longer delay was necessary in the trial of larouche, six aides and five larouche organizations
the defendants are charged with conspiring to obstruct a federal grand jury investigation into alleged credit card and loan fraud during larouche's 1984 presidential campaign
keeton has ordered assistant u.s. attorney john markham to search the files of the fbi, cia, national security council and vice president george bush
reilly said he would present evidence of entrapment in private if keeton desired, but refused to be specific in open court. keeton did not request the information
the three operatives referred to by reilly are retired army sgt. maj. fred lewis, ron tucker and gary howard. in an fbi document declassified last week, lewis, tucker and howard said they were asked by the fbi and cia to infiltrate larouche organizations
markham filed a memo in which he charged the three men were lying
a search of the fbi files relating to them shows that they were never requested to penetrate the organization and that they never did so,'' markham said in the memo
reilly disputed that, saying markham's memo made no reference to infiltration on behalf of the cia. he also noted a memo between two pivotal players in the iran-contra scandal in which lewis is referred to by last name, but only as proof lewis was well known by government officials
in a memo sent to then-nsc aide oliver north by retired air force maj. gen. richard secord, one of north's principal operatives in the network helping nicaraguan contra rebels, secord said ``our man'' told him lewis had gathered ``info against larouche.''
lewis is the executive vice president of rhyolite management systems, a texas company larouche lawyers contend was one of several companies run by former military officers that the cia used to carry out covert activities
howard and tucker claim to be longtime government informants and were the founders of another texas company, now defunct, that reportedly carried out covert activities
markham originally told defense lawyers that ``our man'' referred to oliver ``buck'' revell, a top fbi official involved in counterintelligence. markham later said he was mistaken and that the reference was to john cupp, a secord associate who worked in the resupply effort
secord and cupp, in interviews this week, also have said the reference was to cupp. both denied any role in or knowledge of a government effort to spy on larouche
reilly on friday filed a motion demanding the information markham relied on when he initially said secord was referring to revell
if `our man here' is in fact oliver revell, it would create a motive for high-level forces in the fbi and national security council to conceal that in order to protect mr. revell,'' the motion said
larouche attorneys said the information might help them prove their contention that north asked the fbi and cia to infiltrate larouche groups because they were interfering with north's private contra resupply effort
an fbi spokesman said the agency would not comment on matters at issue in a trial
the general services administration says it is ``reluctantly'' extending the deadline for bids on a new multibillion-dollar government telephone system to give us sprint communications co. more time to draft its proposal
the gsa said friday it had extended the deadline by a month to april 29 ``to insure the fullest possible competition'' for the contract, one of the biggest ever let by the government
besides sprint, only two other teams of companies are bidding on the project, the work for which will be split 60-40 between two vendors
the other bidders are a team led by american telephone &amp; telegraph co. and another headed by martin marietta corp. with mci communications corp
the environmental protection agency says ford motor co. is recalling 214,900 cars from the 1982 and 1983 model years because some of the vehicles have been exceeding federal emission standards
the company is notifying owners of 185,000 cars from 1983 equipped with the 1.6-liter four-cylinder engine to bring them in for adjustment of the exhaust air-injection systems. these cars were sold as the ford escort, escort exp and escort wagon and the mercury lynx, lynx ln-7 and lynx wagon
the agency said friday that ford also will recall 29,900 cars from the 1982 model year to fix an exhaust gas recirculation system which can cause excessive emissions of nitrogen oxides
the cars affected all have 2.3-liter four-cylinder engines and automatic transmissions. they were sold as the ford mustang, granada and fairmont and the mercury capri and zephyr. cars originally sold in california are not affected
dealers will check the carburetor spacer plates, which allows some exhaust to enter the intake manifold, and clean them of deposits if necessary
the marine corps has devised a new training policy that mandates tougher physical conditioning programs to make sure those who already have made it through basic training are ready for combat
a new training policy order, signed last week and now being prepared for distribution to the field, will require all commands to refocus their physical conditioning program so that it goes beyond just staying in shape to pass the standard physical fitness test
the directive says commanders must ensure their marines face ``a minimum program of three hours per week'' of exercises that can be divided between anaerobic conditioning, progressive resistance training and aerobic conditioning
it says that marine conditioning programs historically have focused on physical fitness and adds: ``the focus, therefore, of our programs must change. each commander must emphasize unit and combat fitness training, (instead of) physical fitness testing, and reflect this distinction in training plans and schedules.''
a proposal to conduct field tests in wisconsin for a genetically engineered bacterium designed to improve the ability of alfalfa to use nitrogen in the air as a fertilizer has won federal approval
the tests, approved friday by the environmental protection agency, will be conducted in pepin county, wis., a county lying on the mississippi river about 20 miles southwest of eau claire
the bacterium, rhizobium meliloti, grows naturally on alfalfa roots, and mutant forms have been used to enhance plant growth in the past
using the techniques of recombinant dna, biotechnica inc. of cambridge, mass. has reinserted the genes responsible for nitrogen use _ nitrogen fixation _ back into the organism, giving it two copies of the genes
lab and greenhouse tests indicate this will enhance alfalfa yield, according to an epa announcement when the company applied for permission to test 13 months ago
jesse jackson won the coveted top spot for new york's april 19 democratic presidential primary ballot as the result of a lottery draw at the state board of elections
board spokesman steven lafever said friday that the order of appearance on the ballot, after jackson, is expected to be tennessee sen. albert gore jr., massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, illinois sen. paul simon, an uncommitted slate, political extremist lyndon larouche and missouri rep. richard gephardt
larouche supporters have filed a challenge to simon's nominating petitions and the board is expected to rule on that challenge monday. after that, the ballot lineup is to be finalized
while the democratic candidates run state wide by name and thus have only one draw for ballot placement, republican candidates rely on delegate slates filed in each of the state's 34 congressional districts. that means there's a separate ballot spot draw in each congressional district for the gop delegate slates
jesse jackson probably won't be on the democratic ticket in 1988, but he should have some sort of ``inspirational role'' in a democratic administration, says former virginia gov. charles s. robb
robb said jackson would be best ``in some part of the greater domestic policy portion where he is simply without peer _ in motivating young people, in encouraging young people not to get involved with drugs, in encouraging people to pursue education,'' robb told the cleveland city club on friday
i think it's probably clear that if he is to have a role in the next administration, it ought to be a role that is principally an inspirational role and not a managerial role,'' he said
vice president george bush's quest for the gop presidential nomination picked up steam in new jersey as three top republicans in the state endorsed him
assembly speaker chuck hardwick and u.s. rep. james courter announced their support of bush in a press conference friday. hours later, u.s. rep. matthew rinaldo endorsed the vice president
at a news conference in trenton, hardwick urged gov. thomas h. kean to change his noncommittal stance while republican leaders asked the party to unite around bush
not only is it time for all republicans to unite behind george bush's candidacy, but that i hope gov. kean, as the leader of our party ... will endorse the vice president in the near future,'' said hardwick
ruth h. berry has been named press secretary for the 1988 democratic national convention committee
donald l. fowler, the committee's chief executive officer, and paul kirk, democratic national chairman, announced the appointment friday
berry previously served as national trip director for the sen. joseph biden's presidential campaign. she did advance work for both the 1976 carter-mondale presidential campaign and the white house press office under president carter
she was a producer for cable news network's election unit in 1983 and worked as an associate producer for special events for abc news in 1982
