two car bombs exploded in the capital's fashionable ``pink zone,'' sending diners diving for cover and running for safety and injuring at least two people, witnesses and officials said
no group claimed responsibility for the bombs that went off friday night in the affluent sector of san salvador
earlier in the day, about 400 union activists marched through the city to demand the release of a detained labor leader
the first bomb went off in front of flashback, a restaurant adjacent to two cafes where leftist guerrillas killed 13 people, including six americans, in a machine gun attack in june 1985
the second bomb exploded about five minutes later in a parking lot behind a pizza hut restaurant, causing no injuries
a red cross spokesman said two people _ a 12-year-old boy and a middle-aged man _ were wounded in front of flashback, one of a row of trendy restaurants and night clubs in the zona rosa
the boy was taken to bloom hospital for children. the spokesman, who refused to give his name, said the extent of the boy's injuries had not yet been determined, but that his life was not in danger
he said the man was treated at the red cross clinic for cuts to his hand, and released
glass shards littered the street in front of flashback
the remains of three cars in front of flashback were still smoldering an hour after the 9:30 p.m. blasts. the car that held the explosives was little more than a frame with some shreds of sheet metal. its make and year could not be immediately determined
the parking lot where the second blast occurred was nearly empty. the car that held the second bomb also was reduced to a twisted black metal skeleton. bomb squad members there said they had not determined what type of explosive was used
flashback was crowded with diners that spilled onto the restaurant's sidewalk tables when the blasts occurred
it was a powerful explosion. people dived for cover, then some jumped up and ran,''said porfirio valladares, a waiter at flashback
he said firefighters arrived in ``about 15 minutes'' and quickly put out the flaming cars
about 400 union activists marched had through the capital several hours earlier to demand that the salvadoran governent free humberto centeno, leader of the telecommunications workers union
one marcher was wounded by a gunshot to the leg when other protesters identified an undercover security agent in their ranks and confronted him. the agent fired a shot and fled
a pickup truck was set afire near the u.s. embassy, where the march stopped for 30 minutes to denounce u.s. support for the salvadoran government. protesters defaced a u.s. embassy wall
there were no confrontations with police or soldiers along the five-mile march route. uniformed security forces were not visible
centeno was arrested thursday night after about 50 union members occupied the labor ministry in demand of higher pay and reinstatement of fired workers
jesse jackson, stumping for votes on home turf in advance of tuesday's illinois democratic primary, says his presidential campaign is in its second phase _ a phase where people can view him as a winner
many of his supporters had hoped he would do well in other state contests but didn't really believe it would happen, jackson said friday night. but his campaign has been buoyed by strong finishes from the south to the midwest and north to alaska
so now we move into the second phase _ when you hope it and believe it. now, let's achieve it,'' jackson told a crowd of more than 1,000 cheering supporters who jammed a hotel ballroom for a $50-per-person fund raiser
jackson said he's finished first or second in 22 of 28 state political contests so far despite being outspent by his democratic opponents. he said his message is making believers of those who thought he could not win because he is black
don't judge the campaign by its budget,'' he told the crowd. ``judge it by its mission and its message.''
the message friday night included familiar themes: a campaign against drugs; emphasis on prenatal care and daycare for the young instead of ``jail care and welfare'' as they grow older; and a push for jobs
in illinois, polls show jackson's top opponents are sen. paul simon, another home state favorite, and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, the front-runner in delegates. jackson has refused to attack his party rivals
if i stop to hit them, i might break my stride,'' he said
and he said he has proven his ability to manage a tight budget
if my competitors had my budget, they could not survive. if i had their budget, they could surrender,'' jackson said
u.s. rep. mario biaggi could have helped wedtech corp. for free, but chose to help plunder millions of dollars from the bronx defense contractor, a prosecutor told jurors in the congressman's racketeering trial
the crime is not what the congressman did. the crime is that he was paid for what he did, the extortion and bribes,'' howard wilson, an assistant u.s. attorney, said friday in u.s. district court
wilson's opening statement to jurors hearing the case of biaggi and six co-defendants outlined how ``a little company in the bronx'' was turned into ``an enterprise that was to be plundered, to be used by the people on trial here.''
and in the end, because of the corruption, because of the greed, because of the lies, the company went kaput,'' he said
wedtech, formed in 1965 as a machine shop, capitalized on laws allocating government contracts for minority-owned enterprises, and by 1985 had grown into a defense contractor with 1,000 employees and $117 million in revenue
the company suspended operations and laid off most of its workers in december 1986, then filed for protection from creditors under chapter 11 of the bankruptcy act
the co-defendants are former bronx borough president stanley simon, 57; bernard g. ehrlich, 59, of bedford, biaggi's former law partner and a former major general in the new york national guard; biaggi's son, richard, 38, of fort lee, n.j.; peter neglia, 39, of armonk, the former regional administrator of the small business administration; former wedtech chairman john mariotta, 57, of scarsdale and ronald betso, 39, of brooklyn, a former policeman and friend of neglia's
all treated this company like a gold mine,'' said wilson
the defendants claimed that mariotta, who is hispanic, was the majority owner of wedtech, entitling the company to no-bid federal contracts, wilson said.but mariotta owned less than half, said the prosecutor
rep. biaggi, who at one point demanded 5 percent of wedtech's revenues, was given 5 percent of wedtech stock, which was put in his son's name, wilson said. the elder biaggi and ehrlich made $4 million from the 225,000 wedtech shares they received, he said
at another point, biaggi, 70, asked for $50,000 for expediting a lease before the city's board of estimate, the prosecutor said
simon demanded and received more than $50,000 in cash, meals, chips for gambling at atlantic city, n.j., casinos, marble for his home, a trip to rome and charitable contributions in his name, wilson said
simon also got a wedtech job for his brother-in-law and took half his raises over the years, wilson said
neglia was wedtech's ``paid-for friend,'' wilson said. among other things, wilson claimed, neglia warned the company about a congressional probe
neglia was paid with stock options, frequent meals, contributions to the republican party in his name and the promise of a job on leaving government, wilson said. less than a month after leaving office in early 1986, he went to work for the law firm of ehrlich and the younger biaggi
mariotta embezzled about $1 million and sold wedtech stock worth $6 million to $8 million, wilson said
ehrlich was ``mario biaggi's partner in the plunder of wedtech. when he got it, he split it,'' charged wilson, who said richard biaggi ``became the front man.''
wilson said the two men's law firm earned $1 million in retainers' fees from wedtech
betso took stock options in his name for his friend neglia, wilson alleged, then lied about it to the department of labor
wilson promised testimony to back up his claims from wedtech accountants, supervisors and workers; sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y.; and four former wedtech officials who pleaded guilty to crimes involving the company
defense attorneys begin presenting their arguments monday
the house ethics committee announced last month it would recommend biaggi be expelled following his conviction last year in another case on charges he accepted illegal paid vacations from an old friend and political ally
biaggi had asked the committee not to act until his appeal of that conviction was settled. the panel decided to postpone bringing the matter before the full house. sakharov</head>
a relative of andrei sakharov says he asked lyndon larouche's help in getting the dissident out of the soviet union but denied a claim by larouche attorneys that he was acting at the bidding of u.s. intelligence operatives
we came to him on our own initiative,'' efram yankelovich said in a telephone interview friday. ``nobody asked us or directed us or suggested it to us.''
yankelovich is married to the daughter of yelena bonner, sakharov's wife
larouche attorney michael reilly said yankelovich and alexei semyonov, sakharov's stepson, approached a larouche aide in 1984 and said a third party promised to spirit sakharov and bonner out of the soviet union if larouche paid $2 million
larouche refused to get involved and ended the discussions after the sakharov relatives identified the third party as a man the larouche organization believed was trying to entrap them, reilly said
attorneys for larouche, six aides and five organizations on trial here on fraud and conspiracy charges were denied access friday to classified fbi documents referring to an attempt to get sakharov and bonner out of the soviet union
the defense lawyers earlier this week were given declassified excerpts from the material. the excerpts say fbi files indicate that in 1984 two intelligence operatives approached two sakharov relatives and told them they could get sakharov and bonner out of the soviet union for $2 million
the operatives, gary howard and ron tucker, are quoted in the same fbi document as saying they and a third man, retired army sgt. maj. fred lewis, had been asked by the fbi and the cia to infiltrate larouche organizations
yankelovich said he never heard of tucker or howard
the larouche lawyers want the entire fbi file to help pursue leads they say show numerous attempts by government informants and operatives to entrap larouche
but u.s. district judge robert e. keeton said the file was properly classified and that the material not already given the defense lawyers was irrelevant
assistant u.s. attorney john markham said the file was created in the boston fbi office during an investigation of possible fraud against sakharov's relatives and possible violations of the neutrality act, which prohibits interference in foreign countries
tucker and howard, in a $1.4 million lawsuit against the government, describe themselves as longtime operatives involved in government sting operations
in the suit, tucker and howard said they gathered evidence against an arms merchant planning to sell weapons to iran but that the government refused to prosecute the case because it would have exposed the iran-contra scandal
a man aboard a pakistani airlines jet fired two shots and wounded a security guard today before being overpowered minutes before the aircraft was to land near the afghan border, officials said
karachi airport authorities said there were no other injuries among the 143 passengers and 13 crew members aboard the a-300 airbus. the jet, on a domestic flight from karachi to quetar, landed safely
the incident occurred as the jet prepared to land at quetta, a city near the afghanistan border in western pakistan
the man entered the cockpit with a revolver and two security guards tried to grab him, said the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity
a scuffle ensued in the first class cabin during which the man discharged his gun twice, wounding one of the guards, according to officials
they said the second guard managed to subdue the gunman
officials said the gunman has not been identified and his motive was unclear
pakistan's national news agency, app, reported that the gunman also was injured, but airport officials could not immediately confirm this
they could not explain either how the man was able to smuggle a firearm aboard the plane
airport security usually is extremely strict in pakistan. passengers pass through two metal detectors and have their carry-on luggage inspected at least three times before boarding a flight. pilot</head>
survivors of a commuter airliner crash that claimed nine lives expressed outrage at a government report that the pilot had traces of cocaine in his body
it makes me mad,'' said nancy hill of cortez, who suffered a broken leg and a dislocated shoulder in the jan. 19 continental express accident outside durango. ``we should have protection from this kind of thing.''
both the pilot and co-pilot died in the crash, and investigators have not determined which one was flying at the time
the eight survivors were rescued after one, peter schauer, trudged 1{ miles over a snowy mountainside to a house
our lives will never be the same, and when there is this kind of problem involved, you have to be even more angry,'' schauer said friday
the toxicology report released friday in washington said pilot steven s. silver had .022 micrograms per milliliter of benzoylecgonine, the principal metabolite of cocaine, in his bloodstream
he also had 1.8 micrograms per milliliter of metabolized cocaine and .022 micrograms of cocaine in his urine, according to the report by the national transportation safety board's bureau of technology
i would say that is a small amount'' of cocaine, said dr. merrit m. birky, an ntsb chemist who had an outside lab analyze the samples. ``it would be inappropriate for me to comment on the significance of this.''
birky said cocaine is quickly converted to benzoylecgonine in the bloodstream and has a half-life of seven hours in the body. but birky said he was unable to say how much cocaine the pilot ingested or when he ingested it
the ntsb did not characterize the finding as a cause of the accident or indicate whether the pilot might have been impaired
silver, 36, of denver was an employee of trans-colorado airlines inc. of colorado springs. trans-colorado leases planes and crews to rocky mountain airways, a continental airlines subsidiary that operates in colorado as continental express
the swearingen metro iii twin-engine turboprop crashed in a mountainous area in southwestern colorado after it was given clearance to land at durango-la plata county airport
the report said the toxicology report on co-pilot ralph harvey, 42, of denver will be released later
bill white, a denver attorney acting as trans-colorado's spokesman friday, said the company was ``obviously surprised. we're concerned.''
the air line pilots association said it was ``deeply disturbed'' by the report, but said it ``leaves unanswered more questions than it resolves.''
george james, president of airline economics inc., a washington consulting firm to the airline industry, said he was unaware of any other commercial airline accident in which drug use had been involved
the department of transportation on thursday proposed a drug testing program for more than a half million airline employees
in a statement friday, transportation secretary james burnley called the evidence of drug use by silver ``a tragic reminder that not even commercial aviation is exempt from the drug abuse problem which plagues our society.''
two passengers on a greyhound bus suffered gunshot wounds today when a bullet hit the vehicle as it rolled down a downtown highway, police said
the bullet apparently struck the bus near the middle of the vehicle around 1 a.m., hit the first victim's foot, then lodged in the second victim's leg, said police detective charles dudley
passengers sujal badami, 24, of clemson, s.c., and eric douglas, 21, of denmark, s.c., were treated at erlanger medical center and released, said hospital spokeswoman debbie goad
badami was wounded in the foot and douglas in the leg
the shooting on interstate 124 followed a similar case thursday, in which a truck driver was seriously wounded when two shots pierced his tractor-trailer on the interstate, police said
sam lands, hit in the chest and wrist, was in satisfactory condition today at erlanger, ms. goad said
the bus was hit as it headed for memphis, police said. the driver said he pulled over and flagged down a passing truck driver, who used his citizens band radio to call police
the bus driver said company policy prohibited him from giving his name
a drunken driver struck the bus a glancing blow while it was parked on the side of the interstate, police said. the driver, whose name was not released, was arrested, and was to be charged later today, police said
police have no suspects in either shooting, and could not say until ballistics tests were completed if they were related. it was not clear whether the shot that struck the bus was fired by a sniper or from a passing car
a 5-year-old died after his stepfather allegedly beat him with a tree limb, a belt and his hands because the boy couldn't recite the alphabet past ``g,'' authorities said
dwayne blocker, 24, was being held in the cook county jail today on $150,000 bond, said a jailer who refused to give her name. he is to be arraigned april 4
blocker, who was indicted on murder charges by a county grand jury friday, admitted beating stepson charles moss because he could only reach ``g'' when blocked asked him to say the alphabet, said police lt. james phelan
the boy's mother, joyce blocker, 21, was sick wednesday and blocker picked up charles from preschool, phelan said
after the child could not complete the alphabet, blocker shouted, ``do it again,'' the lieutenant said
then he punched him several times, hit him with a belt several times and then went outside and got a tree branch and struck him several more times,'' phelan said
after the attack, the boy ran upstairs to his mother's room, said david schneidman, a spokesman for the state department of children and family services
charles collapsed in the room, and the stepfather tried to revive him, schneidman said
the youngster, who died at st. francis cabrini hospital, had a broken arm, bruises on his leg and a solid bruise from the shoulder blade to his buttocks, schneidman said
when this guy said he became angry because the boy could not get past the letter g, that sounds absurd, ridiculous,'' he said. ``but frankly, reasons like that are very common among child abusers
in severe abuse cases, there are several things that can trigger an incident,'' said schneidman. ``the child's learning ability is one of the common reasons. others are eating habits and toilet training.''
another child from the family, 1-year-old jasmine blocker, was admitted to the hospital to check for potential abuse, schneidman said. the state has moved to gain temporary custody of her
only a very small number of people carrying the aids virus will fail to develop some form of the disease within six years, scientists predicted today
a study estimates that at least 75 percent of those with the virus will contract aids or aids-related complex in that period
the big question still is, `will everybody at some point progress (from the virus to aids) ... or is there a chance that some people will be able to ride it out for 15 years?''' said paul o'malley, author of an earlier study on the virus' progression
results of the study were published in today's editions of the british medical journal
the researchers at the university of california, san francisco and other institutions studied 288 men with the virus for three years,
the scientists used five ``markers'' in the blood to estimate how many would contract aids or arc, a milder form of acquired immune defiency syndrome which generally develops into active aids. the markers included measurements of proteins and cells
twenty-two percent of the participants developed aids during the three-year period and 19 percent progressed to arc. tests on another 24 percent showed abnormalities which the researchers found were highly predictive of aids or arc
although that adds up to 65 percent, the researchers extrapolated that at least another 10 percent of people infected with hiv, or human immunodefiency virus, will develop some form of the disease for a total of 75 percent
the scientists called the estimate conservative, saying the actual rate of progression may be much higher
even the men who had not developed aids or arc after three years showed clear signs of progression toward a worsened condition in their blood markers, the study found
hiv infection is much more serious than we thought in the early days,'' said andrew moss, ucsf associate professor of epidemiology and international health at san francisco general hospital. ``it may take eight or nine years, but eventually the infected person will probably get aids
what we saw was that the number of those showing no effects from hiv infection is very small,'' added moss. ``this means that if you are infected with the aids virus, you will almost certainly go on to get aids,'' he said
o'malley, the director of the city health department's aids research project, said the new study apparently provides important information for hiv-positive people trying to decide whether to take immediate risks with anti-viral drugs or await advances in treatment
as each year progresses we know more, but we still can't fully answer it,'' said o'malley. his study, released in february 1987, determined that the risk of developing aids increases in the second five years after infection
moss and his colleagues in the study are urging the expansion of current trials of antiviral drugs on people who are hiv positive, but do not have symptoms of arc or aids
we need to speed up the trials of the current drugs and look for more treatments as well,'' moss said
the national centers for disease control reported this week that 55,167 cases of aids have been reported since june 1981 and 30,932 of those people have died
a major blizzard continued blasting the northern plains today, packing winds of 30 to 50 mph that reduced visibility to near zero and piled up snow in drifts up to 10 feet high
a band of showers and thunderstorms spawned by the same storm system produced hail the size of golfballs in north-central texas. the rain extended across central arkansas and central illinois into southwest wisconsin and southeast minnesota
areas hit hard by the blizzard friday included northeast colorado, western and north-central nebraska, western south dakota and eastern wyoming. roads remain closed in many areas. bitterly cold wind chills of 10 to 25 below zero were common
blizzard warnings remained in effect today over much of the eastern dakotas and western minnesota
winter storm warnings or winter storm watches were up in sections of minnesota, wisconsin, iowa and michigan
on friday, snow was reported as deep as 31 inches, with snow drifts 5 feet deep in chadron, neb. drifts measured 10 feet in cody, although only 6 to 7 inches fell. snowshowers also lingered over the central rockies
strong winds over the northern plains included gusts to 69 mph at akron, colo. wind gusts over 50 mph were clocked at rapid city, s.d.; scottsbluff, neb.; limon, colo.; and duluth, minn
there were numerous reports of large hail across north-central texas friday night. hail the size of golfballs was reported in de soto and terrell. in arkansas, 1-inch hail fell at burg
today's forecast called for snow and strong winds from the dakotas and nebraska across the upper mississippi valley into upper michigan; strong winds in kansas and oklahoma; snowshowers lingering over the northern and central rockies and thunderstorms extending from alabama, mississippi and northwest georgia across the tennessee valley, the ohio valley and the middle mississippi valley, with rain reaching into southern wisconsin, lower michigan and the lower great lakes region
highs were expected in the 20s and 30s from the northern and central rockies across the northern two-thirds of the plains and the upper mississippi valley into upper michigan, upstate new york and northern new england; and the 70s and 80s from southern texas across the central gulf coast states and the southern atlantic coast states, with a few readings in the 70s across southern california and southwest arizona. the rest of the nation will have highs in the 40s, 50s or 60s
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 1 degree at yellowstone park, wyo., to 70 degrees at miami, key west, fla., and brownsville, texas
