the rev. jamie mock-robbins, an early leader in the sanctuary movement to aid central american refugees, died at age 32
mock-robbins, co-pastor of university baptist church, died on thursday. he had been battling cancer since october, the seattle times said
in 1982, under the direction of mock-robbins and the rev. donovan cook, university baptist became the first church in the pacific northwest to declare itself a sanctuary for refugees fleeing persecution in central america. about 50 refugees have been sheltered at the church
mock-robbins also spent much of the past four years in central america working with schools and churches. he organized relief in 1986 for victims of the san salvador earthquake, which left about 1,000 people dead and hundreds of thousands injured and homeless
i have never known anyone as loving and gentle and dedicated to living the gospel, and he demonstrated it daily, especially in work in central america,'' said cook
mock-robbins also attended and helped organize demonstrations and vigils in seattle to protest u.s. military intervention in central american countries
a native of dearborn, mich., mock-robbins was a graduate of albion college and andover-newton theological seminary in boston
he is survived by his wife, katherine mock-robbins; his parents from dearborn, mich., and a sister
a memorial service was scheduled for sunday at university baptist
richard croxton adams, who invented the paint roller to help america adapt to a world war ii shortage of brushes, died at the age of 76
adams, a descendant of presidents john adams and john quincy adams, suffered a stroke last week and died wednesday in grossmont hospital, said his wife, mary
an engineer, industrialist and civic leader, adams invented and held the first patent on the paint roller. he developed it in his basement workshop while working in the market research department of the sherwin-williams paint co. in 1940
the invention was spurred by a shortage of paint brushes caused by world war ii, then raging in europe
at the time of his death, adams was working with a group of southern california educators to establish a research center where academicians could study biological and sociological issues
in addition to his wife, adams is survived by three sons, a brother and eight grandchildren
a memorial service was scheduled for monday
iraq claimed today it raided an iranian oil tanker in the persian gulf, resuming a campaign to cut tehran's economic lifeline after the foes halted 12 days of missile attacks on each other's cities
the raid came amid reports from u.s. military sources in washington that iran has started building launch pads for silkworm anti-ship missiles on its abu musa island near the strait of hormuz, the narrow entrance at the gulf's southern end
the official iraqi news agency quoted a military spokesman as saying iraqi warplanes on friday night attacked a ``very large maritime target'' _ usually meaning an iranian oil tanker _ off the iranian coast, scoring ``an accurate and effective hit.''
the air raid was within the framework of iraq's firm and legitimate right in tearing the arteries of oil supplies of the iranian regime to deprive it of employing its oil revenues for the purposes of aggression,'' said the spokesman, who was not identified
the agency, monitored in nicosia, gave no other details, and the attack could not be immediately confirmed by independent shipping executives in the gulf. iran usually does not report attacks on its shipping
the ship raid occurred only hours after a truce went into effect to stop the unprecedented long-range missile duel in the ``war of the cities'' that had begun feb. 29
iraq fired eight rockets at tehran and three at the holy city of qom, south of tehran, friday afternoon just 16 minutes before baghdad said it would stop shooting
more than 400 ships of different nationalities have been damaged in the gulf since the iran-iraq war broke out in 1980. the ``tanker war'' began in early 1984
iraq on friday had claimed another a ship attack but that also could not be confirmed
iraq's last confirmed attack on a ship was on tuesday, when warplanes blasted a maltese-flag tanker shuttling iranian crude
that attack was preceded by a lull since feb. 12, the last time iraqi warplanes were confirmed to have hit a ship
defense officials in washington, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the iranians are building launching pads in abu musa. they added that u.s. intelligence had not yet detected efforts by iran to move any of its chinese-built silkworms to the island, which serves as base for revolutionary guards
iran has batteries of silkworms, which have a range of about 50 miles, on its shore along the strait of hormuz
it also has fired missiles believed to be silkworms into kuwait's main oil port from the faw peninsula, which it captured from iraq in 1986
steve mills, a vaudeville comic who began his show biz career at age 14 before world war i and continued performing until the late '70s, has died. he was 92
mills, who had been mostly confined to his home since a 1977 stroke, died wednesday at his home in this suburb south of providence
mills began his career when he played amateur night with fred allen and benny rubin in his hometown of boston. he then formed the castle trio with friends and broke into vaudeville in the boston area shortly before the war
after serving as an army bugler at fort devens, mass., in 1918, mills joined the major vaudeville and burlesque circuits
in 1924, he performed in billy gilbert's ``whiz bang babies'' and was lead comedian for the first time in 1926 in ``miss tabasco.'' in 1928, mills was ``top banana'' for billy minsky at the national winter garden theatre in new york
after signing with the shubert organization in the early 1930s, mills appeared in ``three little girls,'' ``no, no nannette'' and ``prince of pilsen.''
after burlesque closed down in new york in 1937, mills played new england nightclubs until 1944, when he rejoined shubert to perform in the operettas ``wildflower'' and ``firefly.''
he played ``a lady says yes'' in new york, then returned to new england clubs before buying his warwick home in 1947
in the 1960s and early 1970s, mills appeared on tv talk shows and performed with mildred natwick and hans conried in ``70 girls 70'' in new york, the ``best of burlesque'' show in las vegas, nev., and the ``minsky show'' in miami
he last appeared on stage in 1977 in the show ``this was burlesque,''
mills is survived by his wife, abagail, a daughter and four grandchildren
i got a fair hearing and the people decided.'' _ former colorado sen. gary hart, announcing his second withdrawal from the race for the democratic presidential nomination
if mike dukakis has 41 percent, get everybody together in a room and say, `jesse, gore, gephardt, you came close, but mike's the candidate. let's pick the guy who's ahead after california.'' _ new york gov. mario cuomo, urging the democratic presidential candidates to close ranks after the primaries
i have responded to this extraordinary social movement of deaf people, not to the demands of the students and protesters.'' _ elisabeth ann zinser, upon resigning as president of gallaudet university after a week of angry demands for a deaf president by students at the world's only liberal arts university for the deaf
a wildfire raged through west texas today after burning 200,000 acres of prarie, killing livestock, threatening homes and closing roads
no people were reported killed or seriously injured in the blaze, which an army of hundreds fought friday. officials said could take several days to extinguish the fire
it looked like we were in hell _ fire all around. pretty spooky,'' jimmy t. brooks, a 40-year-old cowboy, said here friday before going back to the battle
winds diminished from 30 mph to about 10 mph, helping firefighters bring parts of the blaze under control, said terry harlow of shackelford county's emergency management team
the fire destroyed a mobile home and several hunting sheds in the sparsely populated region about 150 miles west of dallas. the blaze also damaged oil field equipment and ranch fences
the fire covered an area about 60 miles long and 25 miles wide in portions of callahan, shackelford and throckmorton counties, officials said, and a 20-mile wide swath of the blaze burned out of control. a few families were evacuated from ranches, officials said
joe fox, the texas forest service official overseeing the firefighting effort, predicted it could take another four days to extinguish the blaze
albany, a town of about 2,500 people and the county seat of shackelford, was under siege friday. a change in wind direction brought the fire to within 100 yards of the town, said lawrence winkler, a spokesman for the shackelford county emergency division. but the wind died down
all four major highways through albany were closed by heavy smoke, officials said
smoke and haze also cast a light fog-like pall over the dallas-fort worth area late friday afternoon, and some fort worth residents said they smelled the smoke
gov. bill clements dispatched 100 national guard soldiers. they joined west texas fire departments, texas forest service firefighters, state highway department employees, units from abilene's dyess air force base and the fort worth fire department. winkler said volunteer oilfield workers also pitched in
some firefighters suffered minor burns and were temporarily overcome by smoke, officials said
at the 88-year-old nail ranch, an estimated 35,000 acres were scorched, an unknown number of cattle lost and 20-25 miles of fence destroyed, said ronnie nail, one of the ranch heirs
shifting winds made it difficult to determine where the fire would spread, and in some cases firefighters were nearly surrounded by the swiftly moving flames
one of the fires may have started when someone was burning tires near here, while two others appeared to have formed along farm road 604 and may have been caused by passing motorists
there was speculation that trash fires may have sparked the blazes thursday, when humidity dipped to 7 percent
spain told the united states it would give political asylum to panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega if it helps end that central american country's political crisis, a newspaper reported today
spain's leading daily, the independent el pais, quoted jose antonio yanez, as saying, ``spain, in a critical situation, would be prepared to receive noriega, if it can lead to a solution'' of the panamanian political situation
yanez is a top policy adviser to socialist prime minister felipe gonzalez. elena chi, consul at the panamanian embassy in madrid, told the associated press that noriega had no plans to seek asylum in spain
panamanian president eric arturo del valle was dismissed feb. 26, a day after he tried to fire noriega. as chief of the 15,000-strong defense forces, noriega is considered the real power behind the civilian government
despite delvalle's ouster by the noriega-dominated national assembly, the united states still considers delvalle panama's legitimate president
the united staets has frozen official panamanian government funds deposited in u.s. banks, creating a financial crisis in panama, whose currency is the u.s. dollar
el pais said yanez, who ended a three-day visit to washington friday, expressed spain's position in a one-hour meeting friday with elliot abrams, u.s. undersecretary of state for interamerican affairs
it said spain's offer was made on condition that the u.s. government not seek noriega's extradition from spain to face indictments in florida on charges of drug trafficking and money laundering. noriega has rejected the accusations
other conditions set by spain included that noriega himself request asylum in spain and that panama's political opposition agree to the move, the newspaper said
yanez, the paper said, also received a guarantee from the united states that it would respect the panama canal treaty of 1977 calling for the u.s. government to turn over control of the panama canal at the end of 1999
the paper also reported the united states delivered a message to noriega in which it promised the military leader the washington would not oppose his residence in a third country
gabriel lewis, a former panamanian ambassador to the united states now leading the opposition to noriega in washington, told el pais he appreciated spain's offer of asylum for noriega ``because his leaving would clear up the panamanian crisis.''
the newspaper also quoted panamanian defense forces spokesman maj. edgardo lopez as saying: ``once and for all: noriega is going to stay in panama and, if necessary, die in panama, but he will never accept a shameful exit.'' graf pvs ``waldheim attended...''; edits thereafter to tighten.</note>
protesters gathered outside the office of president kurt waldheim today to demand that he resign because of his world war ii past as an officer in the german army
a small group of demonstrators maintained an overnight vigil on the square in front of the president's office, and said they will remain until late sunday
the protesters fixed a 10-foot-long banner to a nearby fence that read, ``who will make waldheim resign.''
we know that this will not force him to resign,'' said one protester, who identified herself only as a 23-year-old student at vienna university
but hopefully it will help keep attention focused on him, and remind people what a problem he has become for our country,'' she added
the demonstrators were among 300 people protesting outside the imperial hofburg palace on friday, the 50th anniversary of austria's annexation by nazi germany
organizers said they expected thousands of people for an afternoon protest near the president's office in the center of the capital
waldheim attended several events marking the annexation, but the controversy forced him to drop plans to deliver a major address
austria's president normally is the keynote speaker for such events, but waldheim was the silent guest at several of the ceremonies and did not play a major role
waldheim concealed his role as a german army lieutenant in the balkans until it was disclosed in the media in march 1986, but he has said he will not leave office until his term expires in 1992
last year, the u.s. justice department placed the former u.n. secretary-general on a list of undesirable persons, effectively barring him from entering the country
a panel of historians concluded last month that waldheim was in close proximity to nazi war crimes, including the deportation to death camps of jews and the murders of partisans, but did nothing to prevent them
the report left open the question of waldheim's guilt or innocence in atrocities, fueling pressure that he resign
waldheim always has denied any wrongdoing
ceremonies friday marking anshluss drew few large crowds. shops, schools and businesses remained open, and many viennese ignored a nationwide moment of silence. some public transport stood still and the state-run radio fell silent during the observance
austria's largest-circulation daily, the tabloid neue kronen zeitung, gave the anniversary events scant coverage
chancellor franz vranitzky told a special cabinet session friday that the nazi invasion and annexation, or anschluss, mattered to austrian politics today
the events of 50 years ago pose relevant, fundamental questions about the essence of politics,'' vranitzky said. ``if one attempts to avoid them, they sooner or later return with greater emphasis.''
vranitzky, in a later address to 900 students in vienna's historic musikverein concert hall, urged young austrians not to ``make blanket accusations against an older generation or to reproach them'' for past mistakes
speaking friday at an evening service in vienna's landmark st. stephen's cathedral, roman catholic archbishop karl berg of salzburg called on austrians to recognize the mistakes of the past
austrians must ``recognize guilt, feel regret and ask for forgiveness,'' berg told the several thousand people gathered in the gothic cathedral
an inmate convicted of murdering two police officers claims he has satisfied his sentence of 20 years to life in prison because he ``died'' briefly during open-heart surgery
the heart and respiratory functions of jerry rosenberg, an inmate at the auburn correctional facility, stopped for about 90 seconds during surgery in syracuse's university hospital on dec. 5, 1986, said attorney richard baumgarten
rosenberg, a self-styled jailhouse lawyer, was denied parole wednesday for the fifth time since he became eligible for it in 1981. rosenberg claims the parole board has no jurisdiction over him because he had ``died,'' said baumgarten, a spokesman for rosenberg
baumgarten said he sent a letter to gov. mario m. cuomo requesting a pardon, and if it is denied, rosenberg will pursue the case in federal court
he cannot be forced to serve a second life sentence,'' he said
baumgarten said rosenberg has documentation to support his claim, but wouldn't say what it is
dan hurley, the syracuse hospital's communications director, said the state considers a person dead only after he is declared brain dead by two physicians, one of them a neurosurgeon or a neurologist
although he couldn't reveal rosenberg's files without his physician's approval, he said rosenberg's case ``certainly wasn't death as we know it.''
rosenberg was sentenced to death in february 1963 after he was convicted of killing two policemen during a robbery in brooklyn. the death sentence was reduced in 1965 to 20 years to life
rosenberg, who says he has earned three law degrees through correspondence courses, said he is not licensed as an attorney, but is recognized in state and federal courts as a legal representative in more than 250 cases. he said he has been accepting thousands of dollars in legal fees from inmates and others for 15 years
however, state department of correction officials last year found him guilty of illegally receiving $8,800 in fees from inmates and sentenced him to a four-year term in a special housing unit of the prison. they said he needed a license to collect fees
rosenberg may, however, represent inmates if he asks the permission of the prison superintendent and provides his services for free, according to state prison regulations
rosenberg could not be reached for comment because he is in solitary confinement. kaufman.</note>
