a man aboard a pakistan international airlines jet fired two shots and wounded a security guard today before being overpowered minutes before the aircraft landed near the afghan border, officials said
karachi airport authorities said there were no other injuries among the 143 passengers and 13 crew members aboard the a-300 airbus. the jet, on a domestic flight from karachi to quetta, landed safely
the incident occurred as the jet prepared to land at quetta, a city near the afghanistan border in western pakistan 375 miles north of karachi
the man entered the cockpit with a revolver and two security guards tried to grab him, said the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity
a scuffle ensued in the first class cabin during which the man discharged his gun twice, wounding one of the guards, according to officials
they said the second guard managed to subdue the gunman
officials said the gunman has not been identified and his motive was unclear
pakistan's national news agency, app, reported that the gunman also was injured, but airport officials could not immediately confirm this
they could not explain either how the man was able to smuggle a firearm aboard the plane
airport security usually is extremely strict in pakistan. passengers pass through two metal detectors and have their carry-on luggage inspected at least three times before boarding a flight
a shotgun fired from a passing car blew out a window of the chinese consulate in southwestern japan, the latest in a series of anti-chinese incidents
consul general guo chu and 15 other people were inside the building when the shooting occurred friday night, but no one was hurt, officials said
chief cabinet secretary keizo obuchi told a news conference today the incident was ``extremely unfortunate'' and expressed hope it would not hurt sino-japanese relations
japan's foreign ministry called in zhao zhongxin, counselor at the chinese embassy in tokyo, and expressed regret over the incident in the name of foreign minister sosuke uno
an unidentified person in a car fired a shotgun at the chinese consulate in fukuoka, 560 miles southwest of tokyo, at about 10:50 p.m., police said
the blast broke a window and damaged the ceiling and walls on the first floor of the three-story building, said takanobu kashiwagi, a fukuoka police spokesman
two nearby policemen guarding the building heard the shot and saw a car speed away, kashiwagi said
investigators found an abandoned car about a mile from the consulate this morning. kashiwagi said the car had been stolen in fukuoka two days earlier
relations between china and japan have deteriorated in recent years, with china criticizing japan over its increased military spending and angry over a japanese court decision awarding a disputed student dormitory in kyoto to taiwan
china says ownership of the dormitory, purchased by taiwan in 1952, should be transferred to china because of japan's switch of diplomatic relations from taipei to beijing in 1972
some japanese rightists have lashed out against the chinese criticism. since last june, at least five monuments in different parts of japan dedicated to sino-japanese friendship have been splattered with red paint. in september, a smoke bomb was hurled at a wall at the chinese consulate in osaka
an elderly couple who crashed to the dance floor during a vigorous quickstep ended up in the high court in london, where a judge said their testimony had put him off dancing for life
ballroom dancing is not normally a dangerous pastime. i'm terrified now _ i shall never go near a ballroom again,'' said the judge, sir leslie boreham, 70, as he threw the case out thursday
dance teacher edith spry, 72, had sought damages from 70-year-old jack plowright. she testified during a five-hour hearing that she asked plowright for a dance during a 1981 vacation on the spanish island of majorca
mrs. spry said plowright ``whirled me round like i had never been whirled round before,'' leaving her breathless, bruised and flat on her back on the dance floor
he was dancing at a terrific speed. i was quite frightened. . .. but before i could say anything i was on the floor,'' mrs. spry testified
mrs. spry sued plowright for unspecified damages, claiming he kicked her left leg and caused an ulcer when he fell on her. she blamed his fast-paced dancing on incorrect footwear _ plastic sandals
plowright denied dancing boisterously and said he overbalanced when his feet stopped during a turn. he said the floor was uneven
the judge decided that plowright did not dance with reckless abandon and dismissed the case
prince charles said a roaring avalanche that missed him in the swiss alps took only seconds to bury two skiing partners, killing one. he said his skiing party was aware of the dangers when they left the main trails
the hon. audrey lindsay, mother of the dead skier, maj. hugh lindsay, was quoted today by the british domestic news agency press association as telling a relative: ``i don't blame anybody. it was an unfortunate accident.''
looking distraught and wearing black, charles, his wife, princess diana, and sister-in-law, sarah, the duchess of york, returned home friday from switzerland
their plane, which landed at northolt air base near london, carried the coffin containing the body of the 34-year-old lindsay, a former aide to charles' mother, queen elizabeth ii, and a close friend of charles and diana
they were met at the base by lindsay's widow, sarah lindsay, who is expecting a baby in may. mrs. lindsay, a buckingham palace press officer, had helped answer questions about the avalanche before discovering her husband was killed in it
in a handwritten statement read to reporters at zurich airport after the royal party left for england, charles, the heir to the british throne, said:
all members of my party were skiing off the piste (the regular ski runs) at own our risk and we all accepted ... that mountains have to be treated with the greatest respect and not treated lightly,'' he said
he said that when the avalanche thursday at klosters, switzerland, started ``with a tremendous roaring'' he and three others in the group skied out its path. the other two, lindsay and patricia palmer-tomkinson could not evade the snow slide
to my horror, maj. hugh lindsay and mrs. palmer-tomkinson just failed to ski clear and were swept away in a whirling maelstrom as the whole mountainside seemed to hurtle past us to the valley below,'' the prince said. ``it was all over in a terrifying matter of seconds.''
charles described how he helped dig mrs. palmer-tomkinson out of the snow with a shovel and then with his hands. she broke both legs and is in a swiss hospital
the 39-year-old prince has been skiing for more than 15 years and knows the area well where the avalanche occurred. he was leading the ski party and press association quoted police at klosters as saying he personally asked thursday for the party to be allowed to ski on the perilous slopes where the avalanche later occurred
charles was praised for helping save the life of mrs. palmer-tomkinson. but some british newspapers called him foolhardy for taking on the dangerous haglamatte slopes of klosters
mrs. lindsay was at northolt to see six soldiers from her late husband's royal lancers regiment carry his flag-draped coffin from the red and white jet of the queen's flight
she left afterwards with her father while charles went to windsor castle 20 miles away to see the queen. diana and sarah left in another car for kensington palace in london
their movements for the weekend are private,'' buckingham palace said
lindsay's funeral is expected to take place at the royal military college at sandhurst on thursday, provided legal matters are settled in time, his regiment, the 9th@12th royal lancers said today. the service in the memorial chapel will be followed by a cremation
dennis day, a singer who served as comic foil for jack benny on television and radio shows, was hospitalized in critical condition today with a brain injury, an official said
he's showing signs of improvement day by day, and we're taking it day by day,'' publicist kitty davis said friday. ``he's showing signs of response.''
day, 71, a tenor known for his recordings of irish ballads such as ``danny boy,'' was diagnosed last july as having amyotropic lateral sclerosis, also known as lou gehrig's disease. the progressive nerve disorder causes a loss in muscle control
but day wasn't hospitalized until he fell and hit his head at his bel air-area home wednesday, said armen markarian, spokesman for st. john's hospital and health center
his condition was critical early today, and he remained under close observation, according to a nursing supervisor
day complained of a severe headache while he was being examined in the hospital emergency room early wednesday, markarian said. tests showed bleeding in the brain and he was taken to surgery, markarian said
he's been in critical condition since then,'' the spokesman added
day was born eugene denis mcnulty in new york city. his singing career began in 1939 as a naive kid with a golden voice on jack benny's radio show
one of his trademark lines was a sprightly ``gee, mr. benny!''
he recorded a number of songs, such as ``peg of my heart'' and ``clancy lowered the boom,'' and he also appeared in several films, including ``buck benny rides again,'' ``music in manhattan,'' ``one sunday afternoon'' and ``the girl next door.''
during a vacation in hawaii last year, day became aware of a muscle-control problem and returned to the scripps clinic in la jolla, where doctors diagnosed lou gehrig's disease
he was confined to a wheelchair during recent months, ms. davis said, but he made regular appearances at irish fairs and benefits for medical research
a train inspector who tampered with the breaks of a train because his relatives were refused seats has been sentenced to eight years in prison, china's official xinhua news agency said today
the report said a court in lanzhou, northwest china, found wang gang guilty of sabotage in dismantling six brake shoes on a passenger train traveling from urumqi to zhenzhou on jan. 18
it said wang, an inspector at yumen city in gansu province, became angered when he asked an attendant working on the train to find two berths for his relatives and was told there were no available seats
the faulty brakes were discovered after the train left the station. they were replaced at the next station, the report said
china has been plagued this year by disasters on its overcrowded railway system, with 34 people killed in a compartment fire, 19 killed in a head-on collision and 88 killed in a train derailment. all three accidents occurred in january
the head-on collision, in northeast china's heilongjiang province, was blamed on sabotage, although there have been no reported arrests
railways minister ding guangen resigned last week to take responsibility for the accidents
colossus, reputed to be the largest lowland gorilla in captivity, is moving from frosty new hampshire to a spacious new home in florida, where he'll get to enjoy the sunshine and perhaps a little romance
the 600-pound gorilla is to fly in a chartered dc-3 sunday from benson's animal park in hudson, n.h., to nearby pensacola. he'll then be trucked to the zoo, about 10 miles east of gulf breeze, said pat quinn, president and director of the park
colossus was captured as an infant 20 years ago in africa and has not seen another gorilla since then, but quinn said he hopes to introduce him to females of his species and breed him
we hope to socialize him so he will breed naturally with females,'' quinn said
the socialization process is to start by letting colossus see, smell and touch a male chimpanzee. then he would be introduced to another bachelor male gorilla or a infertile female, quinn said
an initial attempt at breeding may be through artificial insemination, and one potential recipient is koko, the signing, cat-loving gorilla owned by the gorilla foundation in woodside, calif
semen will be obtained from colossus before he is moved and then frozen
we are hoping to obtain some of that for use with koko because she is very anxious to become a mother,'' said penny patterson, director of the gorilla foundation
ms. patterson said 16-year-old koko's keepers know she wants to have a baby because she has told them so through sign language. that skill and her doting care of a pet kitten landed koko on the cover of national geographic magazine
all ball, so named by koko because it was a tailless manx, was hit by a truck and killed after the national geographic story, but koko was given a replacement kitten named smokey, now an adult cat still living with her
koko and a male gorilla, michael, communicate with sign language to express their feelings, ask for food and certain teachers and inquire about other animals
colossus' sperm may be used because captive gorillas sometimes develop incest taboos against cage mates, so michael would be unsuitable, ms. patterson said.another advantage is that colossus was captured in the wild as an infant and isn't inbred with zoo gorillas. comment. picks up 7th graf pvs, `the bodies...</note>
the bodies of three ira guerrillas killed by british troops in gibraltar will be flown to dublin monday on a chartered plane, the ira's political wing sinn fein said today
police said friday night they will move in to stop any ira paramilitary display at the funerals and asked the families for a public promise that there would be no such display. there was no immediate reaction from the families
last sunday's killing of the three unarmed irish republican army guerrillas sparked nighttime rioting in belfast much of the week. authorities have said the guerrillas were plotting a huge car bomb explosion in the british colony of gibraltar, on spain's southern tip
the irish government had complained that there was no attempt to arrest the guerrillas before they were shot
a sinn fein statement said spanish customs had refused ``to accommodate the return'' of the bodies of mairead farrell, 31, daniel mccann, 30, and sean savage, 24, on the first available scheduled flight to dublin
as a result, it said, the bodies will be put aboard a chartered plane which will fly directly from gibraltar to dublin, from where they will be taken to belfast, in the british province
spanish customs spokesman julio verdu in la linea de la concepcion, which borders gibraltar, said today ``it is absolutely false'' that the spanish government had refused entry into spain of the three bodies
verdu said health ministry officials had stayed on the job overtime friday night in case the families decided to transport the bodies to malaga
the bodies have been kept at the gibraltar royal naval hospital while attempts have been made to find a way to return them to ireland
the mainly roman catholic ira has been fighting to unite the predominantly protestant northern ireland with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic under socialist rule
no date has been set for the funerals, but sinn fein sources in belfast have been hinting they may be held next thursday, st. patrick's day
ira funerals in northern ireland have seen repeated violence as angry crowds clashed with police trying to stop paramilitary ira members from firing over the coffin
police say the ceremonial gunfire represents an illegal show of arms. but despite their presence in force, paramilitaries shielded by crowds of thousands often have managed to fire the traditional salute
more than 80 people were killed and hundreds were injured today when soccer fans were trampled in a stampede to get out of a hailstorm, eyewitnesses and hospital sources said
the storm pelted about 30,000 fans with hailstones during a match between a nepalese and bangladeshi team at the national stadium
fans rushed to stadium exits but found them locked, witnesses said
hospital sources confirmed 60 dead and more than 250 injured, many of them in critical condition. witnesses said there were more than 20 bodies left at the stadium that were not taken to hospitals
none of the athletes was involved in the stampede, they said
strong winds accompanied the storm, uprooting trees in katmandu valley, surrounding the capital
bill britt, the ``hermit of chestnut hill'' whose refusal to leave his makeshift home in the woods cost him his life, was remembered at his funeral as a colorful, articulate ``free spirit.''
fifty relatives and friends packed the funeral home friday to pay tribute to the garrulous, 52-year-old eccentric whose body was found monday in his lean-to at the chestnut hill cemetery. authorities said he had frozen to death about two weeks before
the funeral also attracted the media, and the room was lit up with television lights, a touch which britt's son said his father would have enjoyed
my father would have loved this. he's got all the cameras here,'' britton steven boughner, 30, said
but if his father loved attention, he also cherished independence. said his son: ``he was a free spirit and he (taught) me not to be afraid of anything or any individual.''
britt's daughter, ingrid boughner, 28, wept talking about the father who was reunited with two of his three children only a year ago
my father never really was a hermit,'' she said. ``he was a naturalist. ... he was the most colorful and articulate human being.''
britt's friend of two decades, birth control activist bill baird, recalled britt's ``passion for freedom, independence and the beauty of the woods.''
also at the service were britt's mother, marion, 86, his two brothers, and close friends like sophie ``bubbles'' haggett. ms. haggett spoke to britt daily by telephone from her home in malden and would bring him soup and clothing. britt died while the 70-year-old woman was laid up in the hospital
britt's body was cremated. his ashes were to be scattered today in the woods where he had lived
britt was once an ordinary married man with three children and a job in an office. all that changed after a painful divorce in 1969
soon he cast off his three-piece suits and his three-piece name, britton william boughner. he began to retreat to the woods at the state-owned chestnut hill reservoir, near the affluent suburb of the same name where he was born
but the ``hermit of chestnut hill'' was hardly a recluse. he was shrewd, witty and stubborn, given freely to tears. he would ride the trolleys and hunt for pay phones to call reporters, clad in cast-off clothing and dragging an armful of plastic buckets
bear-shaped and nearly toothless, britt had blind eyes swollen with infection. he refused welfare and lived on the nickels he got for empty bottles and cans
two years ago, officials began trying to force britt to leave the state land
britt fought back. he showed the world a misunderstood hermit who wanted only to be left among the trees. it landed him on ``late night with david letterman.'' actor mickey rooney suggested a tv movie about his life
a sympathetic judge respected britt's wish for a suburban eden and ordered the state to find a suitable alternative site
britt refused them all. but last july, he was finally ejected from state land and moved to the adjacent cemetery
the chicago sun-times editorial board says the newspaper will endorse vice president george bush for the republican presidential nomination and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis as the best choice for democrats
the board, in a statement released before formal editorial endorsements are published sunday, praised bush's ``variety and texture of public experience'' and said dukakis would give his party the best chance of regaining the white house
the rival chicago tribune on friday endorsed sen. robert dole for the gop nomination but has taken no stand on the democratic race in tuesday's primary. the tribune said dole has at times been ``the lone republican voice of reason and good sense on matters of budget and foreign affairs.''
we urge illinois republicans to give enthusiastic validation to the bush candidacy,'' the sun-times editorial board said in a statement issued friday
the editors cited bush's past experience as a congressman, cia director, united nations ambassador, national party chairman as well as his current position as vice president
rarely has a presidential candidate offered the variety and texture of public experience that mr. bush represents,'' the editorial board said
mr. bush has more inside knowledge of the workings of more aspects of government than all but a few candidates in two centuries,'' the newspaper's editors said
we have supreme confidence in mr. bush's understanding of international affairs and his capability for stewardship in guiding the united states through the mine fields of world politics,'' the editors said
in their democratic endorsement, the editors said, ``on balance, we consider governor dukakis the best democratic choice to grapple with and attempt to master the awesome powers of the presidency.''
there is no question _ no question at all _ of mr. dukakis' skills, talent, fiscal prudence and sound instincts administering a large bureaucracy,'' the newspaper's editorial board said
we also believe he represents the party's strongest contender to regain the white house.'' resignations. picks up 5th graf pvs,, `troops were ...'</note>
israeli soldiers shot and wounded a palestinian who threw a hand grenade, and prison officials opened fire on protesters who pelted their bus with stones, wounding one woman, the army command said today
bethlehem's mayor elias freij told the associated press about 300 palestinian policemen have handed in their resignations, including all 50 officers in bethlehem
an army spokesman said the hand grenade did not explode. soldiers chased the assailant and shot him in the back. he was taken to hadassah hospital in jerusalem, but a hospital official said he had no details about the man's condition
the incident took place friday evening in the village of bani naim, near hebron in the occupied west bank. it was the second time palestinians have thrown hand grenades at israeli troops since violence broke out three months ago
today, prison service employees opened fire on protesters who pelted their bus with stones and broke several windows in the west bank village of nur el-shams, the army spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity
a 50-year-old woman was wounded and taken to a hospital, the spokesman said
in bethlehem, soldiers dispersed two demonstrations and arrested several protesters who threw stones and empty bottles at the local police station
freij said the resignation of the local police ``would make things very difficult. there was a theft in town about a week ago. our policemen found the thieves and put them in jail within 12 hours. who will do this now?''
freij said all the police in ramallah and jericho resigned. the arab-run palestine press service said 68 policemen in hebron also quit. the resignations go into effect monday, freij said
on friday, the army barred palestinian worshipers from three mosques in gaza city on the moslem holy day in an attempt to maintain order. israeli soldiers wounded nine worshipers after services in the west bank and gaza strip
troops razed four palestinian homes to punish suspects in the attempted lynching of a collaborator and the knifing of a jewish settler
prime minister yitzhak shamir attacked the latest u.s. peace plan and said it was formulated to please the arabs. the plo has also rejected the plan because it did not provide for direct palestinian representation at negotiations
troops were posted friday around al amari mosque in gaza and barbed wire blocked the street to keep out worshipers. gaza's main mosque draws about 2,500 faithful, and local residents said it was the first time it was closed
two other mosques in gaza city also were shut by the army to prevent demonstrations, which have become routine on fridays since violence broke out dec. 8 in the territories seized by israel in the 1967 middle east war
israeli bullets or beatings have killed 87 palestinians in anti-occupation rioting
the army turned journalists away from nablus and hebron but the clampdown was not as widespread as the previous friday, when nearly all the west bank was closed to coverage
in beit ummar, 10 miles south of jerusalem, troops shot and wounded eight palestinians, two of them seriously, hospital officials at beit jallah and mukassed said
soldiers fired tear gas canisters to disperse protesters outside the beit ummar mosque. witnesses said at one point troops entered the building to broadcast a message over the loudspeaker ordering protesters to go home
the soldiers entered the mosque while we were still kneeling barefoot on our prayer rugs. people started shouting allahu akbar,'' or ``god is great,'' said youssef hassan khalil, 30, who lay on a cot in mukassed hospital with a wounded right ankle
in jabaliya refugee camp near gaza city, soldiers fired on demonstrators outside a mosque, wounding one palestinian in the leg, officials at shifa hospital said
israeli troops destroyed one palestinian home in hebron and three in biddya village, 30 miles west of jerusalem
the army command said the homes in biddya belonged to families of three residents who led a lynching attempt march 5 against a man suspected of collaborating with israel
shamir broke his silence two days before flying to washington and criticized the peace initiative proposed by secretary of state george p. shultz
the only word i agree with in the u.s. plan is the name shultz,'' shamir was quoted as saying in an interview with the daily haaretz
the plo has said that it would not agree to indirect representation through a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation as suggested in the shultz plan
an american farmer who was held prisoner 54 days in nicaragua has received a polite welcome back in that nation, but cannot return to his farm in costa rica, according to a published report
james denby, who was shot down over nicaragua on dec. 6, has returned to managua to retrieve his damaged private plane and review his legal status there, the st. louis post-dispatch reported
although he was accused of being a spy and cia informant while being held by the sandinistas, he has become something of a celebrity upon his return to managua, the newspaper said. nicaraguan soldiers reportedly have been seen asking for his autograph
i didn't know i'd done anything to become a public personality,'' denby told the newspaper thursday. ``i've been a little amazed. it seems unusual for a soldier to come up to me and ask for an autograph after being in prison for two months.''
denby, of carlinville, ill., was freed jan. 31 after bill press, a democrat running for the u.s. senate from california, persuaded the nicaraguan government to release denby before a congressional vote on aid to the contra rebels
after his release, denby delivered a message in washington d.c. against contra aid, although the lifelong republican later said he had supported the contras while farming in central america
denby said he returned to managua to get documentation that the nicaraguan government no longer has any charges against him, and expects to receive it
but he told the newspaper he still has some problems to solve, including settling a bill for $3,000 from the nicaraguan government for towing his cessna 172 from the costa rican border, where it was shot down
ironically, denby was refused entry to costa rica when he tried to return to his farm, and costa rican officials told him they had not been notified of any change in his legal status by nicaragua
in fact, i got deported to panama right when things got bad with (panamanian military strongman manuel antonio) noriega,'' denby told the newspaper. ``i didn't think that was the proper place to be.''
as a result, denby is staying on in nicaragua
the chicago sun-times editorial board says the newspaper will endorse vice president george bush for the republican presidential nomination and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis as the best choice for democrats
the board, in a statement released before formal editorial endorsements are published sunday, praised bush's ``variety and texture of public experience'' and said dukakis would give his party the best chance of regaining the white house
