the european space agency fired its first ariane 3 rocket into space this year in a flawless launch that carried two telecommunications satellites _ one american and one french _ into orbit
officials called the launch friday night of the west's only active commercial satellite launcher ``a complete success,'' with all operations perfect. it was ariane's 21st launching and the first of eight planned for this year
the ariane 3 placed into orbit france's telecom 1c and the american spacenet iiir-geostar, which includes facilities for the associated press
technicians said the two satellites, placed into orbit by ariane above the equator, obtained an altitude of 22,554 miles
the critical day for the spacenet satellite is wednesday, when its own motor ignites to place it into its definitive orbit 87 degrees west above the equator
liftoff from the space agency's jungle base on the northern coast of south america came at 8:28 p.m. local time (6:28 p.m. est)
the third-stage engine, at fault in three of ariane's four failed launchings, ignited normally four minutes after blastoff, officials said. twenty minutes after blastoff, the rocket separated from its payload, thrusting the two satellites into geostationary transfer orbits
frederic d'allest, president of arianespace, the european space agency's commercial arm, immediately announced plans for launches on may 11 and at the end of may. one would be a demonstration of the more powerful ariane 4 rocket, described by esa as ``the new generation of the european launcher.''
this success enables us to envision the ambitious program of eight launches a year,'' d'allest said after the launch. ``for that, vigilance and rigorousness are needed.''
some experts estimate the commercial space market will be worth more than $1 billion per year after 1991
including friday's payload, arianespace has 43 satellites on its order books worth $2.36 billion, according to the company
to keep up with the orders, the kourou space center has made two launch pads available
the launch friday was first scheduled for december but was delayed for extra tests after abnormalities were detected in the oxygen and liquid hydrogen third-stage engine
we preferred to take the time to understand the problem,'' said d'allest
third-stage engine failure was the cause of failed ariane launches in september 1982, september 1985 and may 1986. the last failure, the 18th launch, left the rocket grounded for more than a year
another failed launch occurred in may 1980 because of a problem with the first-stage engine
the 21st launch thrust into orbit the american gte spacenet corp.'s fifth satellite, spacenet iii r-geostar r01. the satellite is aimed at increasing the company's telecommunications services in the united states and helping set up a system of satellite communication with mobile units such as trucks, cars and trains
the satellite, with an expected lifetime of 10 years, weighed 2,674 pounds before liftoff and 1,562 pounds in orbit
gte spacenet lost a satellite in the 1985 failed launch
two transponders on spacenet iii purchased by the ap are to provide the new york-based news cooperative with domestic satellite delivery services over the next 10 years. a satellite being used is nearing the end of its operational service
the french telecom ic, the third in a series of satellites owned by france telecom, the state-owned telecommunications system. it is to replace telecom 1-b, which broke down jan. 15
with the u.s. space shuttle grounded and america's titan 4 and delta rockets not yet competitive, ariane remains the only active launcher for commercial satellites in the west. dakota reopened.</note>
a major blizzard continued its slow march east across the northern plains today, stranding travelers and schoolchildren, forcing authorities to close interstate highways and causing scores of minor accidents
snow combined with winds of 30 to 50 mph produced limited visibility and drifts up to 10 feet deep from northeast colorado and southeast wyoming into northern and western minnesota
there's zero visibility. we're just advising people not to travel right now,'' said polk county, minn., sheriff's dispatcher bob janorschke
conditions were so bad by 9 p.m. friday that even snow plows were pulled off roads in parts of minnesota, the state transportation department said
wyoming state offices were closed friday, although the legislature met. north dakota capitol workers were sent home about an hour after they arrived
blizzard warnings remained in effect today for much of the eastern dakotas and western minnesota, and winter storm warnings or winter storm watches were issued for sections of minnesota, wisconsin, iowa and michigan
in chadron, neb., 31 inches of snow fell, with snow drifts 5 feet deep. up to 40 inches of snow fell in two days in the mountains of utah at the alta ski resort, with 37 inches at snowbird. three to 4 feet fell around lead and deadwood on the edges of south dakota's black hills. visibility in many areas was down to zero
in western nebraska, school bus driver linda barret and her 13 riders took refuge thursday at a farm some 20 miles from harrisburg when the storm cut visibility, and bus driver sharon grubbs and her eight riders, ages 7 to 13, wound up at a farm 17 miles from the town
it looks as if the children will be snowed in at least until this morning,'' mrs. barrett said friday night
power has been out at the second farm, owned by jack and karen holt, since late thursday, cutting off the heat
you can see your breath in the house,'' said one of the stranded youngsters, 14-year-old jeff rundell
ms. grubbs said the house was holding the heat to about 40 degrees
in the nebraska panhandle, kimball civil defense director dan jenson estimated 600 stranded travelers spent friday night in the town of 3,800 residents. many stayed with townspeople, jenson said
outside scottsbluff, neb., jim and elizabeth davis of hot springs, wyo., spent about 15 hours stuck in their car before being rescued friday. davis, 68, said he and his 67-year-old wife had apples and candy, plenty of blankets and a full gas tank
winds gusting to 69 mph were reported friday at akron, colo., and to 67 mph at fort morgan, colo., while gusts over 50 mph were clocked at rapid city, s.d.; scottsbluff, neb.; and duluth, minn
the wind blew off a 20-by-30 foot section of roof at a rapid city hotel, and it landed on three cars. no one was hurt
the weather threatened thousands of newborn calves, and ranchers in the nebraska sandhills region worked around the clock to get animals to shelter
we had 300 calves born yesterday. we're dragging them in, separating them from their mothers,'' said marianne beel
the storm could cause severe losses to south dakota's cattle industry. dick kjerstad, chairman of the state beef checkoff campaign committee said friday
interstate 80 was closed for more than 300 miles, from walcott, wyo., to big springs, neb., because of snowdrifts and low visibility. almost 140 miles of interstate 25 were closed in wyoming, more than 200 miles of interstate 90 in south dakota, and parts of interstates 25 and 70 in colorado. a 200-mile section of i-94 in north dakota, closed friday afternoon, was reopened this morning. servitude</head>
border guards rescued 88 men, women and children from traffickers who were trying to smuggle them out for prostitution and indentured servitude abroad, officials and newspapers said saturday
young girls were lured away from school by women who told them their mothers were ill and offered to take them home, the government-owned dainik bangla and other newspapers reported
a senior police official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said hundreds of women had been smuggled across the border in recent years
most of these women land up in brothels, either in india or in pakistan,'' he said
in some cases, people have paid smugglers who promised them an escape from bangladesh's grinding poverty, according to newspapers. the smugglers, known as ``manpower agents,'' promise jobs as servants and manual laborers in prosperous middle eastern nations
often the victims end up as nothing more than slaves in households or on farms
maj. noor, a battalion commander of the bangladesh rifles border guards, said a new alert was declared monday at the border between bangladesh and the indian state of west bengal in an effort to stop the smuggling
we have recovered at least 80 women and children and some accompanying men since the latest crackdown started on march 7,'' noor said when contacted by telephone at border town of rajshahi
he said the group included 28 women, 31 children and 29 men
dhaka newspapers said 200 women and children had been rescued from the smugglers and 15 men had been charged with human trafficking since jan. 1
the latest reported interception occurred friday when six women, 16 men and one child were caught in the border towns of sahebnagar and bidirpur, the dainik bangla and daily itefaq newspapers said. two of the men were arrested on charges of trafficking in human lives
by piecing together sketchy reports in dhaka newspapers the past three days, a picture emerges of how the traffickers operate:
eleven-year-old najma akthar was playing with friends at their schoolyard last week in munshiganj, just outside dhaka, when a middle-aged woman approached her
the woman said najma's mother was seriously ill. puzzled and worried, the sixth-grader left the playground with the woman in a rickshaw
three days later, she and eight women who also had been lured away on false pretenses were in bidirpur, 90 miles northwest of dhaka. border police rescued them before they could be taken across the frontier
others paid for what they thought would be passports to better lives
bangladesh, with 105 million people, is one of the world's most densely populated nations. the per capital annual income is about $150
i sold my jewelry to pay the man who promised me a job in pakistan,'' dainik bangla quoted josna rani sarkar as saying
the 25-year-old woman, whose husband had deserted her, was one of those found by border guards this week
mrs. sarkar and other women were quoted as saying they paid between $100 and $200 for the journey
a foreign ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the government was investigating local press reports that at least 10,000 bangladeshis had been jailed abroad for using false passports and other papers
the dainik bangla, a bengali-language newspaper, said last october that police suspect some children have been smuggled out of bangladesh for more macabre purposes
the newspaper said there were unconfirmed reports that children had been taken across the indian border to west bengal and killed so their skeletons could be sold for medical studies
bangladeshi officials have declined to comment on this report
similar reports of indian children being killed in 1984 surfaced in the indian state of bihar. headless bodies were found in a river, and a box of children's skulls was later discovered at a railway station in patna, bihar's capital
platoon,'' the critically acclaimed film about america's moral anguish and loss of innocence on vietnam's battlefields, has been drawing tens of thousands of vietnamese viewers, according to the official vietnam news agency
people have been flocking to watch the film on video in ho chi minh city, formerly saigon, said a vna report seen in bangkok on saturday
the agency said ``platoon'' was the first u.s. film about the vietnam war to be screened in ho chi minh city since the communist victory over u.s.-backed south vietnam in april 1975
the brief report noted that the film was directed by oliver stone, who had fought in vietnam, and that it received academy awards in 1987
falling off horses, plummeting oceanward in a tangled parachute or fleeing an avalanche on a ski slope, prince charles maintains an old royal tradition of thrills and spills
the royal pratfall had become enshrined as a national joke until thursday, when charles narrowly escaped an avalanche that killed his close friend, maj. hugh lindsay, on a swiss ski slope
british hearts missed a beat realizing how close the avalanche had come to claiming the 39-year-old heir to the throne. ``it is only when you nearly lose someone that you become fully conscious of how much you value them,'' commented novelist a.n. wilson in the daily mail
inevitably, a cry went up for the royals to stop playing daredevil. but at the same time britons have come to expect it of them, judging by the derision charles's youngest brother edward has suffered in some quarters for shunning rugby and quitting the royal marines prematurely
zooming down the slopes with charles at the swiss resort of klosters were his wife, princess diana, and sister-in-law sarah, the duchess of york
on the morning of the avalanche, sarah, 28 and four months pregnant, tumbled into a river while skiing. that probably was the only reason she and diana stayed in their chalet and were not on the slopes when the avalanche broke loose
sarah's husband prince andrew, charles's other brother, was off the portuguese coast aboard the navy ship on which he serves as a helicopter warfare instructor. a few hours after the avalanche, the vessel lost a helicopter and two crewmen at sea
andrew flew combat missions in the 1982 falkland islands war, and few suggested he shouldn't. risking one's life for the public good is a tradition set in stone by king george vi, when he refused to flee london during hitler's blitz
charles's sister, anne, races horses and sometimes falls off them. his father, prince philip, was a polo player and took a well-photographed spill in a carriage-driving race. his mother, queen elizabeth ii, also is an accomplished, though more sedate, equestrian
anne's husband, capt. mark phillips, has suffered a few riding spills. he is also a repeat offender at the wheel, and recently was fined for clocking more than 100 mph on a 70-mph highway
on the outer fringes of royalty, risky sports and high-speed driving are routine. in 1972, prince william of gloucester, a cousin of the queen, was killed flying in an air race
charles has taken innumerable knocks on the sportsfields. he has a small facial scar from a fall playing polo, and in florida he collapsed dehydrated during a match
on his first ski run he pitched headfirst into snow. flying a light plane he came within seconds of a midair collision
his first parachute jump in 1971 came equally close to disaster. his foot snarled in the cords and he plunged thousands of feet upside down before righting himself and ending up in the ocean
charles's biographer, anthony holden, notes that the prince's grand-uncle, edward viii, was forced by his father to give up steeplechasing in the 1930s, but says it's unlikely the same will happen to charles
we cannot legislate about whether the prince of wales goes skiing or not,'' he told a bbc interviewer
it's in his character. he feels a need to prove himself physically.''
in charles, royalty-watchers see the dilemma of a vigorous man in the prime of life, well-aware of his privileged status and feeling forever compelled to justify it
forced to stay out of politics, the endearingly jug-eared prince is limited to speaking out on issues like modern architecture and the plight of britain's inner cities
he can only hint at his state of mind through remarks to friends that reach the media second-hand. the picture that emerges is of a man searching for a role, fearful of becoming a museum piece
his mother, at 61, shows no sign of giving up the throne, and chances are he won't be king before he is in his fifties
he is exasperated at being labeled an eccentric because he is interested in alternative medicine, communes in solitude with nature and once let on that he talks to his plants
his reverence for nature permeated the elegant, passionate statement he issued after the avalanche
he spoke of mountains needing to be ``treated with the greatest respect,'' and of the avalanche as ``a whirling maelstrom as the whole mountainside seemed to hurtle past us into the valley below.''
the times of london, weighing the calls for the prince to stop taking risks, concluded saturday that he should carry on regardless
should we become a nation whose competitive sporting instincts were restricted to the chess board or the ping-pong table, we would flourish neither in peace nor war,'' it said, ``and a great many brave spirits would be stifled.''
the death of vietnamese premier pham hung has given a natural prod to recent leadership changes that have brought western-style economic reforms to vietnam
hung, 75 and the no. 2 man in the communist party hierarchy, died of a heart attack in southern vietnam on thursday
hung was among the last of the ``old guard,'' a group that joined the revolution at its start but which saw its influence dwindle as the party left the battlefields to confront the challenge of economic development
over six decades, he played key roles in ousting the french, japanese and americans from vietnam. but he also helped forge the orthodox postwar policies the party now blames for vietnam's economic and social ruin
when hung became premier in june 1987, western diplomats saw him as a ``transitional figure'' selected to ease the break with the past and usher the way for technocrats more clearly identified with reforms
the choice of vo van kiet, a vice premier and chairman of the state planning commission, as acting premier should give impetus to the reform program
western analysts regard kiet and party general secretary nguyen van linh as the country's leading proponents of reforms based on material incentives, decentralized decision-making and limited free enterprise
the two championed such reforms years before they were declared the no. 1 priority at the sixth national party congress in december 1986
related reforms have included an easing of restrictions on the media, attempts to open vietnam to the west and reconciliation with former south vietnamese officials and other groups once considered enemies of the regime
other deaths have accelerated vietnam's recent changes
in july 1986, party leader le duan, a hardliner, passed away. several months later, at the december congress, the new party chief, truong chinh, relinquished his party post along with two other party co-founders, pham van dong and le duc tho
linh was chosen party general secretary and other pragmatists including kiet moved up the ranks of the politburo, the most powerful party group. in all, six of 13 politburo members were dropped at the congress
in june 1987, dong resigned the premiership he had held since 1955 and chinh resigned as vietnam's president. that removed from the top ranks the last of the party co-founders, an enduring clique comparable to russia's bolshevik or china's ``long march'' generations
in addition, a total of 17 ministers were sacked in major government reshuffles in june 1986 and february 1987, and the politburo has ordered a purge of corrupt and inefficient lower-level party and government officials to last until the end of this year
among western diplomats, hung had a reputation as a conservative hardliner, largely because from 1980 to february 1987, he held the powerful post of interior minister, which deals with internal security
he shared many common experiences with other top officials who emerged from the april 1975 communist victory bitter and defiant
hung joined the revolution at the age of 16. the french arrested him in 1931 and banished him to a decade and a half of hard labor at the notorious prison island of poulo condore. from 1945 until the french defeat at dien bien phu in 1954, hung held key party posts in southern vietnam
he assumed a high profile in defeating the south vietnam government and its american allies, who had replaced the french. hung was secretary of the south vietnam commission of the party's central committee and political commissar of the south vietnam liberation armed forces, or the viet cong
in 1975, he served as political commissar of the ho chi minh campaign, the final north vietnamese offensive which climaxed with the capture of saigon on april 30
a tatar leader scoffed saturday at a government overture to members of the disgruntled ethnic group and called a plan to allow some tatars to return to their crimean homeland a campaign to deceive the public
reshat dzhemilev, who was jailed for three years because he once asked saudi arabia to aid the cause of his people, said moscow's move would affect only a small number of his people _ and only those who toe the communist party line
it's a campaign to deceive the public, to create the appearance of action,'' dzhemilev said in a telephone interview
the tatars were deported in 1944 from crimea, a peninsula in the ukrainian republic that extends into the black sea
a government official told a commission in the central asian republic of uzbekistan on march 5 that crimean tatars who are ``the most virtuous and well-proven in work and social life'' would be allowed to return to crimea, the newspaper pravda vostoka reported
the newspaper, in its march 6 edition, said the state labor committee would decide which crimean tatars are eligible for resettlement on the basis of recommendations from labor collectives, and commissions of crimean tatars
dzhemilev said he did not believe the crimean tatars who attended the commission meeting in the uzbek capital of tashkent faithfully expressed the wishes of most of his people
pravda vostok said the commission was made up of republic-level representatives of crimean tatars and that the meeting also was attended by officials of regional commissions
two hundred families maybe will be allowed to move there, but that will not solve the problem,'' said dzhemilev, a leader in the crimean tatar effort who lives in tashkent but spoke during a visit to moscow. ``it's just supposed to distract attention.''
the newspaper indicated that the crimean tatars would be allowed to resettle ``as conditions are created'' primarily in steppe regions of the crimea. it hinted that resettlement will be limited in the areas on the black sea that have become popular resorts
the crimean tatars, who number from 250,000 to 350,000, are among the more than 100 national groups in the soviet union. soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has said that ensuring national unity while granting ethnic groups cultural and linguistic rights is ``the most vital, fundamental issue of our society.''
the crimean tatars have been fighting for the right to return to their ancestral homeland ever since they were driven away. in may 1944, soon after soviet troops liberated the crimea from nazi germany, all the crimean tatars were charged with betraying their country and forcibly deported
they were shipped in sealed freight cars to the eastern regions of the soviet union, with most winding up in reservations in uzbekistan, kazakhstan, turkmenia and kirgizia. thousands died during deportation
the war crimes charges leveled against them were dropped in 1967 but the tatars were not allowed to return permanently to the crimea
the crimean tatars stage demonstrations regularly to press their cause, the most recent being a rally march 5 outside a moscow hotel. police broke up the protest and detained 15 of the 20 demonstrators, dissidents reported
the government set up a national commission headed by president andrei a. gromyko to consider the crimean tatars' demands, and on feb. 3 it endorsed steps to promote the group's culture. it also said new procedures had been adopted on resettlement, but did not release details
it was an unforgettable getaway car, unfortunately for a man accused of using the white cadillac limousine in two holdups and one attempted robbery
a man dressed in a black leather jacket entered a doughnut shop early friday and demanded money, police said. he got $20 and sped off in the white limousine, victims told officers. soon afterward, a man tried to hold up a convenience store but fled without any money, again in a white cadillac
at another convenience store, the man escaped with $6, and witnesses remembered the limousine and black leather jacket, too
officer gerald young cruised the neighborhood looking for the car, and spotted one in front of a house two blocks from one of the stores
alexander j. fulton jr., 36, came out of his house while police were checking the car and asked what was going on, police said
police found a black leather jacket, and witnesses identified both fulton and the car, they said. fulton was booked on two counts of armed robbery and one of attempted armed robbery
fulton, police said, is the owner of fulton limousine service. it has one car _ a white cadillac limousine
finding out what is happening in tibet has become almost as difficult in this age of high-tech telecommunications as it was for 19th-century adventurers who had to scale snow-swept mountains to reach the fabled land
chinese authorities, hypersensitive to criticism of their tibetan policies, have shut out all foreign reporters since pro-independence tibetans on march 5 staged their fourth protest in five months
they also have halted plane ticket sales to foreigners in chengdu, the main gateway to tibet
in the 19th century, westerners faced possible death from frigid temperatures and bandits when they set out to discover the mysteries of tibetan buddhist worship and the location of their gold and silver fields
foreign reporters in 1988 have no clear picture of what would happen if they somehow managed to evade the barriers and enter lhasa. expulsion from china is one possibility. no news agency has attempted it
concern remains high that authorities are using lhasa's isolation to crack down heavily on youthful militants among the city's fewer than 1,400 tibetan buddhist monks
one of the few official reports on the march 5 protest concluded ominously: ``local religious leaders ... demand justice against the rioters (and) are of the opinion that the people's government has exercised too much restraint and shown enough tolerance and patience towards these people.''
closing off lhasa was easy this time because most travel there already had been halted following three independence protests in september and october in which at least 14 people were killed and dozens others arrested
fourteen foreign journalists who went to lhasa to cover those protests were given 48 hours to leave tibet
an official report said one policeman was killed in daylong clashes march 5 between police and protesters, but unconfirmed reports put casualties at 21 tibetans and three police killed
a u.s. state department official told the associated press that at least 6,000 people took part in the riots and pro-independence rallies
only one reporter, from agence-france presse, was in lhasa on march 5 and he was ordered to leave the next day
the fewer than one dozen foreign travelers left in tibet's mile-high capital of lhasa have become the only link, albeit a weak one, to the outside world
backpackers staying in lhasa's grubby cold-water guesthouses have been interviewed several times each day by reporters telephoning from chengdu and beijing
most have acknowledged the limits of their information _ some don't speak tibetan or chinese, and those who do fear bringing police attention to their tibetan friends and so stay away from the protests
many sympathize with the tibetan cause and all are anxious to keep a low profile aware that chinese authorities have blamed foreigners for past protests
chengdu, a city of 2.6 million people in western china's lush sichuan province, about 760 miles east of lhasa, became a listening post last week for several western reporters
they met lhasa's only outgoing flight each morning and intercepted the few dozen passengers in hopes of obtaining updates on conditions in the city
the interviews produced unconfirmed reports of hundreds, perhaps as many as 1,000 arrests since march 5, several beating deaths of arrested protesters and shows of force by convoys of more than 100 trucks filled with armed police
authorities have refused to comment on the reports. officials in the tibetan autonomous region's foreign affairs office brusquely told reporters who telephoned to put their questions in writing
the result is that reporters are hard put to screen fact from fiction
most foreigners in lhasa or arriving in chengdu from tibet were amazingly patient in answering reporters' questions
a japanese traveler who spoke barely any english nonetheless spent an hour trying to convey what he saw to non-japanese-speaking reporters, by using gestures and imitating the sound of automatic rifle fire
reporters wondered whether their calls to lhasa might get the recipients in trouble. one tibetan woman who answered the telephone at a hotel willingly answered a few questions and then asserted, ``i'm not afraid because ...'' when the line suddenly went dead
president corazon aquino told military cadets saturday to leave policy-making to civilians and concentrate on defeating communist rebels on the battlefield
meanwhile, a classified military intelligence report said the rebels were losing support among the filipino people and predicted that the new people's army would lose about half its fighters by the end of mrs. aquino's term in 1992
the report appeared to contradict public statements by the armed forces leadership that the rebellion is growing and poses a major threat to philippine democracy
mrs. aquino made her remarks during graduation exercises at the philippine military academy, on a mountaintop 130 miles north of the capital of manila
the insurgency war cannot be won by programs and speeches, nor by commissions and committees,'' mrs. aquino told the crowd of 3,000. ``it will be fought, and it will be won, only by you and the men you lead.''
mrs. aquino reminded the 135 graduating cadets that ``policy is the business of the civilian authorities.''
she urged the graduates to place allegiance to the constitution ``above your deference to superiors or friendship for your peers.''
last year, cadets staged a brief sit-down strike in sympathy with leaders of the august coup attempt in which at least 53 people were killed and hundreds wounded, including mrs. aquino's only son, benigno aquino iii
former col. gregorio ``gringo'' honasan, leader of the august coup attempt and a graduate of the academy, was arrested last december in manila
mrs. aquino said the academy curriculum would be revised to emphasize small unit leadership and combat skills. she also promised that officers who display skill in combat will be favored for promotion
honasan complained that corruption and favoritism had sapped the fighting spirit of the 160,000-member armed forces of the philippines
about 2,000 troops stood guard during the commencement ceremony. soldiers armed with m-16 rifles and grenade launchers searched vehicles entering the grounds and helicopter gunships hovered overhead during mrs. aquino's speech
on march 18, 1987, four people were killed when a bomb exploded during rehearsals for the annual graduation exercise. officials blamed right-wing extremists but no one was ever charged in the blast
the academy, modeled after the u.s. military academy at west point, was established in 1904 to train officers for the philippine constabulary while the country was an american colony. it now trains all branches of the military
a classified military intelligence report on the communist insurgency, made in a national intelligence estimate at the end of 1987, predicted the communist party will ``suffer increasing political isolation by 1992.''
the report, distributed to defense secretary fidel ramos in january, says the party will have to step up military operations to recover political support
the report predicted the rebels would escalate their campaign of assassinations of police and soldiers ``to continuously project a position of strength.'' the rebels claimed responsibility for killing scores of police, soldiers and officials in manila last year
but the report estimated that the new people's army, the party's armed wing, had already decreased from 24,430 fighters in 1986 to 21,520 by the end of last year. it predicted the rebel army would decline in strength to 12,170 by 1992, when mrs. aquino's term ends
rebel supporters, or ``mass base,'' had declined from 3.6 million people to 3.1 million people since mrs. aquino took office and was expected to decline to about 1 million by 1992, the report added
the associated press obtained excerpts of the report from sources who insisted on anonymity
the report attributed the decline in rebel strength to improvements in the combat capability of the armed forces and mrs. aquino's economic and political reforms
the forecast contradicts the military's public assessment of the rebel threat. last week, the army said the new people's army numbered 25,000 fighters and that the guerrillas had drawn up plans to take power by 1992
when a major international trade fair opened here last week, the welcoming speech to hundreds of foreign buyers and sellers came from a man the government considers a traitor
aurelio barria, the young, energetic owner of an import-export business, took time off from trying to overthrow his country's military regime to tell the exposition delegates of panama's advantages as a marketplace
if that had a certain strangeness to it, it only served to underscore the complexity of the crisis in panama, where politics, power and money are almost inseparable
panama is undergoing what you might call a `neutron bomb' revolution,'' said one western diplomat. ``the government's opponents are trying to destroy it without destroying the country, and it's a tricky task.''
the diplomat was referring not only to the internal opposition but to the united states, where the reagan administration has been reluctant to impose tougher economic sanctions against panama despite strong public support for such action
with only two opposing votes, the u.s. house on thursday called for a prompt, get-tough policy to rid panama of its military strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega. in floor debate, he was described by one representative after another as a thug, a thief, a tyrant and a drug trafficker
but in announcing new sanctions on friday, president reagan heeded the advice of his chief of staff, howard baker, and his national security adviser, colin l. powell, who had been urging a more moderate course
the president ordered the withholding of panama canal fees due the country that amount to about $6.5 million a month, eliminated preferential tariffs on its exports and told customs officials to keep a closer eye out for ``drug smugglers and money launderers'' from panama
but reagan stopped short of a total trade embargo, which many in congress had urged, and didn't exercise other punitive economic measures at his disposal. he did say he was prepared to take further steps if noriega doesn't resign
barria and other anti-noreiga panamanians are concerned that any drastic measures designed to remove him could wreak havoc on the country, like a harsh chemotherapy treatment that debilitates the patient while attacking his cancer
what we want is not to destroy the country, and not even just to get rid of general noriega, but to end military domination of the civilian government,'' barria said recently
barria is the president of panama's chamber of commerce, industry and agriculture. he was re-elected to a second term late last year while in exile, having fled the country after being charged by the government with sedition
the treason charge came as a result of his principal occupation since last june, that of a leader of an anti-noriega coalition of business, professional, labor and political groups known as the national civic crusade
i haven't really attended to my business in months,'' said barria, who returned to panama in january after being freed on bail. then he added with a laugh: ``hell, i don't even know if i have one left.''
whatever the status of barria's business, one of the major props of panama's economy appears to have suffered irreparable losses in the past nine months of civil turmoil
the banking system as it existed ... is destroyed,'' said a source close to panama's financial community. he, like the diplomat, spoke only on condition of anonymity
the source said as much as $12 billion has been transferred out of panama by wary depositors since the civic crusade began its effort to oust noriega last summer with a series of demonstrations. the 118 banks that make this country one of the world's largest offshore banking centers began 1987 with more than $40 billion in deposits
the amount of money that has fled panama's banking center cannot be confirmed. the government only will admit a crisis exists _ one it blames largely on the united states
most of the money deposited in offshore banks in panama never contributed directly to the nation's economy. it neither was taxed nor used to finance home mortgages, car loans, new businesses or industry or capital improvements
it was just there on paper,'' said the banking industry source. but shuffling that paper did provide employment for about 9,000 people and led to a building boom. in that way, the banking industry contributed, along with real estate, 14.5 percent of the nation's gross national income
the offshore institutions are branches of major banks from more than 30 countries engaged primarily in the sheltering of funds from latin american depositors who are weary of political instability in their own countries
among the hardest hit banks, when the money began fleeing the country last year, were the 12 institutions owned by panamanians. much of the money on deposit in them was transferred either to panama's international banks or to other countries
then, on feb. 25, the country's civilian, figurehead president, eric arturo delvalle, called for the dismissal of noriega, who had been indicted by two federal grand juries in florida almost three weeks earlier on drug trafficking and money laundering charges
within hours, noriega proved who the real boss of panama is by engineering delvalle's ouster
that triggered a new, greater run on the panamanian banks and they closed four days later, on march 1. two days after that, the government ordered them to remain closed, admitting that it could not provide enough money to cover anticipated withdrawals. it also closed temporarily the 106 foreign banks
the banks remain closed, with no sign they will reopen this week. the situation has created chaos for individuals and businesses as well. all are strapped for cash
the noriega government says it is a victim of ``economic aggression'' by the united states, where federal courts have tied up some $50 million in official panamanian funds on deposit in u.s. banks. at question is whether the money rightfully should be controlled by noriega or delvalle
delvalle has been in hiding for two weeks, but the united states still considers him the legitimate president. the civic crusade leaders, who used to refer to delvalle as a puppet, also have reluctantly endorsed him as the true constitutional authority
some opposition leaders complained privately that state department officials forced them to support delvalle and join him in a call last week for a new transitional government pending elections scheduled for next year
said a diplomatic source: ``it's important at this point that they appear united, that they not be fighting among themselves. i think washington made that point to them. what happens to delvalle later is something they can work out at the appropriate time.'' charges</head>
a prosecutor charged saturday that anwar sadat's brother and other relatives used the slain president's name ``to ruin the country'' and should lose $8.2 million in property as punishment
esmat sadat, already convicted of using his brother's position to enrich himself during anwar sadat's 11 years in office, responded that the prosecution was sullying the late president's name by making the accusations
the exchange came during a hearing of the ethics court to decide whether the assets of esmat sadat, three sons and seven other family members should be confiscated
the property, estimated at $8.2 million, was sequestered in 1983 after the defendants' convictions on influence peddling, black marketeering, bribery and other charges. esmat sadat and three sons were sentenced to one-year prison terms
the court adjourned saturday after both sides presented their arguments. a decision is expected on april 9
as the prosecution presented its case saturday, blaming sadat's relatives for ``using the late leader's name to ruin the country,'' esmat stood and objected vigorously
the prosecution insists on using the name of the late leader,'' esmat said loudly from the third row of benches
his name should not be used as a (prosecution) tool,'' he said, looking shaken
sayed abdel-baky, president of the seven-man tribunal hearing the case, admonished esmat not to interrupt the proceedings and said such comments would be heard at the end of the hearing
we are only glorifying the name of the late president,'' said assistant prosecutor mohsen mahmoud. ``at the center of this case is the exploitation of the late president's name.''
he cited examples of the defendants' use of the family name to win government contracts outside bureaucratic channels required of most private citizens
the late president, killed by moslem extremists on oct. 6, 1981, was absolved of any wrongdoing in esmat's earlier trial
the ethics court is empowered to sequester property and order defendants detained for up to five years. after that, the prosecutor may ask the court to confiscate a defendant's property in the name of the state
the court can decide whether to permanently seize the property, keep it sequestered and allow the prosecutor's office to control the assets, or return the property to the defendants
about 150 people rode a convoy of 47 trucks and vans through taipei on saturday to demand direct elections for taiwan's provincial governor and the mayors of the island's two largest cities
leaders of the opposition democratic progressive party, standing on top of the vans, chanted slogans during the two-hour demonstration. banners hung from the cars, including one that read: ``governmental appointment is a symbol of authoritarian rule.''
under existing law, the provincial governor and the mayors of taipei and kaohsiung, a southern port, are appointed by the nationalist government
opposition lawmaker kang ning-hsiang, who organized the demonstration, said the appointed officials ``lack support of the people.''
the demonstration was approved by the police and ended without any violence
the south korean government plans to lift restrictions on overseas travel this year as its pursues democratic development and liberalization, foreign ministry officials said saturday
currently, only koreans over 40 are given passports for overseas tourism, and various conditions are attached
ministry officials said president roh tae-woo has urged foreign minister choi kwang-soo to ease restrictions on overseas travel and allow more young people to venture abroad
the age limit in overseas travel would be lifted gradually this year,'' said a ministry official who spoke on condition of anonymity
roh was elected president last december in the country's first democratic elections in 16 years
president reagan's decision to withhold a $6.5 million payment owed to panama next tuesday was aimed at impairing military strongman manuel noriega's ability to pay government workers this coming week, according to u.s. officials
the timing was no coincidence,'' one official said, expressing hope that the departure of noriega could be hastened if government workers, faced with economic hardship, join the ranks of the opposition
the remaining sanctions reagan imposed on friday will not have an immediate consequence, and the officials believe noriega could be out of office by the time they have an impact
the sanctions were the latest in a series of steps the united states has taken over the past eight months to undercut noriega, who is under u.s. indictment on drug smuggling charges
according to reports from panama, the government is so strapped for cash that it has been considering several austerity measures to deal with payroll budget shortfalls
they included delaying paychecks to the nation's 150,000 government workers, reducing their pay temporarily or giving them partial payment in food instead of cash, the reports said
outside the 15,000-member defense force, the regime's main source of support has been government workers. if civil servants begin turning against noriega, that would narrow his already small base of support even further, said the u.s. officials, insisting on anonymity
the soldiers were paid last thursday but monday is payday for the nation's 20,000 school teachers, and thousands of other government workers are due their paychecks on tuesday
ambassador juan b. sosa, who opposes noriega, said the cash shortage forced panama to default on a $39 million loan repayment due last week to the government of japan
sosa has remained loyal to ousted president eric arturo delvalle and has refused to relinquish his post to a successor named by noriega. sosa shares the reagan administration view that delvalle's ouster by noriega two weeks ago was unconstitutional
before last friday, the administration had suspended all economic and military aid to panama and ordered u.s. representatives in international lending institutions to oppose loan requests from panama
beyond that, it has lent its support to legal efforts by delvalle's representatives here to freeze panamanian assets in the united states
as a result, panama does not have access to the revenues it normally receives from american use of a trans-isthmian pipeline that sends alaskan oil on its way to east coast u.s. ports. those revenues have been variously estimated at between $80 and $120 million a year
in addition, panamanian assets in u.s. banks, estimated at $50 million, also have been frozen
noriega has been attempting to rally support from his countrymen by blaming the united states for panama's financial problems. but secretary of state george p. shultz said noriega's campaign has not worked and that the united states and the panamanian people are ``on the same side.''
reagan tightened the screws on friday when he ordered the $6.5 million fee due to panama for canal-related services placed in escrow. it will be released once civilian government is restored, he said
reagan also acted to strip panama of the right to sell its products in u.s. markets either duty-free or at the lowest tariffs rates possible. these benefits are given to panama under a system of tariff preferences accorded to third world countries and under the caribbean basin initiative, designed to help 21 countries in that region
but most of panama's income from u.s. exports would not be affected by the sanction because they carry no duties to begin with. examples are bananas, shellfish, fish and coffee, which account for well over half of panama's annual u.s. exports
two items which will be affected by reagan's action are sweaters, a $23.5 million business for panama last year, and petroleum products, $14.6 million. u.s. government estimates of panama's total exports to the united states range between $342 million and $388 million
hugh wolfe frank, chief interpreter at the nuremberg war crimes trials, has died. he was 75
frank's body was found thursday in a fume-filled car on a farm track near the wiltshire village of mere in southwest england on thursday
frank had been suffering from parkinson's disease and was known to be depressed about his worsening health
wiltshire police said saturday they did not suspect any crime in connection with his death and had reported the facts to assistant wiltshire coroner peter stoddart
frank, who was separated from his fifth wife, was a skillful linguist who led the team of interpreters at the trials in nuremberg, west germany, of top nazis, including hermann goering and rudolf hess
the wiltshire coroner's office has ordered an inquest into his death
a former national police chief, convicted of involvement in the torture death of a student dissident, was released saturday after his eight-month prison sentence was suspended
the seoul district criminal court found kang min-chang guilty of misfeasance and dereliction of duty, but immediately suspended his sentence in consideration of his contribution to the nation
kang was arrested in january, nearly a year after a dissident college student died while being questioned in police custody. police at first said it was an accident but later admitted the student was killed by torture
the case triggered widespread anti-government protests, leading to the arrest of eight police officers
a fresh controversy flared in january when the opposition urged the government to punish high-ranking police officiers who allegedly covered up the cause of the student's death
filipino doctors performed a simultaneous kidney and pancreas transplant in the first such procedure ever performed in asia, the national kidney institute said saturday
institute director filoteo alano said the surgery was performed march 3 on a 58-year-old filipino businessman who had suffered kidney failure
the doctors replaced the patient's organs with those of an 18-year-old man who was pronounced brain dead after a fall, alano said
dr. enrique ona, chief of the surgical team, said the procedure took about 14 hours, including the time spent removing the organs from the donor
alano said the patient, tan koc lee, had nearly normal kidney functions and was recovering
the drug indictment of a top haitian military officer has spotlighted that nation's emergence as a way station for cocaine traffickers seeking safer routes and reinforces charges that corrupt officials aid smugglers
col. jean-claude paul, along with his brother and ex-wife, were charged in a federal indictment unsealed thursday with using a landing strip on the colonel's farm to fly a 100-kilogram, or 220-pound, cocaine shipment to the bahamas for delivery to miami
haitian president leslie manigat has turned paul's case over to his country's military courts for investigation. there is no extradition treaty between haiti and the united states
one of the principal witnesses in the case, osvaldo quintana, told reporters in january that he saw 9,000 kilograms, or 19,800 pounds, of cocaine in duffel bags in the haitian presidential palace during the administration of ousted leader jean-claude duvalier
quintana also told the associated press that other haitian officials besides paul had a role in the smuggling, but he would not disclose their names
the alleged trafficking by high-level haitians has angered sen. bob graham, d-fla., who said he will introduce legislation this week to lift u.s. trade preferences with haiti
this indictment is further indication that we can't tolerate a regime in haiti that seized power from the haitian people so it could continue the oppression of the past,'' said graham
drug enforcement administration spokesman jack hook said better technology such as improved radar and more cooperation from bahamian authorities have sharply limited the traditional drug routes into south florida
that has forced colombian cocaine traffickers to go through other caribbean islands
we have seen an increase in haiti being used as a transshipment point since we stepped up enforcement,'' said hook
asked about quintana's allegations that other haitian officials are involved, hook would say only that the investigation is continuing
the message that this case sends is the corrupting effects on public officials everywhere becuse of drug trafficking,'' said hook
rep. larry smith, d-fla., was blunter about the haitian connection
more than two years ago i questioned the dea about increased drug trafficking through haiti, and about government involvement in the traffic,'' smith said recently
he said the dea told him then they had no information on haitian officials' involvement in drug smuggling
this is the kind of head-in-the-sand attitude that has allowed government after government to fall prey to the colombian cartels,'' said smith
whether it is a few corrupt officials, a policy of the new military-supported government, or just coincidence, haiti's role has changed since duvalier fled
there has been some increase in drug interceptions since the haitian government changed two years ago,'' acknowledged coast guard lt. cmdr. jim simpson
he said drug officials are spotting more planes flying over the haitian half of the island of hispaniola, which haiti shares with the dominican republic. the dominican republic recently shot down a suspected trafficker, but simpson said haiti does not have the resources to chase drug planes
hook said that since november the dea has had an office in port-au-prince, the haitian capital, and is optimistic that haitian officials will cooperate
in the 90 days before the dea's arrival, haitian customs officials seized 1,500 pounds of cocaine hidden on planes at port-au-prince's airport, he said
and the paul case should make it even more difficult for traffickers, he said
the publicity is going to put a little heat on haiti,'' said hook
but he said no one should expect trafficking to cease if haiti clamps down, since smugglers are already using cuba, the turks and caicos islands and other routes
there is no caribbean island close to the united states that has gone unscathed,'' said hook. ``it just shows the magnitude of the problem.''
a speeding freight train derailed near the baltic port of klaipeda in lithuania, breaking open 23 tank cars that spilled fuel over a 1,300-foot stretch of railway, the tass news agency reported saturday
tass said workers had blocked the flow of oil into the nearby baltic sea, but did not make clear whether the spill was contained before some of the oil reached the water
there was no indication whether there was any permanent environmental damage or whether the accident caused casualties
the accident occurred near klaipeda, but tass did not say how far away from the soviet's major fuel-shipping port on the baltic
twenty three tanks, which were deformed and derailed, leaked oil products to both sides of the railway embankment,'' tass said
according to tentative information, the accident occurred because safe speed at the turn of the railway was exceeded,'' the news agency said, quoting a baltic railway official identified as dmitri blyaskin
rail traffic resumed midday saturday after a halt of several hours, tass said
authorities released two men they had described as prime suspects in a two-state killing spree after the men passed lie detector tests, their prints didn't match those on a weapon and a witness failed to identify them
authorities had planned to hold a hearing friday night to determine if they had probable cause to hold the men in connection with four brutal slayings on monday in gainesville, texas; farmersville, texas; and in saratoga, ark. but when the two passed lie detector tests, authorities canceled the hearing and agreed unanimously to let the men go
the men were given tickets for a bus bound for terre haute, ind., hometown of one of the men, officials said
it was a misidentification is what it was,'' one of the men said. ``we fit the description, so what else can you say? it's not my fault somebody else out there looks like me.''
the other man told the dallas morning news he was terrified to learn ``i was facing death row.''
i thought i was going to die for something i didn't do,'' he said
prosecuting attorney jim hudson jr. said a man who reported having a run-in with the apparent killers the night of the arkansas murder was unable friday to identify the two men in custody
their release leaves officials without a suspect in the slaying of deana andrews woodard, 23, who was found in her gainesville, texas, mobile home monday with her throat slashed, police said
authorities believe ms. woodard's slaying is connected to the fatal shootings of cecil floyd morrison, 85, and cecil leonard morrison, 62. the two were killed in their farmersville, texas, home. the men's pickup truck was found later in southwestern arkansas, and officers said a prescription of ms. woodard's was found in the vehicle
a description of two men who hitched a ride monday night with kenneth olden, 34, of saratoga, whose body was found tuesday, led authorities to the men who were arrested and released. olden's body was dumped along a road after he had been shot three times
they fit the description. but when all the evidence came back in, the fingerprints didn't match (those lifted from a murder weapon) and they passed a polygraph,'' said hempstead county sheriff don worthey said
assistant secretary of state chester a. crocker will hold his first talks in two years with south africa's foreign minister in an effort to advance a u.s. peace initiative for southern africa, the state department said saturday
crocker's meeting with roelof ``pik'' botha next week at an unspecified european location also will give the united states an opportunity to ``register concern'' about recent developments in south africa, spokeswoman anita stockman said. the united states has complained about anti-dissent measures proposed in south africa in the past few weeks
a state department working group arrived in angola on wednesday to explore the possibility of further talks on getting the estimated 40,000 cuban troops out of the country as part of an overall settlement, stockman said
since he took office in 1981, crocker has been seeking to negotiate a withdrawal of cuban troops from angola in return for south african withdrawal from neighboring namibia
the cuban troops have been battling a powerful guerrilla force, unita, which is backed by south african and u.s. assistance
in what appeared to be a major breakthrough when crocker was in angola in january, cuba declared its willingness in principle to pull the troops out of the country, but the overall settlement that would bring that about is still to be arranged
angola has said south african willingness to participate in the negotiations _ and abide by a united nations resolution giving independence to namibia _ is a necessary ingredient of a settlement
stockman said crocker's meeting with botha will ``afford an opportunity to reassess south africa's willingness to proceed toward a settlement involving total cuban troop withdrawal from angola and namibian independence based on u.n. security council resolution 435.''
crocker also is expected to restate u.s. demands for a cessation of cross border forays by south african troops and concern about a new crackdown on groups seeking more rights for the country's black majority
last month, the government outlawed the political activities of 17 anti-apartheid organizations. the government has also introduced legislation to bar a wide range of organizations from receiving foreign funds
foreign governments and private agencies send millions of dollars in assistance to these groups as a way of aiding south africans without sending funds to their government
a three-week festival featuring soviet music opened with envoys for president reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev praising the organizers of the cultural exchange for bringing the two countries closer together
making music together,'' with its 285 soviet musicians, dancers, composers and other artists, is the first part of an exchange that will bring a celebration focusing on american contemporary music to moscow in the fall of 1989
reagan's praise came in a letter to sarah caldwell, a key organizer of the exchange and artistic director of the opera company of boston. it was read friday night by greg guroff of the government-run u.s. information agency
the letter described the event as ``one of the most ambitious cultural projects ever undertaken between the united states and the soviet union ... a testament to the potential of u.s.-soviet cooperation in artistic and cultural endeavors.''
soviet ambassador yuri dubinin, who flew from washington to attend opening ceremonies, read gorbachev's ``best wishes for success for the benefit of peace, friendship and cooperation between our two nations.''
also present at the ornate, turn-of-the century boston opera house was yuri melentiev, the minister of culture of russia, the soviet union's largest republic
melentiev told reporters the festival stood as a symbol of improved superpower relationships in the wake of the meeting between reagan and gorbachev in washington late last year
the festival is in the red because of unexpected costs that drove the price tag above the estimated budget of $2.4 million to $3.3 million, and organizers last month seriously considered the idea of declaring bankruptcy and canceling the event
but organizers said they decided not to call if off after being told by the state department that cancellation could mar relations with the soviet union
harold hestes, president of the greater boston chamber of commerce and a key fund-raiser, said shortly before the opening ceremonies that the original shortfall of $900,000 had been reduced to about $200,000
last september, the fbi asked 20 new york-area libraries to watch for and report on library users who might be gathering information for hostile powers. library officials refused, calling the move an effort to turn librarians into informers
that incident is one of 60 that were added last year by the reporters committee for freedom of the press to a summary of actions ``taken by the reagan administration since 1981 to restrict public and media access to government information.''
the committee's list now has more than 200 items, which ``underscores that contempt for the public's right to know permeates virtually all facets of the current administration's information policy,'' said jane e. kirtley, executive director of the committee
the fbi said its attempt to recruit librarians was part of a national counterintelligence initiative. when the attempt was disclosed by the new york times, james fox, deputy assistant director of the new york fbi office said, ``all we are interested in is the fact that a hostile diplomat is there. we don't want librarians to become amateur sleuths.''
some of the new items on the committee list are:
_``revelations by lt. gen. william e. odom, head of the national security agency, that he regularly refers cases of news leaks to the justice department, asking that the journalists reporting the information be prosecuted under espionage laws.''
_refusal by the justice department to disclose its financial settlement with the families of the challenger astronauts. news media, including the associated press, went to court and last week were granted access to the records
_in november, reporters for the atlanta journal and constitution asked the bureau of prisons for names of prisoners inside the federal penitentiary in atlanta when 1,100 cuban prisoners held that prison for 11 days. the bureau refused, citing a policy of protecting prisoners' privacy by not giving out their names
_last month, president reagan asked congress for a new exemption to the freedom of information act that would require federal agencies to withhold government-generated and government-owned scientific and technical information. it would be the 10th exemption to the foi act and the first since 1974, the committee said
_in march last year, sen. alan k. simpson, r-wyo., ``lambasted'' reporters for questioning reagan during a photo session. ``simpson said reporters did `a sadistic little disservice' by questioning the president while he was off balance.''
the american diet is lousy and people are dying because of it
that's the conclusion of a long-term study by the national cancer institute of what americans eat and don't eat during a typical day
we really need to change the way we eat,'' said gladys block, an nci scientist and coauthor of a study published this month in the american journal of public health. ``i really believe that could make a difference in the amount of cancer we have.''
americans are not eating enough fruits, vegetables, whole-grain breads and high-fiber cereals. they are eating more fat and more salt-cured, nitrite-cured, smoked and pickled meat, all dietary elements that can affect health
in effect, said blossom patterson, a coauthor of the study, americans are forgetting the lessons they should have learned as children at the family dining table
it's not really a new message,'' said patterson. ``this is the same theme that mothers have been playing for a long, long time. eat your vegetables and fruits.''
and, says the nci, if you eat like your mommies told you to, you may live a longer time
the study said that diet is estimated to contribute to about 35 percent of all cancer deaths
block said that the right foods have been shown to help prevent cancers of the stomach, colon, rectum, breast, oral cavity and esophagus. statistics released earlier this year show that all of these types of cancer have increased in frequency. block said the message is that to eat well may mean to live longer. and she said americans simply aren't doing that
in interviews with more than 11,000 people, researchers from the nci and department of agriculture found that:
_ on a typical day, 40 percent of americans do not eat a single fruit, and 20 percent have no vegetable
_ only about 49 percent of americans include ``garden vegetables'' (vegetables other than potatoes or salad) in their daily diet
_ more than 80 percent of those surveyed ate no high-fiber cereals or whole-grain breads
_ daily fiber intake, from whole grains or from vegetables such as corn or dried peas and beans, averaged about 11 grams. the recommended amount is 20 to 30 grams daily
_ more than 40 percent of those surveyed ate at least one serving of lunch meat or bacon daily. these are foods high in fat and salt, and may be smoked or cured with nitrites
women, generally, had a better diet than men, and people over age 55 usually had better diets than young adults, said block
even so, all groups showed a dramatic need for improvement, with consumption of fruits, vegetables and whole-grains falling far short of desirable levels,'' she said
patterson said that even though fruits and vegetables high in vitamins a and c are thought to be of special importance in lowering cancer risk, 75 percent of those interviewed failed to include these items in their daily diets
in a racial breakdown of the data, patterson said the survey showed that black people ate more vegetables than did whites, largely due to a higher consumption of greens, such as collards. whites, however, ate more whole-grain breads and high-fiber cereals
income also plays a role, she said. those with higher incomes tended to eat more fruits and vegetables, along with more red meat
by region, more people ate poultry and fish in the south and northeast than in the west and midwest, and red meat consumption was lowest in the south. high-fiber cereal consumption was highest in the northeast and west, and lowest in the south
the survey data was collected between 1976 and 1980, but block said that preliminary studies of more recent surveys show there has been little change. and the consumption patterns from the 1976-80 survey, in turn, show almost no change from data collected from 1971 to 1974
block said researchers are becoming increasingly convinced that simple changes in diet, such as just adding an apple or orange or some cole slaw to a typical fast food meal, could make a difference
if everybody just had fruit and vegetables every day, that could lead to a drop in the number of cancers,'' she said. 0787</first> `richard gephardt ...</note>
vice president george bush's apparent lock on the republican presidential nomination is beginning to cool democratic excitement over the prospect of a brokered national convention
barring a collapse of unimaginable proportions, bush will spend the final months of the primary season seeking support for the fall campaign from independent voters and potential democratic converts
the longer the democratic nominating war goes on, the better bush likes it. a democratic national convention this summer featuring bloodletting on prime-time tv would suit him just fine
democrats know this well, and that may give them an impetus to rally around a candidate sooner rather than later, particularly given bush's evident vulnerability on the iran-contra affair
no one understands this better than jimmy carter. the former president told an audience in connecticut last week that he emerged from the 1976 and 1980 conventions ``weaker than i went in.''
he said the democrats should find a ``winning ticket'' and unite behind it in atlanta
why is 51 percent the magic number?'' asks new york gov. mario cuomo. ``let's pick the guy who's ahead after california,'' the last state to vote in the primary season
if mike dukakis has 41 percent (of the delegates), get everybody together in a room and say, `jesse (jackson) gore, gephardt, you came close, but mike's the candidate.''
that would avoid what carter calls the ``circus'' type of convention that twice nominated him
carter's lead over republican gerald ford declined steadily during the 1976 fall campaign, although he won a close call. in 1980, weakened politically, he triumped over sen. edward m. kennedy in an emotional convention struggle before losing a landslide to ronald reagan
carter says that this time, he and the 645 so-called democatic superdelegates, ``will have a burning desire to put together a winning ticket'' when they convene in atlanta
that makes the senate democratic caucus, which picks 43 delegates on april 19, and the house democratic caucus, which picks 210 delegates a day later, as critical as any democratic primary waged with television advertising, phone banks and direct mail
the same is true for the 362 members of the democratic national committee who are superdelegates, and the 25 governors
the key now to this thing ending early is superdelegates,'' says robert beckel, a democratic campaign consultant not aligned with any of this year's contenders. ``they're also the key to not ending it early.''
any candidate who succeeds in picking up a large amount of support from the people selected in those two congressional meetings will be able to send a clear signal to the party that he is the presumptive nominee, even before the primary season ends
to earn that support, a contender would presumably have to score well in the industrial state contests leading up to the congressional caucuses _ illinois, michigan, connecticut, wisconsin and new york
richard gephardt, the missouri congressman, already has the support of several dozen house members. he probably could consolidate his strength if he mounted a comeback after his poor super tuesday showing. but he if fails to win in michigan's caucuses march 26, he is a likely dropout, and his supporters are free to go elsewhere
sen. albert gore of tennessee must show quickly that he can win in the industrial states or he will have littel claim on the allegience of congress members
jesse jackson is in the process of obtaining a large bloc of perhaps 800 delegates, and figures prominently in the brokered convention scenarios that occupy democratic political insiders. he will get his share of support in congress, as elsewhere, but most house and senate members aren't likely to go over to his side
the democrat who now looks in the strongest position in the race, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, would have to run well in the industrial states, and probably signal his willingness to name a southerner as his running mate in the fall
carter said he and the party leaders want a winning ticket, and dukakis, for all the boasting over his primary wins in texas and florida, ran poorly among disaffected democrats that the party needs to win the presidency
gore whipped him among democrats who voted for president reagan in 1984, 39 percent to 23 percent, according to abc interviews on super tuesday with primary voters in 12 southern states
dukakis defeated gore among liberals and the two split the moderate vote. but gore won among self-described conservatives, 38 percent to 21 percent, according to the abc polls
a father whose two teen-age sons joined the racist skinheads group turned them in to police after one of them confessed to fatally stabbing a homeless black man
i can't elaborate on it. but i will say that i did turn them in,'' lowell ``bud'' mckee told the st. petersburg times. ``there are more things involved than i can make public.''
scott mckee, 18, and dean mckee, 16, members of the skinheads, a group known for its hatred of blacks, jews and homosexuals, were arrested march 4 and charged with first-degree murder in the december slaying of isiah walker, 41
mckee, who adopted the boys in 1977 after marrying their mother, also told the tampa tribune he tried to commit his younger son to a crisis unit last month but gave up after he was referred from agency to agency
he sought treatment for dean after the boy ran away several times and threatened to kill his mother and himself if he were placed in a program for disturbed children, mckee said. he did not know about the slaying at the time, he said
mckee said he wanted to get his son committed under the state's mental health act, which lets judges order the temporary detention of anyone deemed by mental health experts to be a danger to themselves or others. but mental health officials said threats don't always constitute proof of mental illness
dean was hospitalized for two months at age 15 after attempting suicide and had private counseling for six months after he was released, mckee said
elisabeth ann zinser, who resigned as president of gallaudet university amid protests from students who want a deaf leader, enraged students and faculty at the school for the hearing impaired by suggesting she would quickly learn sign language
in truth, say professors at gallaudet, learning sign language _ widely considered the nation's third most frequently used ``foreign'' language _ is as difficult as mastering russian or chinese
she (zinser) thought she would come in here and pick up sign language in three months,'' said robert johnson, an audiology professor at the nation's only liberal arts college for the hearing impaired. ``unfortunately, you don't catch sign like you catch a cold.''
there are three different varieties of sign language, the purest of which has no connection with the english language, while the crudest version relies heavily on english vocabulary and sentence structure, johnson said
johnson and scott lidell, both professors in gallaudet's department of linguistics, say around 2 million americans are considered deaf by audiometric standards, while 18 million others suffer from some hearing loss
those who use sign language are usually in the smaller group, while persons with less severe hearing loss do not usually learn sign language. the majority of gallaudet's students are profoundly deaf, and use sign language, according to school officials
american sign language, the purest form of signing, is commonly used between people who are either profoundly deaf, or have been deaf since birth, johnson said. comparing asl to the use of a foreign language, asl users are roughly equivalent to those fluent in a foreign tongue
but similarities with written or spoken language end there, johnson emphasized
english relies on a linear structure, with one word following the last, but in asl, the message is conveyed through simultaneous use of facial expressions, finger signs, and motions,'' johnson said
asl has a base vocabulary on which general themes, not individual words, are built. images, rather than words expressed in sign, convey the signer's message
it's extremely time-efficient,'' lidell said. ``you have two hands, a face, and a body participating in delivering the message. in spoken or written english, you have just words. signing gives you more channels.''
deaf people comunicating with hearing people mix sign language with some components of formal english, the result being a type of sign language called contact variety signing, or pidgin sign english
in the contact variety method, the message expressed may use numerous images associated with asl, but the message is based on the syntax of an english sentence
it is this form of communication through which gallaudet student protest leaders, with the assistance of interpreters, conveyed their message to the media and campus onlookers
sign supported english is the third type of sign. it does not rely on facial expressions, and involves sending messages primarily with spoken english. signing symbols are used to reinforce the spoken message, in what johnson describes as ``coding speech on the hands.''
sign supported english, johnson said, is slow and awkward, and is the only type of sign language zinser could have learned in less than six months. there are sign language symbols for each of the 26 characters in the english alphabet, and, when signers cannot find a symbol for an english word, they may spell out the english word, then return to sign. fingerspelling is used in all three types of sign
gallaudet professors, 30 percent of whom are deaf, are required to know sign language, and must pass sign examinations for promotions or raises, according to roger beach, a counseling professor who designed gallaudet's exam program
actress audrey hepburn will trek to famine-ravaged regions of ethiopia to survey conditions there as she carries out her duties as a newly appointed unicef special ambassador
the united nations said miss hepburn will leave monday on the four-day visit, which will include stops at relief and rehabilitation centers in the hardest-hit provinces of tigray and eritrea. the trip ends thursday at development projects in central shoa province, according to unicef
total and near-total crop failures last year threaten an estimated 7 million people with famine in northern ethiopia, where fighting between rebels and the nation's marxist government has hampered relief efforts
a country music buff is hoping readers will go gaga over his new book featuring baby pictures of more than 150 country music stars, including glen campbell, willie nelson, naomi and wynonna judd, dolly parton, ronnie milsap and the oak ridge boys
paul randall, a radio personality, gathered the photos for his book, ``baby photos of the country stars,'' which also includes current pictures of the performers and trivia questions about their careers
randall is a former publicist for rca records in nashville and has written two previous books, ``facts, fallacies and folklore'' and ``country music quizzes.''
former president jimmy carter is joining health officials in a campaign to eradicate guinea worm disease, a crippling parasitic affliction that plagues millions of africans and asians
carter will travel to africa this week on a six-day, three-nation visit to bolster efforts to wipe out the guinea worm, which strikes 10 million people a year in developing countries
the world health organization voted in 1986 to make guinea worm disease the next target for global eradication, following the successful eradication of smallpox 11 years ago
traveling with carter and his wife, rosalynn, will be carter presidential center executive director william foege, who led the smallpox effort while at the centers for disease control. also in the party will be several staff members from the center and global 2000, a policy institute under the auspices of the carter center
guinea worms can grow to lengths of nearly 3 feet inside the body. they do not themselves cause a fatal disease, but the painful sores created when they break through skin can be crippling. their larvae are spread through contaminated drinking water
fighting the disease involves improvements in water supply, which can be costly for developing countries
the image of country music singer loretta lynn, ``the coal miner's daughter,'' now has been immortalized in oil as well as celluloid
artist wayne hart has finished the first two of six oil paintings of the singer. one, entitled ``the beginning of the legend,'' depicts the singer holding a rose. the second, called ``memories of a coal miner's daughter,'' shows a coal car and its track
the remaining four will be completed during the next two years, said miss lynn, who was born and raised in kentucky mining area
her autobiography was made into a 1980 movie, ``coal miner's daughter,'' starring sissy spacek, who won an academy award as best actress. miss lynn's hits include ``when the tingle becomes a chill'' and ``you're looking at country.''
chinese companies that want to sell their products abroad are being given greater freedom to do so, the government announced saturday
the state council, china's cabinet, said the nation will introduce a contract system under which the power to handle most import and export commodities will be transferred to local foreign trade companies and certain well-managed industrial enterprises
details of the new system were provided by the official xinhua news agency
it said areas and cities enjoying special status as foreign trade centers will be able to sign contracts with the state guaranteeing the state a certain amount of hard currency
after that they will be free to pursue international contracts as they wish
following introduction of the system, china will reduce mandatory state quotas for exports and the number of state-handled export commodities
national export and import corporations will handle only a small amount of commodities. instead, their branches will become independent managerial entitites run by local governments
xinhua said the new foreign trade structure encourages local authorities and export-oriented enterprises to participate in foreign trade
the report said china this year will also reform its foreign exchange managerial structure. local governments, enterprises and institutions and foreign-funded businesses will be allowed to exchange hard currency through government-run exchange centers
it said china's coastal areas will be encouraged to develop export-oriented industries by expanding labor- and expertise-intensive industries
communist party chief zhao ziyang has proposed significant increases in the number of regions given preferential treatment in developing foreign trade as a means of helping china make greater inroads in world markets
the state council urged local governments to accelerate the introduction of the responsibility system _ making companies responsible for profits and losses _ in foreign trade companies
china's foreign trade climbed 13 percent last year to about $80 billion. the reformist leaders in beijing see foreign trade as a critical factor in introducing technology and earning hard currency for the nation's modernization drive
a condemned man who insists he's innocent and whose case has become a rallying cry for death penalty opponents is seeking his seventh reprieve from the electric chair, with just two days left before his scheduled execution
willie jasper darden faces execution early tuesday at florida state prison near starke for the september 1973 killing of furniture store owner carl turman during a $15 robbery
let me tell you something. willie darden is not a murderer!'' darden, 54, told the associated press in a 1985 interview, a claim that he has made to dozens of reporters who have interviewed him
darden has received six stays of execution, more than any other florida inmate, and his case has attracted international attention, with supporters saying he was a victim of racial prejudice at his trial because he is black
two witnesses say they have information to back up his story, but their accounts were dismissed as mistaken and not new by the lawyer who prosecuted darden
there is no question he is guilty,'' ray mcdaniel, now a bartow attorney, said friday in a telephone interview
mcdaniel said he believed darden will die tuesday. ``i don't think you will find a judge with the guts to issue a stay,'' he said
i think it's time. i think it's about 12 years too late,'' mcdaniel said, who added that darden was linked, but never charged, with other murders
attorneys for the office of capital collateral review filed an appeal friday with the florida supreme court
darden's is one of the most-litigated cases involving a death row inmate, with nearly 100 judges involved in decisions. it has been before the u.s. supreme court four times already
mcdaniel discounted the assertions of two people who repeated claims friday at an amnesty international news conference in tallahassee that they believe darden is innocent
the rev. sam sparks, a baptist minister, and christine bass, a lakeland secretary, said they had information they say might clear darden of the crime
i know willie darden is innocent. it is not a belief, it is a knowledge,'' said ms. bass
sparks said turman's wife had told him that all blacks looked alike to her and that her identification of darden was unimportant because lawyers had told her that darden committed the crime. helen baum, formerly helen turman, recently denied having made that statement to sparks and reaffirmed her identification of darden as the man who shot her husband
ms. bass said darden's car was broken down near her home until a tow truck arrived about 25 minutes before the robbery, eight miles away
mcdaniel said the two are mistaken about the times and that the defense knew their claims at the time of the trial
amnesty international officials have claimed gov. bob martinez is rushing to execute darden for political reasons
the governor signed a seventh death warrant for darden on march 8, just a day after the u.s. supreme court refused to intervene, and set his execution for tuesday, giving darden's attorneys less than a week to prepare his case
i think what the governor is looking for some kind of ritualistic sacrifice that he can go through to prove he's tough on crime,'' said magdaleno rose-avila, national director of amnesty international's campaign to abolish the death penalty. he noted that the governor's popularity rating has been low in recent polls
when martinez signed the sixth death warrant in darden's case earlier this year, soviet dissident andrei sakharov, american actress margot kidder and british rock star peter gabriel urged clemency for darden. sakharov won the 1975 nobel peace prize for his defense of human rights in the soviet union
the governor's spokesman said politics had nothing to do with the decision
international attention has no real bearing on whether a legally imposed sentence that has been upheld by the courts should be carried out,'' said press secretary jon peck
thousands of protesters outside the offices of president kurt waldheim on saturday urged him to resign and remembered the victims of nazism 50 years after adolf hitler's troops marched into austria
police estimated about 5,000 people attended despite pouring rain and strong winds. the organizers estimated 10,000
the demonstration, called by more than a dozen well known austrian intellectuals, marked the march 1938 annexation of austria to nazi germany
one of several banners displayed said, ``memorial year without waldheim.''
debate has surrounded the former u.n. secretary-general since 1986, when the first revelations surfaced about his service in the german army in the balkans during world war ii
a panel of historians appointed by the austrian government issued a report last month that said he was ``in close proximity'' to some nazi atrocities, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them
it also said waldheim concealed his wartime past and tried to make it seem harmless once he could no longer hide it
demonstrators arrived saturday by bus and train from across austria. loudspeakers played a recording of hitler's speech to cheering masses on the adjoining square on march 15, 1938
hundreds of thousand of austrians welcomed the annexation, known as the anschluss, but others actively resisted it
author peter turrini, one of several artists and intellectuals who addressed the crowd, said austrians had not yet done enough to confront their wartime past
there has not yet been one minute of confession,'' he declared
chancellor franz vranitzky, speaking at the site of a former prison camp for gypsies, said austrians ``may not behave as (they did) after 1945 ... when no one asked what hapened to the austrians who left the country in 1938.''
at the demonstration before waldheim's offices, rosa jochmann, a former concentration camp inmate and resistance fighter, gave an emotional speech that left many spectators weeping
she recalled that even people who were not directly responsible for nazi atrocities ``simply walked by'' acts of violence
it is not true that one should not mourn, one must,'' she said. ``all those who lived through it (the nazi period) must speak. i will never be silent.''
the organizers appealed for a minute of silence after the speech. in contrast to friday, when a nationwide minute of silence was only sparsely observed, the entire square fell still
israeli warplanes blasted palestinian guerrilla bases on the outskirts of sidon on saturday in apparent retaliation for the killing of three israelis aboard a hijacked bus five days ago
police said at least one guerrilla was killed and eight wounded in the 10-minute raid
a police spokesman said four israeli jets dive-bombed the bases in four runs that began at 2:30 p.m
black smoke billowed from the stricken targets at the villages of ashrafiyeh, minyeh, qraiyeh and ein el-dilb on the southern and southeastern edges of sidon, said the spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity
he said guerrilla defenders opened up with twin-barreled anti-aircraft guns, but no hits were reported
the stricken bases were manned by fighters from fatah, the mainline guerrilla group headed by palestine liberation organization chairman yasser arafat, the spokesman said
an israeli military communique said the planes struck in the early afternoon at installations used by guerrillas to plan attacks against targets inside israel
it said the targets were demolished and all the planes returned safely to base. it gave no other details
ambulances, their sirens wailing, raced to the bombed villages and evacuated casualties to hospitals in sidon, 25 miles south of beirut
on monday, in the latest attack inside israel, arab guerrillas hijacked a commuter bus carrying workers from the israeli dimona nuclear plant in southern israel
three israeli civilians were killed and eight wounded in the hijacking, which ended when israeli troops stormed the vehicle. three arab gunmen were killed in the shootout
fatah, the largest plo guerrilla faction, had claimed responsibility for the hijacking
saturday's air raid was the second such attack on palestinian targets in lebanon this year
twelve israeli warplanes carried out a rare nighttime attack jan. 2 against bases manned by fatah guerrillas and fighters of the syrian-backed popular front for the liberation of palestine-general command
twenty-one people were killed and 30 wounded in that attack, six weeks after a popular front guerrilla, flying a motorized hang-glider, infiltrated from lebanon and attacked an army base in northern israel
six israeli soldiers were killed and eight wounded before the guerrilla was killed on nov. 25
the syria-backed group leads an anti-arafat camp within the plo. it is headed by former syrian army captain, ahmad jibril, and is based in damascus
a soccer player who witnessed a deadly stadium collapse in the libyan capital last week said he thought tripoli had been hit by an earthquake
suddenly there was a rumble ... and then the bodies fell down,'' maltese player john buttigieg told the rome daily il messaggero in an interview published saturday
part of the grandstand collapsed thursday after some of the 60,000 spectators at the 75,000-seat june 11 stadium panicked because of a knife fight, according to reports
news reports from malta and yugoslavia said 20 people were killed and that scores of people were injured. radio malta in a report from tripoli said at least 17 people died and that two people were arrested
the reports conflicted with those from the libyan news agency jana, which said two people were killed and 16 others were hospitalized
buttigieg said at first he ``screamed like a madman'' at his team captain that it was an earthquake
the grandstand in front of me was coming down like a sand castle and the fans ... fell by the tens, by the hundreds,'' buttigieg was quoted as saying
three years ago i saw on television the scene at heysel, but in tripoli it was worse, much worse,'' he added, referring to the may 1985 riot by english fans at brussels' heysel stadium that killed 39 people
after a part of the third tier of seats, the highest, fell on the second tier, it was hell. there was a continuous scream ... i saw people run toward the dead,'' he said
the referee told us to go into the dressing rooms. but we couldn't. the entrance was blocked by bodies and pieces of cement,'' he said
the belgrade daily politika ekspres said the incident began when several fans pulled out knives during a quarrel
seeking shelter nearby, spectators toppled an iron fence. at the same time, a 6-foot-thick, 15-foot-high wall crashed down, the newspaper said
the paper said many people were injured when fans stampeded toward the exits
people began to enter the field,'' said buttigieg. ``they ran toward the collapsed grandstand. perhaps they wanted to help the injured, but no, they wanted to fight. with whom, i do not know.''
politika exspres said about 5,000 fans chased those who had brandished weapons. one of them was caught, but police managed to drag him free from the enraged crowd, it said
the maltese paper l'orizzont reported that libyan leader col. moammar gadhafi had planned to attend the match, which opened a sports festival in tripoli. however, at the last moment he changed his mind and was represented at the match by a city official
the exhibition game was stopped in the 43rd minute and did not resume
mats and margareta johansson won a car worth $10,000 on a tv game show, but the couple found out they may have to pay $8,300 in taxes on the prize, a newspaper said saturday
the newspaper aftonbladet said the johanssons took it for granted that ford fiesta was a tax-free prize. they won it last fall on the popular quiz game, ``the card is played,'' on sweden's publicly-owned television
the report said the couple was seeking exemption from tax on the prize with the national swedish tax board
sweden's taxes are among the highest in the world and can take a bite of 70 percent to 80 percent of earnings on an average salary
president reagan warned house and senate negotiators saturday he will veto a trade bill they are preparing unless ``protectionist and defeatist'' provisions are eliminated
the conference committee working on the final draft of the bill has already eliminated a number of troublesome provisions, including illegal quotas, budget-busting giveaways and protectionist measures,'' reagan said from camp david, md., in his weekly radio address
he added, however, that he opposes many remaining provisions, and ``i'm hopeful within the next phase these will be jettisoned. only wholesale elimination of many of the existing items will produce a bill i can sign.''
the trade bill, a 1,000-page set of provisions that have been worked on for three years, is currently the subject of negotiations involving no fewer than 17 congressional committees
one of the casualties of the process has been a controversial, house-passed amendment that would have required 10 percent annual rollbacks in ``excess and unwarranted'' japanese surpluses in trade with this country
reagan expressed a willingness to work with congress to produce a bill he could sign
a protectionist trade bill is a serious threat to our export boom,'' reagan said. ``it's a serious threat to the millions of american jobs that depend upon international trade. it is filled with scores of provisions that are protectionist and defeatist.''
my veto pen is ready if the final bill remains anti-trade, anti-consumer, anti-jobs and anti-growth,'' he said
with an improvement in trade in recent months, he said, a protectionist trade bill ``would be like closing the barn door just when the horse is trying to get back in.''
much of the recent narrowing of the u.s. trade deficit has been credited to a decline in the value of the dollar against foreign currencies, making american goods less expensive overseas
reagan said, however, that since the third quarter of 1986, the merchandise trade deficit in real terms has declined 18 percent and the volume of exports has grown four times as fast as the volume of imports in the past 15 months
adopting protectionist measures and starting trade wars now would be like closing the barn door just as the horses tried to get back in,'' he said
lawmakers have said they want to have the bill ready by easter. in recent weeks, quotas on lamb imports and payments to sugar refiners hurt by imports have been stripped from the legislation by the senate conferees
sen. jeff bingaman, d-n.m., in his party's weekly radio speech, said reagan's upbeat comments about exports ``hides our trade deficit problem _ staggering figures which are monthly reminders that america is not the economic power that it was.''
the 1987 trade deficit was about $170 billion
here is the text of president reagan's radio address, delivered saturday from camp david, md
my fellow americans, i'd like to talk to you today about our nation's trade policy. i can't think of a recent economic issue that has generated more heat and less light, yet has more importance to our long-term national interest than trade
throughout the seven years i've been in office, professional doom sayers have latched onto one issue after another as evidence of an american decline. they can't seem to acknowledge the obvious good news that surrounds us _ the low inflation, the over 15 million new jobs since november 1982, and the longest peacetime economic expansion of the century
trade is only the most recent subject of lamentation by our critics. for them our trade deficit is an excuse for getting the government more involved in in private business. they say that americans can't compete with foreign workers, so we should slow imports by erecting protectionist trade barriers
as usual the doom merchants are wrong. the u.s. economy remains the most dynamic and exciting one on the globe. our entrepreneurs, our can-do spirit and our economic freedom are the envy of the world. the pessimism used to justify protectionism is totally unfounded. let's clear up a few myths
first, the trade situation is improving far more quickly than people realize. economists may disagree on the impact of the trade imbalance, but there is no disagreement that there has been a remarkable turnaround in the real trade deficit
since the third quarter of 1986, the merchandise trade deficit in real terms has declined 18 percent, and over the past 15 months, the volume of exports has grown over four-times as fast as the volume of imports. clearly we are in an export boom. american industries, particularly manufacturers are setting records
unfortunately there's a threat to all this good news. i'm talking about the trade bill pending in congress. adopting protectionist measures and starting trade wars now would be like closing the barn door just as the horses tried to get back in. the best way to keep our exports growing is to keep international trade expanding, and that brings me to another myth _ that congress can pass a law that will reduce the trade deficit without destroying our prosperity. legislation can reduce a trade deficit only if it reduces economic activity. if people are not working, they're not trading. we had a trade surplus and 25 percent unemployment in the great depression
a protectionist trade bill is a serious threat to our export boom. it's a serious threat to the millions of american jobs that depend upon international trade. it is filled with scores of provisions that are protectionist and defeatist. my veto pen is ready if the final bill remains anti-trade, anti-consumer, anti-jobs and anti-growth. however, the administration is willing to work diligently with congress to produce a bill that would increase our international competitiveness and complement our efforts to promote trade, exports, jobs and productivity, not stymie them
all those working on the bill should take a deep breath, take another look at the trade outlet and work together in a constructive spirit. it is still possible to write a bill that i can sign
indeed, i am encouraged by reports on the status of the trade bill negotiations. the conference committee working on the final draft of the bill has already eliminated a number of troublesome provisions, including illegal quotas, budget-busting giveaways and protectionist measures. many objectionable provisions remain, including procedural changes in the law. but i'm hopeful within the next phase these will be jettisoned. only wholesale elimination of many of the existing items will produce a bill i can sign
regardless of whether i sign trade legislation this year, we will continue our free and fair approach to trade policy. we will challenge unfair trade practices of other countries in order to achieve a level playing field for american industries. we will negotiate to knock down trade barriers on a bilateral or multilateral basis. in that regard, we will seek early enactment of the u.s.-canada free trade agreement and push for concrete progress in the upcoming uruguay round of trade negotiations
finally, we will continue to coordinate economic policies with our major trading partners, thereby helping to maintain a favorable international climate for trade expansion. america's open market is its great strength, not its weakness. international trade has helped bring unparalleled prosperity to the american people. it would be a tragic mistake to surrender to doubt and defeatism, just when our prospects are looking so bright. i have confidence in america, and i'm sure you do, too
until next week, thanks for listening, and god bless you
in an atmosphere of deepening crisis, panama's leaders met again saturday to figure out how to pay the 130,000 public employees whose salaries come due early this week
with its treasury virtually empty, the government reportedly was considering delaying or reducing the semi-monthly paychecks of the workers who have been among its staunchest supporters
panama's new chief of state, manuel solis palma, and his cabinet have been meeting almost constantly since thursday evening in an effort to solve the problem, which could have strong political repercussions
it became even more critical friday when the reagan administration in washington announced new economic sanctions against panama, including the withholding of $6.5 million in monthly panama canal fees
the sanctions were meant to force the ouster of gen. manuel antonio noriega, who has ruled panama since 1983 as head of its defense forces. he is under indictment in the united states on drug smuggling and money laundering charges
with solis palma and the foreign minister, jorge abadia, tied up in the emergency economic meetings, the government saturday still had not responded formally to the punitive measures taken in washington
but boris moreno, head of the government's national information office, referred to the sanctions as ``economic aggression'' and an ``outrage'' and said they had created a virtual ``state of war.''
this means that if the united states government does not like the government of another country, it can withhold any funds deposited in the united states,'' he said
panama uses the u.s. dollar as its currency and even before the latest sanctions were announced washington had halted normal transfers of funds from the u.s. federal reserve. other monies on deposit by panama in private u.s. banks also have been tied up by legal actions
panama's 118 local and foreign banks were ordered closed until further notice on march 3 because the government could not provide enough money to cover withdrawals. most had already shut down or were operating on a limited basis because of a run on deposits that began late last month
the bank closure left thousands of people and businesses holding checks they could not cash. in the absence of cash, most people were hoarding the dollars they had and many businessmen said they were working out barter deals with suppliers and customers
eric arturo delvalle, the deposed president whose ouster last month sparked the current crisis, predicted earlier this week that the government's inability to pay its employees would ``add a new political dimension'' to the problem
delvalle made the statement from hiding. he has not been seen in public since shortly after noriega engineered his ouster in a thinly disguised coup that came only hours after he tried to dismiss the general. the united states still recognizes delvalle as panama's legitimate president
an avalanche on mount crevacol in northern italy killed two swiss skiers saturday afternoon, authorities said
the italian news agency ansa said authorities had not released the names of the victims, who were skiing with two other friends when they were buried by the snowslide
here is the text of the democratic party's response, by sen. jeff bingaman of new mexico, to president reagan's radio address on saturday:
in one respect, the president has done our country a great service. in 1981, when he took office, we were not feeling good about ourselves. there was the iran-hostage crisis, there was runaway inflation
by 1984, the president's rhetoric had helped us to feel proud of america once again. and that good feeling hit its height in the summer of 1984 at the summer olympic games in los angeles. the president had reminded all americans that we are a proud people
but now that ``feel-good'' rhetoric is becoming a problem in itself. the president insists that the economy is in great shape, and that america has never been better off. but the truth is, that we have seen feel-good rhetoric used to paper over the very real problems that challenge our country. and that's not the way americans work
as americans, we pride ourselves in solving our problems, not in papering them over. the real issue that the president's feel-good rhetoric ignores is what kind of america are we leaving for our children. what standard of living will our children have? will they realize the american dream the way that we've been able to? will our children ever be as well off as we have been?
the president's rhetoric hides the fact that wage rates today are below what they were 15 years ago. it hides the fact that the new service sector jobs that have been created pay about half as much as the manufacturing jobs they replace. it hides the fact that both parents in most of america's young families have to work, and they have to work whether there are young children to take care of or not
it hides the fact that fewer and fewer young american families can afford to buy their own house today. and it hides the fact that the wages of our young families make it virtually impossible for them to save _ save for hard times, save for a down payment on a house, or save for their children's education
the president's rhetoric also hides our trade deficit problem _ staggering figures, which are monthly reminders that america is not the economic power that we once were. it hides the fact that during this administration, as a country we have added $1.5 trillion to the national debt. that means that in 1989, we will spend more on interest payments in the national debt than on the total combined budgets of the departments of agriculture, commerce, education, energy, interior, labor and justice
these interest payments consume precious funds which will not be spent on rebuilding america's economic power, and will not be spent on educating our children
mr. president, you have reminded us that we are a great country and that we are proud to be americans. but we are now ready to get to work solving some of those very real problems that exist. it does not help to pretend that the problems don't exist
it does not help to stay the course when the course has taken us into the ditch. we're ready to invest the time, money and energy in revitalizing the american economy. we're ready to fight unfair trade practices
we're ready to create new jobs which pay more than the ones that they replace. we're ready to make specific investments in education and retraining of our workers, in new research and development, and in the commercialization of new technologies. and we're also ready to reverse our growing dependence on foreign sources of energy. also we're ready to invest the time, money and energy in the education of our children
instead of lecturing our children's teachers, we're ready to do our part to help make our educational system work, work better and work harder. we're ready to do what has to be done to prepare our children to take the good jobs that this country can create in an economic revitalization program. mr. president, feeling good and staying the course just are not doing the job
a proud america means an america that can recognize its challenges and meet those challenges head-on. only if we do so will our children be as proud to be americans 20 years from now as we are today. this is u.s. sen. jeff bingaman. thank you for listening
some hunters develop stuffy noses, wheezing and hives around deer in what one researcher calls a case of ``bambi strikes back,'' and some people are literally allergic to exercise, scientists have found
research also shows that cockroaches often prompt asthmatics to wheeze, while fleas make others sneeze, the scientists say
their studies of unusual, often unrecognized and potentially deadly allergies are being presented during the american academy of allergy and immunology's annual meeting, which opened friday and ends wednesday
the prevalence of such allergies is unknown, but the studies suggest they probably are more common than once thought, especially among people with common allergies, such as sensitivity to pollens, household dust and foods such as peanuts and shellfish
there's all kind of weird triggers to allergies,'' said dr. robert k. bush, a university of wisconsin allergist and chief of allergy at the veterans administration hospital in madison. bush co-authored the study of 12 deer-sensitive wisconsin hunters with dr. david schroeckenstein
this may not be real common,'' bush said of the hunters' deer dilemma. ``but there are certainly a lot of people who get exposed to these animals, and the potential is there for them to become allergic.''
most of the hunters suffered congestion, hives, asthma, sneezing, runny noses, itchy eyes, and swollen eyelids and lips after inhaling deer hair or touching the animals' hair, saliva, blood or urine. one was a state ``deer checker'' who went into allergic shock after cutting his hand on a tag he placed on a deer. the man recovered
poor bambi gets shot. then bambi strikes back. that's a good headline,'' bush said
the allergy academy's president, dr. albert sheffer of harvard university medical school, co-authored the largest study to date of exercise-induced allergic shock, which was first recognized in 1969 and is ``characterized by hives, choking and-or a life-threatening drop in blood pressure and loss of consciousness.''
sheffer concluded that while the condition is rare, ``it's the most common physical allergy,'' even more common than hives induced by heat or cold
the study, outlined saturday by harvard's dr. john wade, analyzed a group of 199 people who develop allergic shock, called anaphylaxis, when they exercise
jogging prompted shock in 71 percent of the patients, aerobics in 38 percent, dancing in 26 percent and swimming in 17 percent. many were allergic to certain foods, pollen, cat dander, aspirin and other painkillers
the cause of exercise allergy is unknown. while exercise-induced shock is life-threatening, ``we don't have any evidence anybody died from it,'' sheffer said
dr. bann kang, head of the allergy section at the university of kentucky medical center in lexington, said her study of 680 asthmatics in chicago found 283 of them were allergic to body parts, eggs and feces of cockroaches in house dust, an allergy first identified in new york in 1967
they usually have very severe, intractable asthma,'' she said. ``they have attacks all the time.''
because many doctors don't recognize cockroach asthma, they only treat symptoms, then ``send the patient back home, where the home is filled with material that may induce asthma attacks again,'' kang said
while flea bites are known to cause hives, a new study revealed fleas' body parts inhaled from house dust also trigger allergic reactions, said the study's author, research associate walter trudeau of the university of south florida school of medicine and the veterans administration hospital in tampa
trudeau's study found 18 of 100 consecutive patients treated at an allergy clinic for other allergies also were allergic to fleas that invaded their homes aboard their cats or dogs
desensitization injections can eliminate allergies to pollens, house dust and cockroaches, but there is no effective serum to desensitize people allergic to deer, fleas or exercise, the researchers said
people allergic to fleas should get rid of their pets, or at least exterminate the fleas, trudeau said. hunters allergic to deer should stop hunting if necessary, bush said
people prone to develop exercise-induced allergic shock ``should not exercise for at least four to six hours after eating,'' since exercise allergy often causes symptoms only if allergenic foods were consumed, sheffer said
a federal judge has grounded air panama's u.s. operations, freezing the company's assets while he decides which leader of panama should control the government-owned airline
basically the airline is out of service,'' said mark cohen, the miami attorney who sued to seize air panama's assets on behalf of eric delvalle, panama's president-in-hiding
u.s. district judge william hoeveler on friday issued a 10-day restraining order freezing the airline's assets while he considers which panamanian government should control the company _ delvalle or ruling military stongman gen. manuel antonio noriega
noriega was indicted last month on drug trafficking charges by federal grand juries in tampa and miami. soon afterward, delvalle ordered noriega to resign, but the panamanian assembly backed noriega and ousted delvalle
each man contends he is panama's legitimate ruler; the united states recognizes only delvalle's claim
attorneys for air panama did not attend the hearing but responded to hoeveler's questions by telephone
an air panama reservations clerk in miami said saturday that no air panama officials would be available until monday
air panama's assets in the united states include two boeing 727 jets, ground equipment and facilities, tickets that can be exchanged for cash and an undetermined amount of money in u.s. banks, cohen said
peter reaveley, head of the aviation development department at miami international airport, said curtailment of air panama service should not have much of an impact on travel to the central american nation
business and tourist travel to panama has already been drying up,'' he said
air panama has been flying once daily from miami to panama city. eastern airlines and pan american airways also have daily service there
florence ann felton doesn't monkey around when there is a baby beast in need at her husband's zoo _ she takes the critters home
felton, whose husband george felton is the director of the greater baton rouge zoo, can't bear it when the animals become orphaned or rejected by their natural mothers. ``i love them,'' she said of her furry patients
the babies, though, are exotic _ wild. they do not make good pets,'' mrs. felton said
i've raised them on bottles, but i know they have to go back,'' she said
the main problem is getting them on a bottle,'' she added. ``once they're on a bottle, it's no problem.''
the feltons live near the zoo in a home that has been modified for easy care of baby animals
they have raised chimps, bears, cougars, otters, leopards, jaguars, small deer, antelope and other hoofed stock, baboons, monkeys, lions, and tigers
baby beasts must be fed every two hours, with feedings spread out gradually. mrs. felton said animal babies got her up more often during the night than did her own children, all of whom are now on their own
do the animals ever remember her?
some do, she said. two young cougars she once helped raise would stand up at the zoo with their paws on the wire, trying to get her to scratch their noses
ashland women deny they are ladies of leisure, despite a recent report saying there are fewer of them in work force than anywhere else in the country
the 1988 congressional district fact book said only 31.6 percent of the northeastern kentucky women are employed, while the national average for working women was 54.7 percent in 1986
but some members of the american business women's association in ashland dispute the finding
i've got three daughters and two daughters-in-law and they all work,'' said margaret moore. ``i've worked all my life. all the women i know work.''
helen hunt, vice president of the association, said she doesn't think ashland is much different than any other area
usually women can find work here quicker than men,'' she said
on the other hand, prince georges county, md. topped the list of working women with 62.6 percent; arlington, va., was second with 62.2 percent, and bloomington, minn., ranked third at 62.2 percent, the book said
ranking slightly above ashland are huntington, w.va., 31.9 percent; washington, pa., 36.2 percent, and the economically depressed south bronx section of new york city, 36.5 percent, the book said
the book was published by the joint center for political studies, a washington, d.c., think tank, which used u.s. census data to determine its rankings
one explanation for the small percentage of working women in ashland might be that males traditionally have held the high-paying jobs at large local employers such as ashland oil and armco inc
perhaps it wasn't necessary for women to work in some situations,'' said mike sturm, employment and training program supervisor with the kentucky department of employment services in ashland
the chicago tribune endorsed tennessee sen. albert gore in tuesday's illinois presidential primary, passing over homestate candidates sen. paul simon and jesse jackson
the tribune endorsement in sunday editions called gore ``an underdog with sound judgment and an important message.''
the chicago sun-times, the state's second largest newspaper after the tribune, has endorsed massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in the democratic race and vice president george bush in the republican primary
the endorsement is offered in the same spirit as our earlier endorsement of sen. robert dole in the republican primary _ in hopes that an underdog with sound judgment and an important message can pick up momentum in illinois and contest his party's nomination all the way to its convention,'' said the tribune editorial
the tribune conducted a poll for sunday's editions that showed simon was favored by 35 percent of those surveyed, jackson 30 percent and dukakis 18 percent. gore and gephardt had a combined total of about 10 percent
among the likely republican voters, bush was supported by 62 percent and dole by 28 percent. robertson was the first choice of only 6 percent
the survey, conducted by peter d. hart research associates, contacted 504 republicans and 501 democrats on wednesday and thursday and had a margin of error of 5 percentage points
the tribune endorsement said gore was the only candidate who could ``prevent the democatic debate from winding down into the staid pronouncements of ... dukakis .... and the jazzier echo of the class-conscious mr. jackson.''
the tribune gave gore high marks on his knowledge of domestic and foreign affairs and also warned the democratic party it needed ``a strong gore candidacy just to avoid a repeat in november of its 1980 and 1984 humiliations.''
dukakis leads in the race for delegates to the party's national nominating convention, followed by jackson and gore. missouri rep. richard gephardt is fourth and simon is last, although there are more uncommitted delegates than simon and gephardt have together. job-related illness</head>
some 65,000 americans a year develop lung diseases from on-the-job causes, making lung disease the most common preventable cause of job-related illness and death in the country, the american lung association said saturday
long-term exposure to cancer-causing substances in the workplace, for example, is blamed for about 16,000 lung cancer deaths a year, the association said in its 1987 annual report
that is about 12 percent of the nation's total lung cancer deaths last year, the association said
among the workplace substances that cause lung cancer are arsenic, a hazard in the oil refining, smelting and mining industries; asbestos, in asbestos milling and manufacture, insulation and shipyard work; chromium, used in glassmaking, potting and battery making; nickel, in nickel refining, and petroleum products and oils, the association said
not everyone in those industries is exposed to those substances, however, the association noted
other job-related lung diseases include chronic bronchitis, a stiffening of lung tissue called pulmonary fibrosis and industrial asthma, the association said
on other topics, the annual report said smokers who kick the habit have to wait 10 years or more before their risk of lung cancer falls to about that of people who have never smoked
but that should not discourage smokers from quitting, because quitting causes an immediate and dramatic plunge in the risk of other diseases, especially emphysema and chronic bronchitis, the report says
the report also calls lung cancer statistics on blacks ``horrendous,'' resulting from higher percentages of smokers among black men and women than among whites
in 1985, about 41 percent of black men aged 20 and older smoked, compared to about 32 percent for white men, while about 32 percent of black women smoked, compared to 28 percent of white women, the association said
from 1973 to 1984, the lung cancer death rate among black men rose 25 percent, from 64.3 deaths per 100,000 population to 80.3, three times faster than the rate among white men, the association said in a separate statement
for black women the death rate nearly doubled, from 11.9 per 100,000 population to 20.4, the association said. wounded</head> pvs: `an airport...'</note>
a man waving a pistol rushed the cockpit of a passenger jet saturday and demanded the pilot fly him to india or afghanistan, then shot a guard three times before passengers pummeled and subdued him
the pakistan international airlines jet was carrying 143 passengers and 13 crew members on a domestic flight from karachi to quetta when the attempted hijacking took place about seven minutes before landing, said app, the pakistani national news agency
the hijacker also reportedly suffered a gunshot wound during the scuffle with the guard and passengers. there were no other injuries and the aircraft landed safely, the news agency said
the news agency said a man identified as mannan achakzai, 28, from the baluchistan province was arrested. it said two other passengers also were detained as suspected accomplices, but had no details
the plane, an a-300 airbus, was preparing to land at quetta in baluchistan, near the afghan border in western pakistan
app said a man from the first-class section apparently went to the bathroom, then returned shortly afterward with a revolver and rushed toward the the cockpit
the gunmen shouted at the pilot to divert the aircraft to either the afghan capital of kabul or to new delhi, app said. it gave no information on the gunman's motive
a guard on the aircraft, liaquat ali, tried to overpower the gunman but was shot three times in the back
two passengers ``jumped on the hijacker and unleashed a volley of blows and punches,'' app said. officials identified the two passengers as provincial government ministers masir mengal and mohammad rind
an airport official who spoke on condition of anonymity said that achakzai was wounded by a bullet fired from his own revolver during the scuffle
two doctors, one pakistani and one dutch, were on board the plane and administered aid to the guard and gunmen, app said
it was a miracle that the air guard survived although he was hit thrice,'' dr. louis koster, a dutch physician who was on board the flight, was quoted as saying. ``fortunately, none of the bullets could pierce through any vital organ.''
airport security is extremely heavy in pakistan and airport officials could not explain how the gun was brought on board. passengers must pass through two metal detectors and have their carry-on luggage inspected at least three times before boarding
here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from south carolina to attend the 1988 democratic and republican national conventions this summer
method: caucus
date: saturday, march 12
candidates filed: bruce babbitt, michael dukakis, richard gephardt, albert gore, gary hart, jesse jackson, paul simon
pledged delegates: 44 super elegates: 4 total: 48
delegates allocated: saturday, march 12
selection of delegates: saturday, april 16

south carolina uses a three-step process of caucuses and conventions for picking its delegates to the democratic national convention
precinct caucuses on march 12 pick delegates to the county conventions later in the month, which name delegates to the state convention on april 16. partricipants at each step of the process will be divided according to presidential preferences and are pledged from one level to the next
twenty-nine pledged national convention delegates from congressional districts will be chosen and allocated in congressional district caucuses at the state convention. the rest of the state's 15 pledged national convention delegates will be chosen at the state convention and will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to presidential preference expressed by state convention delegates
method: primary
date: saturday, march 5
delegates: 37
delegates allocated: saturday, march 5
selection of delegates: saturday, april 9

south carolina republicans awarded all of their national convention delegates to vice president george bush in a winner-take-all primary on march 5
the delegates from congressional districts will be picked at district conventions in the next few weeks
the at-large delegates will named at the state convention in april. 3rd graf pvs: about 150...</note>
tibetan women set fire to a chinese flag and demanded freedom for their homeland on saturday, vowing to return to the region they fled nearly three decades ago
in london, about 50 tibetan demonstrators protested outside the chinese embassy. there was no response from the embassy and police maintained a discreet watch on the demonstrators, who ended their vigil without incident
in switzerland, about 400 tibetans carried banners that said ``china out of tibet,'' and ``long live the dalai lama'' on a peaceful march through zurich's inner city
about 150 tibetan refugees participated in the new delhi demonstration, one of the latest last week to mark the 29th anniversary of an unsuccessful uprising against chinese rule in the tibetan capital of lhasa
the pride and might of communist china will not crush the spirit of tibetan nationalism,'' the tibetan women's organization, which organized the new delhi protest, said in statement
indian policewomen stood by and watched the tibetan women burn the red flag of china near parliament
tsewang topgyal, a spokesman for the demonstrators, fled his country at the age of 5 in the wake of the violent revolt in 1959. he said ``this anniversary is like christmas for tibetans. it is a time when we remember family and friends at home
there are few tibetans who have not lost members of their immediate family due to the chinese presence there,'' he said
on march 10, 1959, tibetans revolted against their chinese rulers, who responded with a brutal crackdown. india is the home of at least 100,000 tibetan refugees who fled tibet along with their leader, the dalai lama
the anniversary of the tibetan revolt coincides with an upsurge in anti-chinese rioting in lhasa
an official report said one policeman was killed in daylong clashes march 5 between police and protesters in lhasa, but unconfirmed reports put casualties at 21 tibetans and three police killed
during three independence protests in september and october, at least 14 people were killed and dozens arrested
the world's birthrate will begin declining within the next 12 years for the first time in recorded history, a group of development experts said saturday
this will be a momentous occasion in the history of the world,'' said dr. william foege, director of the task force for child survival and former head of the centers for disease control in atlanta
scientists attending the task force's three-day international symposium here agreed that new projections from developing countries show that the birthrate should stop growing nearly a half century earlier than demographers previously thought possible
that would be followed by the stabilization of the entire population, said foege, an epidemiologist who conducted the birthrate study. the birthrate is the number of births per 1,000 population
dr. kenneth warren, a vaccines expert and head of the health unit of the rockefeller foundation, said: ``people have considered that world population growth would continue indefinitely. the question has been, is man going to overrun and destroy the whole planet? it's something people have been despairing about.''
the task force for child survival is a coalition that includes unicef, the u.n. children's fund, the world health organization, more than a dozen international aid agencies and doctors and health ministers from 11 developing countries
the organizations have been working on an international campaign to immunize children against polio, diphtheria, tuberculosis and other diseases in a project aimed primarily at developing nations
the common perception that low infant mortality causes population increases is apparently incorrect, said warren
actually, a low death rate for infants actually causes populations to stabilize. industrialized countries such as the united states have relatively low birthrates
experts at the conference said asian and latin american countries now are following this trend. an increasing number of countries are weighing in with lower birth rates
the experts said women in poor countries are likely to have larger families to offset the loss of children to disease
foege, using data from the world bank, examined trends in infant mortality and birthrates from 1960 to the present and projected infant mortality by nation through 2000
if we're wrong, we're only wrong by a few years, the concept isn't wrong,'' foege said, adding that his predictions of the anticipated drop int he birthrate could have an error margin of five years
previous predictions have indicated that the birthrate would stabilize midway through the next century, when the population reaches about 13 billion
if foege's projections are correct, the population would stop growing at about the year 2150
because of increased life expectancy and other factors, the population level will take at least several decades to level off after the birthrate stops growing
there's full agreement on the prediction,'' said james p. grant, executive director of unicef. ``with the kinds of improvements in survival we've been talking about at this meeting, the decline could come even sooner.''
the birthrate prediction made at on the last day of the symposium was part of an optimistic appraisal of the progress made in improving health care and the potential to extend life for children worldwide
the drug enforcement administration, at the invitation of bolivia, peru and ecuador, has been assisting an offensive aimed at south american cocaine-processing facilities and growing areas that was first tried with u.s. military troops amid much controversy in 1986
under the initiative, dea officials say, specially trained u.s. drug agents with the assistance of aircraft from the agency are accompanying bolivian military forces into the jungles of that country and locating cocaine processing laboratories, which are then dismantled by the troops
the effort, begun last year, is a continuation and broadening of operation blast furnace in 1986, dea spokesman cornelius dougherty said. in blast furnace, 170 u.s. army personnel raided about 20 drug lab sites in bolivia. the injection of u.s. troops drew criticism from civil liberties groups concerned about the use of the military to enforce civilian laws
the new operation doesn't involve u.s. military personnel
we're working with the governments in the primary coca-growing countries of peru and bolivia, where they are using their troops and we are sending along dea advisers as intelligence experts,'' dougherty said
the agents have undergone extensive training in weapons, language and jungle survival, in addition to the regular 14 weeks of field training dea agents take. the jungle survival training is given by the u.s. army special forces, the green berets
as part of the effort, dea planes outfitted with sophisticated electronic gear are being used for aerial reconnaissance to identify drug labs
in peru, dea agents began in mid-1987 to help immobilize and disrupt the flow of cocaine products from the principal area of that country where illicit coca is cultivated, the upper huallaga valley. extensive production of coca paste and cocaine base also takes place there, david l. westrate, assistant dea administrator for operations, said in congressional testimony earlier this month
partly as a result of the effort, there have been substantial seizures of coca leaves, cocaine base and chemicals used in producing coca paste and base, westrate said
under an agreement made in 1987 with bolivia, dea agents helped the government there locate and destroy numerous coca processing facilities. a total of 26 labs for producing coca base or refining it were seized last year in bolivia, westrate said
dea agents also are taking a more active role in ecuador, a transit country for large amounts of chemicals used in processing cocaine in other south american countries, dea officials said. most of the coca paste produced in ecuador is transported to colombia for conversion to cocaine hydrochloride. words. pick up 7th pvs, `al-amaya has...'</note>
iraq said saturday its jets hit a tanker in the persian gulf and an oil pumping station on the iranian mainland, indicating a return of hostilities to economic targets during a truce in the ``war of the cities.''
but iran later accused iraq of violating the truce by sending a warplane to bomb the town of gachsaran in southwestern iran
tehran television, monitored in cyprus, quoted a spokesman for the war information headquarters as saying the plane was ``forced to flee under heavy anti-aircraft fire.''
he said the aircraft was seen ``dropping it bombs out of frustration in a desert area.''
the unidentified spokesman said the incident ``indicates iraq wants to continue its acts of mischief, and the islamic combatants will not remain silent if civilian targets are attacked again.'' iraq did not comment on the report
iran's islamic republic news agency, monitored in cyprus, earlier reported that revolutionary guards attacked and set ablaze the offshore al-amaya radar facility in the northern tip of the gulf friday night
al-amaya had been transformed by the iraqis from an oil platform to monitor activity in the gulf. irna said surface-to-air and shore-to-sea missile pads on the facility were destroyed in the attack
the official iraqi news agency, also monitored in cyprus, reported that iraqi warplanes blasted the imam hassan oil pumping station in southwestern iran saturday afternoon
the agency quoted an unidentified iraqi military spokesman as saying the facility was ``totally destroyed.''
in an earlier dispatch, iraq reported to have struck a ``very large maritime target'' off the iranian coast friday night. the attack was not independently verified by gulf-based shipping executives
ina quoted a military spokesman as saying the iraqi warplanes scored ``an accurate and effective hit'' on the vessel, and returned safely
it quoted a spokesman as saying the raids reflected iraq's ``determination to destroy iran's economic lifeline and deprive the enemy of revenues employed to finance aggression.''
the cease-fire in the ``war of the cities'' passed the 24-hour mark, with no attacks on each other's capitals or major population centers
hundreds of civilian casualties were reported in the unprecedented 12-day duel. iraq claimed to have hurled 71 long-range missiles into tehran and two other cities and iran said it fired 29 missiles at iraqi cities
the barrage ended friday afternoon after iraq fired eight rockets at tehran and three at the holy city of qom, the last one just 16 minutes before the 4 p.m. truce deadline
iraq had made its right to fire the last shot a precondition for the truce, on grounds that iran, the ``aggressive party,'' had triggered the exchange
iraq's terms for the cease-fire also stipulated that tehran not attempt to launch a ground offensive against any iraqi population centers
it did not bar either side from continuing to attack military or economically strategic targets
ali ahani, director general of european and american affairs of iran's foreign ministry, speaking in the hague, netherlands, said iran will unleash a new battlefront offensive against iraq in response to the missile attacks
we are going to give a decisive response in the war of the fronts because of this bloodshed,'' he said, refusing to provide specifics on the offensive
baghdad's officially controlled press called the cease-fire a triumph and warned iran against resuming the bombardment, ina said
al-thawra, voice of iraq's ruling arab baath socialist party, said the missile war taught the ``charlatans of iran'' a ``painful, bitter lesson.'' it said any iranian ``violation'' of the cease-fire ``would, for sure, generate a devastating iraqi reply.''
iraq had vowed to disrupt oil exports by which iran finances its share of the 7{-year-old war. the attacks concentrate on iran's government-owned or chartered tankers that shuttle oil from kharg island in the northern gulf to centers in safer waters near the strait of hormuz
iraq broke a three-week lull in the ``tanker war'' on wednesday, when its warplanes struck the 41,195-ton maltese-flag tanker tenacity
baghdad reported another attack on friday, which like the one it claimed on saturday, could not be confirmed
the iranians retaliate for iraqi raids with attacks on neutral commercial shipping. although gulf radio monitors say iranian gunboats were actively challenging ships in the southern gulf in recent days, there have been no attacks since feb. 11
indications arose of a new potential threat to shipping in the southern gulf, where iran was reported by u.s. military sources to be building launch pads for its chinese-made silkworm anti-ship missiles on abu musa, a tiny island used as a base by iran's revolutionary guards
the washington-based sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said american intelligence had detected no sign of actual missiles being installed
positioning the weapons, which have a range of 50 miles on abu musa would extend the so-called ``silkworm envelope'' by about 100 miles into the gulf, embracing the busy united arab emirates cities of dubai, sharjah and ras al-khaimah. quotes throughout. picks up 9th graf, `on thursday ...' adds byline.</note>
thousands of soccer fans saturday stampeded into locked stadium exits to escape a sudden hailstorm, killing at least 93 in the crush, witnesses and hospital sources said
gumball-sized ice pellets rained down on the 30,000 fans watching a match between nepalese and bangladeshi teams at the national stadium. eyewitnesses said screaming spectators rushed to the stadium's eight exits but found only one open
police and hospital sources in the city confirmed more than 70 people, including two police officers, were trampled to death or suffocated. government television reported 73 people were killed, and witnesses said another 20 bodies left at the stadium were later retrieved by relatives
more than 100 people were hospitalized with injuries. hospital sources said 12 were in serious condition. many more were were treated and released
at the government-run bir hospital near the stadium, maya laxmi vaidya, a white-haired woman clad in a sari, said her 12-year-old grandson was killed in the stampede
i've told my family not go out on saturday. older people understand this and don't go out,'' she said
the day is considered unlucky among nepal's hindus. it is named for the planet saturn, which in hindu mythology possesses strong negative powers
the government ordered a judicial commission to investigate the disaster and announced payments of $450 to relatives of the dead and $90 to the injured
crowds angered by authorities' failure to open the gates attacked three cars with government license plates outside the stadium with rocks, smashing windshields
reporters who arrived at the stadium moments later found it largely deserted. sandals and shoes littered the ground near the one open gate
witnesses said most of the deaths occurred there, as spectators who found other exits locked rushed toward the only outlet
ram bista, a teletype operator who took part in rescue efforts, said spectators who got outside commandeered vehicles to rush victims to hospitals
we stopped all buses, all taxis, all rickshaws,'' he said
one spectator who demanded anonymity accused police of being ``selfish. they took care of themselves and nobody came to help the crowd,'' he said
it was nepal's worst sports-related disaster on record
the downtown stadium was filled almost to capacity for the final game of a major tournament in nepal's most popular sport. the tribhuvan challenge shield cup, named for a former nepalese king, pitted a team from the national cigarette factory against the mukti joddha, meaning ``freedom fighters,'' from nearby bangladesh
stadium officials said none of the athletes was involved in the stampede or was injured
despite sunshine for most of the day, the storm howled through this himalayan capital at midafternoon, packing winds of more than 50 mph. it uprooted trees throughout katmandu valley and temporarily disrupted telex lines
on thursday evening, panicked soccer fans in tripoli, libya fled knife-wielding ruffians and triggered the collapse of a sports stadium, killing at least 20 people, news reports from malta and yugoslavia said
the reports conflicted with those from the libyan news agency jana, which said two people were killed and 16 were hospitalized
the worst soccer disaster on record took place on may 24, 1964, when rioting left nearly 300 dead and 500 injured after argentina beat peru on a last-minute goal in lima
on may 29, 1985, 39 people died at heysel stadium in brussels, belgium, when british soccer fans went on a rampage against italian fans
fifty-three fans died on may 11, 1985, when a fire engulfed the main stand during a match at bradford city's soccer stadium in northern england
on jan. 2, 1971, 66 people died when an overcrowded stairway collapsed during a local soccer match between glasgow rangers and celtic in glasgow, scotland
in 1969, el salvador and honduras suffered thousands of casualties in the so-called ``soccer war,'' which began after a disputed soccer match between the two countries. the brief war was provoked by honduras' decision to expel many salvadorans who had settled in honduras. up 15th pvs, `sharaa said...'</note>
syria on saturday rejected an american proposal for an arab-israeli peace settlement, submitted last week to arab and israeli leaders by secretary of state george p. shultz
syrian foreign minister farouk al-sharaa also said he did not believe any other arab leader would support the plan
we have studied the american proposal and we think the plan, as presented to us, is not acceptable. we also believe that it is not acceptable to any other arab side,'' sharaa told reporters
the palestine liberation organization and israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir also have rejected the plan. shamir's rival in the coalition government, foreign minister shimon peres, supports the plan
sharaa spoke at damascus airport after seeing off his swedish counterpart, sten andersson. andersson left for home after a 24-hour visit and talks with president hafez assad and sharaa on the arab-israeli conflict
sharaa's statement was the first outright syrian rejection of the plan, which shultz submitted to assad during a visit to damascus march 4
shultz handed copies of the proposal to king hussein of jordan, shamir, peres and egyptian president hosni mubarak
the proposal, aimed primarily at halting violence that has raged in the occupied west bank and gaza strip since dec. 8, called for limited self-rule for 1.5 million palestinians living under israeli occupation
it also called for the formation of a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation to negotiate a permanent settlement in the west bank and gaza under an international peace conference to convene by may 1
at a later parley, other arab-israeli conflicts, including the future of the syrian golan heights, occcupied by israel in the 1967 war, would be discussed
shultz had asked that the leaders concerned respond to his proposal within 10 days
the syrian president, speaking at a rally on tuesday, had indicated he rejected the plan, saying israel did not want peace and that the arabs have no alternative but to keep up the fight against the jewish state
but he did not openly reject the plan
earlier last week, assad discussed the proposal with hussein, the jordanian monarch, during a meeting in damascus
sharaa said ``we hope the american adminstration would come up with a much clearer proposal,'' leaving the door open for additional u.s.-syrian consultations
sharaa said syria would not accept any settlement that is not based on ``the termination of israel's occupation and recognition of palestinian rights'' to self-determination and the establishment of a state. religion</head>
conservative judaism on saturday offered its first comprehensive definition of principles, declaring its faith is linked to israel, but not bound to it
both israel and the diaspora, the countries to which the jews have been dispersed, are partners to ``aid and enrich the other in every possible way,'' the 23,000-word statement said. ``each needs the other.''
however, jewish identity was termed essentially a matter of religion rather than geography
our religion has been land-centered but never land-bound,'' the document said. ``it has been a portable religion so that despite our long exile from our spiritual homeland, we have been able to survive creatively and spiritually.'' ``we do not believe that jewish identity can be replaced by israeli identity, or the ability to speak hebrew. we are convinced that jewish religion is essential as a source of ethical and moral values,'' the authors said
some jews have viewed the jewish state as the ``religious center of world jewry,'' the statement said, adding that various jewish communities have ``complementary roles'' in maintaining judaism
the statement, ``emet ve-emunah,'' hebrew for ``truth and faith,'' was drawn up over 2{ years by a 35-member commission of scholars, rabbis and laity set up in 1985
never before in its history has the century-old conservative movement in this country produced such an overall summation of convictions
officials of the rabbinical assembly, the rabbinical arm of conservative judaism, and its jewish theological seminary hailed the document as ``monumental and historic.''
it provides a consensus view of the movement's ``positions on personal and general questions'' affecting jewish life, said the commission chairman, seminary professor robert gordis
he termed it ``a way of life for the jew today to live in loyalty to the tradition without resigning from the 20th century.''
conservative judaism is the middle ground between the other two major branches, reform, which freely adapts jewish practices to changing times, and orthodoxy, which sees ritual as commanded by god and thus unchangeable
conservatism's statement deals with god, revelation, evil, the messianic hope, jewish law, personal practices, the role of women, israel, social justice, relations with other faiths and meaning of ``chosen people.''
the widely misunderstood ``chosen people'' concept often ``has been distorted into an expression of moral arrogance,'' despite counterefforts, the statement said
instead of implying any innate jewish superiority, god's choosing of the jews to reveal his purposes laid on them special obligations and duties as a result of their accepting that role
far from being a license for special privilege, it entailed additional responsibilities not only toward god but to their fellow human beings,'' the statement said
often, however, they had to pay a bloody price for insisting on this role, enabling them to identify with (the prophet) isaiah's `suffering servant' who accepted the blows and contempt of others in order to bring the truth of god to the world.''
the statement deplored the rifts that have developed among different branches of judaism and urged work to overcome them, declaring:
in the face of unflagging enemies and widespread anti-semitism, jewish unity is more vital than ever. ... only when jews live in harmony and peace with each other ... will we be worthy of messianic redemption.''
regarding israel, the statement voiced deep attachment to the land and pride in the achievement of the modern state in gathering jews from dispersion and ``rebuilding a nation.''
however, the state's discrimination against the conservative and reform movements is ``morally intolerable,'' the statement said
the writers said israel should recognize religious authority of all rabbis, not just the orthodox, adding, ``we have often suffered from discriminatory policies, but we remain firm and loving supporters of the state of israel.''
israel's jews and their fellows living in the diaspora ``have sustained the creative survival of am yisrael (the jewish people),'' interacting ``in a continual symbiotic process of mutual enrichment, the statement said
and conservative judaism offered this self-description:
the conservative movement affirms that the jewish religion as reflected in the jewish way of life constitutes the most significant factor that identifies, distinguishes, unites and preserves the jewish people.'' graf, `redington, who ...,' to update with redington sliding into second place. ^laserphoto ny22</note>
joe redington couldn't run in the first iditarod trail sled dog race in 1973 because he was too busy organizing the 1,100-mile marathon from anchorage to nome
he missed out again in 1983 when a run-in with an angry moose during training left him with a few cracked ribs
but redington, now 70, has run in every other iditarod, a torturous test of people and dogs billed as ``the last great race.'' and as this year's race approached the midpoint near the frozen yukon river, redington was savoring the lead in a contest he has never won
redington, who has finished as high as fifth three times, grabbed the lead tuesday at rohn, 271 miles from the start, and held it until saturday when he slipped into second place at the yukon river town of galena, 452 miles from the finish
i feel like an old fox being chased by 50 young hounds,'' he said
redington earned the title ``father of the iditarod'' 16 years ago when he spearheaded a movement to get alaskans off snowmobiles and back behind the dog teams that traditionally had provided winter transportation across the vast state
to galvanize the mushing revival, he promoted an idea that many thought impossible _ a race along the old iditarod trail, a supply route used earlier this century to reach interior alaska gold mining districts
in 1925, dog teams relayed diphtheria serum along the trail to the epidemic-stricken community of nome on norton sound
using that historic relay for inspiration, 36 wary mushers set out from anchorage in march 1973. for the next month, the dog teams struggled up into the glacier-ribbed alaska range, dropped into the timbered interior, mushed down the frozen yukon, then crossed over to the wind-blown bering sea coast for a final limp into nome
it was a macho event full of the alaska mystique, and the men who finished _ no women raced until 1975 _ were instant heroes in alaska
today, the race still bursts with a frontier aura. rugged mushers and their teams of 12 to 20 eager dogs brave blizzards, wild animals, frostbite and 1,000 miles of sled-busting trail
but it's not quite so macho anymore
since 1985, when libby riddles ventured into a howling gale and left the men behind, women have dominated the race
riddles won that race, and susan butcher has won the last two, setting a course record each time. last march, she finished in 11 days, 2 hours, about half the time it took in 1973
the fastest competitors have become mushing machines. backed by corporate sponsors and driving high-tech plastic sleds, they shave hours from their race times by going without sleep for days. the winner this year will get $30,000; the next 19 finishers will share the rest of the $150,000 purse
but even some of the leaders refuse to take things too seriously
duane ``dewey'' halverson, a perennial contender, remembers the days when many mushers regarded the iditarod as an extended camping trip
i think the competition is a little stiffer than it used to be,'' he said in mcgrath while his dogs rested on straw laid down in the snow
we'll make it and have fun and see where we finish, and i'll get one of those little teeny trophies this year.''
then he grinned and pronounced his own philosophy of racing dogs across the alaska wilds:
i'm going to have fun if it kills me.'' graf pvs: tutu's group...</note>
the government on saturday banned a church-led opposition group headed by archbishop desmond tutu and said it was a threat to public safety
minister of law and order adriaan vlok said the recently created committee for the defense of democracy was barred from ``performing any activities or acts whatsoever.''
police, meanwhile, issued a separate order banning a sunday rally in cape town that was to mark national detainees day
tutu, who heads the committee for the defense of democracy and who planned to attend the rally, said clergymen instead would hold a church service at st. george's cathedral in cape town. similar church services are scheduled in four other cities
we are dealing with a vicious government that will not tolerate any opposition to its evil and immoral policies,'' tutu told a news conference. ``they have banned a committee even before it has started operating.''
tutu's group was set up following the government's feb. 24 crackdown on black-led opposition groups. in that crackdown, the government banned 18 anti-apartheid organizations from participating in politics
the committee for the defense of democracy is led by several church leaders, including tutu, winner of the 1984 nobel peace prize, and allan boesak, president of the world alliance of reformed churches. the clergymen said the group would attempt to take over some the activities previously carried out by the restricted organizations
however, vlok's latest order places the same restrictions on tutu's group as the other anti-apartheid groups
certain clergy are becoming more and more involved in preaching revolution instead of the true christian message,'' vlok said in a statement
vlok accused church leaders of promoting the aims of the outlawed african national congress, which wages a bombing and sabotage campaign in a bid to overthrow the white-led government
he cited a march 1 broadcast by anc's radio freedom which called for the church in south africa to take a more active role in opposing the government
the anc is currently waging a desperate attempt to extend the revolutionary onslaught and is aiming this attack more and more at the churches and the whites,'' vlok said
the church (should) direct itself to the spiritual area and the government can rely on its prayers to solve the difficult political problems in the country,'' vlok added
tutu's group helped arrange sunday rallies at five sites across the country to mark national detainees day. however, police saturday banned the cape town ceremony, where tutu and boesak were to appear
police spokesman l.j. haasbroek said he had no information on the status of the four remaining rallies
clergymen indicated earlier this week they may defy any attempt by authorities to stop them
saturday's clampdown is the latest in a series of tough government actions aimed at political opponents in recent weeks. in addition to banning political activity by 18 groups, the government has imposed restrictions on individual activists and introduced legislation to prohibit foreign funding of political activity
in a related development, the black sash, an anti-apartheid group made up of white women, estimated saturday that 1,500 activists remain in detention without charge
black sash, which has not been directly affected by the recent crackdowns, said it would continue ``to defend those who are voiceless and incarcerated.''
an estimated 30,000 people have been detained without charge for varying lengths of time during the 21-month-old state of emergency
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
survivors of gov. evan mecham's administration have come forward at his impeachment trial with tales of the chaotic final days when ``mistrust bred mistrust'' and mecham believed his enemies were spying on him with laser beams
a reluctant defense witness, electronics technician antonio corio, told how he was sent to the governor's offices in november to check the security system and do a ``sweep'' to detect electronic bugs and laser beam listening devices
they had feelings there were leaks,'' corio said. ``information was getting out of the ninth floor somehow.''
he said he was reminded that mecham was publicly embarrassed by reports that he thought laser beam listening devices were being used to spy on him. the governor's office was seeking proof
what did you detect?'' asked mecham defense attorney fred craft
not a whole lot,'' corio said to the lawyer's surprise
the technician, who had been called to bolster the claim of bugging, refused to cooperate once he was on the stand. he said he knew about laser beam listening devices, but they have to be used at close range
could you detect sounds in the governor's office if you were on the capitol grounds?'' asked craft
i don't think so,'' said corio
as to who might be using such a device, the governor had a prime suspect _ attorney general robert corbin. corbin said the only laser he ever had was a toy he got for christmas
mecham, 63, the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades, is charged with obstructing an investigation by corbin into an alleged death threat against former mecham aide donna carlson by another mecham associate, lee watkins
in other impeachment charges, the first-term republican governor is accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 in a state fund by loaning it to his auto dealership. the arizona senate is considering the obstruction charge first
mecham faces a criminal trial april 21 on the loan charge and a recall election may 17
the antagonism between mecham and corbin surfaced as witnesses from mecham's inner circle tried to explain why mecham, faced with a probe by corbin into the alleged death threat, would have told the state's top lawman, col. ralph milstead: ``the attorney general is out to hang me. ... don't tell the attorney general anything.''
former mecham aide sam steiger described a feud between corbin and mecham that began in the first days of mecham's term when corbin advised the governor to eliminate the state's martin luther king holiday for state employees. he said it had been illegally declared by gov. bruce babbitt, mecham's predecessor
the governor abided by that decision and took an inordinate public beating over it,'' steiger recalled. ``i thought the beating should have been shared.'' but he said corbin never announced it was his idea
steiger acknowledged under cross-examination that, ``i would be less than candid if i were to say the governor was a supporter of the (martin luther king) holiday.''
mecham's other perceived enemy was the news media, and steiger suggested this led to his downfall
he was a man who won election essentially without the press and the (republican) party,'' he said. ``he learned he could be elected without them. what he forgot was he couldn't survive without them.''
in the final months before mecham was impeached by the house of representatives on feb. 5, close aides such as ms. carlson resigned in protest of mecham's policies. peggy griffith, mecham's chief of women's services, said she and ms. carlson, friends for many years, stopped speaking
mistrust bred mistrust,'' said steiger
you would agree that the mecham inner circle was paranoid?'' prosecutor paul eckstein asked steiger
no, i would not agree with that,'' said steiger who suggested that concern about electronic bugs and traitors on the staff were realistic
the final staff split with mecham was over watkins, in charge of prison construction, said several witnesses. staffers almost unanimously favored dismissal of the unpopular watkins even before he was accused of making a death threat on ms. carlson, then a grand jury witness against mecham
with people telling him mr. watkins should go, he is the kind of person that would dig in his heels and, absent a compelling reason, would defend mr. watkins,'' steiger said of mecham
ms. carlson also said she was told by mecham's chief of staff, jim colter: `we have to take care of lee. he raised a lot of money for the campaign.'' charges'</note>
by allowing robert c. mcfarlane to plead guilty to four misdemeanor counts, independent counsel lawrence e. walsh virtually secured a major prosecution witness if other players in the iran-contra affair go to trial
mcfarlane's promise of full cooperation as part of the plea agreement is a prize for walsh. the former national security adviser was among the inner circle of reagan administration aides who masterminded the iran-contra scheme
walsh said mcfarlane's cooperation would solve the technical problem of ``joinder.'' legal experts said this means walsh could have live testimony from a crucial player instead of having to build his case around documents
mcfarlane, who was national security adviser from october 1983 through november 1985, initiated the review of u.s. arms policy toward iran. after leaving the white house he remained a key policymaker, leading an unsuccessful arms-for-hostages mission to tehran in may 1986
his guilty plea focused on his role in secret u.s. assistance to the nicaraguan contras at a time congress had banned such aid
he admitted that he withheld information about the activities of lt. col. oliver l. north and other members of the national security council staff in three 1985 letters to house committees
he also admitted withholding information from the house foreign affairs committee when he told the panel on dec. 8, 1986, that he was unaware of any efforts to solicit donations for the contras from a third country
although walsh and mcfarlane agreed that the cooperation was voluntary, the independent counsel acknowledged mcfarlane could have faced much more serious perjury charges if he was uncooperative
each of the misdemeanor counts of withholding information carries a maximum one year prison term. by contrast, felony perjury charges carry a maximum of five years in prison, and larger fines also could be levied
walsh said mcfarlane's cooperation wasn't the only reason he went the misdemeanor route
he cited mcfarlane's ``undisguised demonstration of remorse after the false testimony was given in which he tried to correct his testimony; and actually imposed injury upon himself in a fit of depression,'' a reference to mcfarlane's attempted suicide via an overdose of valium last year
while admitting his guilt, mcfarlane told reporters he acted at a time that relations between congress and the white house ``broke down so tragically.''
my actions were motivated by what i believed to be in the foreign policy interest of the united states,'' he said
mcfarlane's comments were reminiscent of remarks by former cia director richard helms on oct. 31, 1977, when he pleaded no contest to two misdemeanor charges under the same law used by walsh
the charges against helms arose from his testimony to the senate foreign relations committee that the cia had made no attempt to prevent the election of marxist salvador allende as president of chile in 1970
i found myself in a position of conflict,'' said helms. ``i had sworn by my oath to preserve certain secrets ... i didn't want to lie. i didn't want to mislead the senate. i was simply trying to find my way through a very difficult situation in which i found myself.''
a monthly magazine has published the first half of an unfinished memoir by late poet konstantin m. simonov in which he explores the shame felt by soviets like himself who aided the repressions of dictator josef v. stalin
simonov began the memoir in 1979 but died in 1980 before he could finish it
he wrote the book ``for the archives'' and told his secretary that he did not expect to see the memoir published in his lifetime, explained an accompanying publisher's note in the march issue of znamya, a literary journal
articles and books re-examining the legacy of stalin have been appearing regularly over the past year as soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's campaign for glasnost, or openness, encourages broader discussion of social and historical problems
the memoir, ``through the eyes of a person of my generation,'' attempts to explain, without excusing, the behavior of those who grew to regard stalin's excesses as a normal state of affairs
referring to his acceptance of the arrest and exile of three aunts in the 1930s, simonov wrote four decades later that such events ``which seem monstrous and impossible today, were then a norm and gradually became habitual.''
he wrote that the rationale he adopted at the time was ``you can't make an omelette without breaking eggs.''
simonov, who was twice honored with the stalin prize for literature and earned numerous other accolades during his writing career, was one of the many literary figures who followed the government's lead in denouncing poet anna akhmatova, writer mikhail zoshchenko and others in a 1946 purge of the intelligentsia
he referred to the role he played in ruining the careers of contemporaries only as ``the events of 1946,'' acknowledging that his readers would know what he meant
simonov had confessed to sinning against his conscience in denouncing respected writers and artists. in the way of atonement, he championed the suppressed works of writer mikhail bulgakov and eventually succeeded in getting published his masterpiece, ``the master and margarita.''
the weekly newspaper moscow news published a commentary on the simonov memoir, observing that simonov was trying to explain why it is possible for many russians to feel both awe for stalin's accomplishments and revulsion over his purges
the second half of the unfinished memoir is to be published in april edition of znamya, the journal said
chrysler corp.'s failed attempt to quietly sell off a fifth of the company before its united auto workers contract expired has created a fracture in labor relations that the two sides hope can be healed at the bargaining table
the no. 3 automaker once planned to use the months before its three-year uaw contract expires sept. 14 to rid itself of most parts operations by selling its 28,000-worker acustar inc. subsidiary
under that plan, chrysler could have evaded restrictions on closing plants or shifting inside work to outside suppliers that already are in place at ford motor co. and general motors corp. under the established uaw pattern contracts for the auto industry
instead, chrysler found itself with a work force whose anger exploded over the possible sale and remains largely unappeased by chrysler's retreat in the face of a threat of crippling plant-by-plant strikes
there's still a lot of hard feelings and the central issue is still not settled,'' said uaw local 412 president jim jensen, whose local represents engineers and other salaried chrysler workers in the detroit area
rather than allow the anger to simmer and build during the three or four crucial months before contract talks open, hurting chances of a settlement and continued quality production, chrysler asked for early negotiations
it's always important to resolve issues that are outstanding,'' said chrysler's chief negotiator, human resources vice president anthony st. john. ``we've had some convergence of issues that have been very difficult for the union and for chrysler.''
the uaw agreed last week, marking the third time in the last 10 years that the two will bargain early. once before, in 1982, the early talks failed. but this time, neither side can easily afford a failure at the table
chrysler and the union are betting that in the talks, which could begin as early as next month and will cover 59,500 workers, they'll be able to fix the problem rather than make it worse
but difficult issues remain, beginning with acustar. in announcing its retreat from the sale, chrysler said it would instead close four acustar plants, affecting 2,000 workers, if it can't sell them in 18 months
we as a union are not prepared to just give up and say there goes 2,000 jobs,'' said jensen, who will be one of 10 elected members of the union's bargaining team
st. john, however, said last week that the fate of the plants is not up for negotiation
jensen and other workers also say they expect chrysler to seek a two-tier wage system _ paying parts workers lower wages and benefits than assembly workers _ because it has shown it considers the parts operation too expensive
the uaw sidelined similar attempts by ford and general motors last fall when it negotiated new three-year contracts with chrysler's larger rivals
given the enormous reaction to acustar, chrysler's ability to institute two-tier wages in this round of negotiations would be very low,'' said harley shaiken, labor and technology expert at the university of california at san diego
uaw president owen bieber said the union will demand a two-year contract so that in 1990, the gm, ford and chrysler contracts will expire together for the first time since 1979
bargaining with the big three together makes it easier for the union to impose one contract on all and gives it a third choice when it is choosing a strike target, the company whose contract serves as the pattern for the others
st. john said chrysler finds advantages in remaining out of synch with gm and ford. chrysler sought a separate relationship with the union beginning in 1979, when workers made the first of many concessions to help the automaker survive
for the first time in 21 years, former black panther johnny spain is out of jail, but the man convicted of slaying two prison guards in the bloody 1971 ``san quentin six'' escape attempt is not yet a free man
release of the one-time prison revolutionary has been opposed consistently by the state. but his parole has been urged by enthusiastic supporters, including dennis riordan, his attorney for the past 12 years, two congressmen and two prison guards, one the best friend of one of the slain san quentin officers
while in prison, spain, 38, earned a high school diploma, became an electrician and has been a model prisoner in recent years. he has had no disciplinary action against him since 1979, when he was caught with marijuana
he left the california medical facility in vacaville last week after a series of court actions allowed friends and relatives to post $350,000 bail for his freedom
i won't let anyone down who has supported me, and there have been many who supported me,'' he promised upon his release, adding that he expected life outside prison to be difficult. ``i'll deal with it. i'm prepared. i've thought about it a lot.''
however, spain still faces a new trial on the prison murders and a monday hearing at which the state will argue against the order calling for that trial. a 2-1 state board of prison terms decision to parole spain next year also will be reviewed by the entire nine-member board march 11
spain had been behind bars continuously since his arrest at the age of 17 in december 1966 for the first-degree murder and robbery of a los angeles man
while on bail, authorities said spain will live in san francisco and work as an electrician. he also will be allowed to travel around the state and visit his wife and childhood sweetheart, pinkey, whom he married in 1977 while in prison. they have two sons
it was a twisting courtroom trail that finally opened spain's cell door
u.s. district judge thelton henderson overturned the san quentin murder conviction in 1986, saying spain had been deprived of his right to a fair trial by being shackled in 25 pounds of chains in every court appearance in the case
but spain still had to remain behind bars because of the 1966 murder conviction
but tuesday, los angeles superior court judge kathleen parker ordered spain paroled immediately for the 1966 murder-robbery. parker said he was eligible for release because the state board of prison terms improperly extended his sentence six years by applying regulations passed in 1976 to disciplinary violations committed in 1970 and 1971
that action cleared the way for bail to be set in the san quentin retrial
during a trial that took almost five years, spain was convicted of murdering two san quentin guards in a bloodbath that left one other guard, prison militant george jackson and two prisoners dead
prison authorities said spain was seen bolting from the maximum-security unit with jackson and helped plot the unsuccessful escape attempt
although no one said spain actually killed guards jere graham and frank deleon, he was found culpable under state law because he had conspired to escape with jackson
bullets hidden in hollow bars of soap and a map reportedly showing escape routes were found afterward in his cell in a section reserved for death row and problem inmates
spain and jackson, a black panther leader and author of the book, ``soledad brothers,'' had become friends while incarcerated together at soledad state prison before both were transfered to san quentin
spain had a troubled childhood in jackson, miss. his mother was a white woman married to a white man, but as spain grew up, it became increasingly clear that his biological father was a black man, not his mother's husband. segregated black schools refused to accept him, as did white schools
his mother sent him at the age of 6 to live with a black couple in east los angeles. he became a high school athlete, but also joined a street gang and committed minor crimes that netted him a stint in a juvenile facility before the 1966 robbery-murder
a vatican official said saturday that permission from cuba's communist government to send 20 foreign priests to cuba was a sign of improving relations between the roman catholic church and that caribbean nation
however, monsignor carlos manuel de cespedes, director of the vaticans' secretariat of the episcopal conference, told vatican radio that the church hopes for still more improvement in the area of individual rights
he said the church would like to see more religious freedom in cuba and the construction of new churches
he said there has not been ``sensational changes in the rapport between the church and state, between catholics and marxists. but, nevertheless, things are moving and i would like to say they are moving in the right way.''
de cespedes said examples of change were the government allowing the cuban church to import 30,000 bibles last year and permission last week for the church to send 20 foreign priests to cuba
vatican radio said there are 406 cuban priests to serve the predominantly catholic population of about 10 million
it said most of the 20 foreign priests that will go to cuba are spanish or italian, but there also will be one mexican and one canadian
rebels led by fidel castro ousted the fulgencio batista dictatorsyip in 1959 and in december 1961 castro declared cuba would be a marxist-leninist state. tenn gov, lamar sted doyle</note>
as the presidential campaign moved from the south to illinois, associated press bureaus in the super tuesday states surveyed officials' reactions to their innovative regional primary. here is a report
if the goal was to beat iowa, the wednesday morning quarterbacks agreed, the south had a winner in its ``super tuesday'' regional presidential primary election experiment
many officials in the 20 voting states were elated to have real, live presidential candidates trooping through, but some felt they could have attracted more attention with a less crowded primary
super tuesday did what i thought it would do,'' said georgia secretary of state max cleland. ``it has meant sudden death to most candidates and sudden life to a few.''
jim hunt, former governor of north carolina, thought super tuesday proved its worth. his candidate, sen. albert gore of tennessee, gained the stature he needed after ignoring earlier contests in both iowa and new hampshire
but although gore did well, he had to share the victory with two liberals, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and jesse jackson. each won about a third of the states and delegates
alabama republican party chairman emory folmar called that a defeat for southern leaders who had hoped super tuesday would give the edge to a moderate or conservative
it blew up in their faces,'' folmar said
but the democratic finish, combined with vice president george bush's 16-1 sweep of tuesday's primaries and caucuses, turned the iowa caucus results on their head. there rep. richard gephardt was the democratic winner, while sen. robert dole and pat robertson both beat bush
presidential candidates may approach the race differently as the result of super tuesday. it could be they will no longer consider iowa a must stop,'' said u.s. rep. tom tauke, r-iowa
gore's strategy has revealed that the new hampshire primary doesn't control how the democratic nominee will be selected,'' said oklahoma attorney general robert henry
however, joe grandmaison, new hampshire's democratic party chief, said super tuesday proved the ``value and singularity'' of his state's first-in-the-nation primary. ``new hampshire's brand of retail politics forces the candidates to face the voters and debate the issues,'' he said
many democrats in the south and some republicans were pleased with the outcome
we wanted to nationalize our message, and we accomplished that. compare the rhetoric between 1984 and 1988. it was far less damaging this year than four years ago,'' said former gov. charles robb of virginia, a democrat who endorsed gore and promoted the super tuesday idea
before this year, all the presidential candidates did in the south was change planes in the atlanta airport,'' said former tennessee gov. lamar alexander, a republican
we just felt for years like the candidates were ignoring us to go to iowa and new hampshire. we've had more presidential candidates in texas already this time than we've had in the whole past 10 years,'' said former texas state sen. john traeger
u.s. sen. lloyd bentsen, d-texas, said super tuesday forced candidates to address locally important issues such as low oil prices, but he thought the calendar was too crowded with 14 southern and border states, plus six other states and american samoa, holding primaries or caucuses
i'd rather texas be out by itself. i wish we could figure out some way to get it ahead of iowa,'' bentsen said
wallace hyde, a democratic fund-raiser from asheville, n.c., and co-chairman of gore's state campaign, was happier
it worked _ almost on the money,'' he said. ``you definitely came out of it with a moderately conservative candidate.''
however, texas state sen. chet edwards said super tuesday was not conceived as a way ``to elect some neanderthal anglo southerner.''
it was designed to give 16 million texans and citizens throughout the south a voice in the selection of our president and a voice in the setting of our national agenda,'' he said
john weaver, executive director of the texas gop, thought democrats hoping for a conservative must be disappointed
i'm sure the people who hoped the democrats would nominate (sen.) sam nunn or chuck robb would rather put this primary in a burlap bag and drop it in the colorado river,'' weaver said
judge-executive jerry taylor of whitley county, ky., called super tuesday ``the biggest farce there ever was.''
unless you have something locally as a drawing card, it's just difficult to get people involved,'' said taylor, a democrat
turnout in kentucky was 24.4 percent for democrats and 22.1 percent for republicans
most states did better. georgia had a 40 percent turnout overall, a record for a presidential primary in that state, and a gop turnout which doubled the previous mark
mississippi's republicans had a record turnout, 31 percent of the total vote in a traditionally democratic state. ``in fact, it was double what we've had before in a republican primary,'' said evelyn mcphail, executive director of the mississippi gop
in texas, a presidential primary record 2.77 million voters participated, or 35 percent
in tennessee and north carolina, officials said the turnout was about the same as in previous, non-super primaries
in maryland, the democratic turnout of 38 percent compared to 34 percent four years ago, when walter mondale was all but unopposed, and 48 percent in 1976 when jimmy carter ran against former calfiornia gov. jerry brown
maryland gov. william donald schaefer, a democrat, called the march 8 primary a waste of time that drew only token appearances by the candidates
mr. bush made a telephone call to one of the baltimore radio stations,'' schaefer said. ``i would hope we would go back to may when the candidate would have to come through and talk to the people.''
maryland also held its congressional primaries march 8, and gop chairman dan fleming said the early primary made it impossible to find a candidate to oppose rep. tom mcmillen, even though the first-term democrat won by only 428 votes in 1986 in a historically republican district
people aren't used to thinking about the election until the first of the year. here we had a filing deadline that was in december for a march primary,'' said schaefer
in massachusetts, republican and democratic leaders agreed they would not want to compete with a southern primary again
joe malone, executive director of the republican state committee in massachusetts, also complained that a big, one-day contest gives an advantage to candidates with money and organization
once you get into what is the closest thing to a national primary, then you better have a lot of ammunition,'' malone said. sign language, to raise first reference to gallaudet and to insert 1 graf with additional quotes; picks up 5th graf pvs, there was</note>
with excitement in his hands rather than voice, alfred sonnenstrahl expressed in candid, joyful words the sense of triumph shared by fellow protesters who made themselves heard on the quietest college campus in america
i've been on this campus for 30 years now,'' he said in sign language. ``and for the first time in my whole life i feel good about being here. for the first time i feel like a complete person.''
the 52-year-old mechanical engineer, a doctoral candidate at gallaudet university, pointed to the students, staff and faculty who had shut down the school for the deaf last week to protest the appointment of a hearing president
look around,'' sonnenstrahl signed. ``you see people smiling. they look alive.''
the transformation of gallaudet occurred even before elisabeth ann zinser, who is not deaf and does not know sign language, gave in to mounting pressure for a deaf president and stepped down only days after she was chosen
there was no mistaking the exhilaration in the brisk air. more than a generation after the civil rights movement began, the time for the deaf was _ finally _ now
even zinser acknowledged the strength of the movement in a news conference the day she resigned
the protest, she said, was ``a very special moment in time for the deaf community ... (that) we could not anticipate.''
twenty years ago, blacks devastated by martin luther king jr.'s murder looted and burned a major commercial strip that is only now being rebuilt. four blocks away, behind its tall fence, gallaudet lay isolated and hidden under a thick blanket of silence
only in the last few years, with civil rights laws, communications technology and a wave of professional interpreters, has that silence begun to lift. deaf people say they are more aware of their rights, more self-confident and more assertive. thus the stage was set for last week's eruption
the campus crusade drew headlines and ``nightline,'' the attention of congressmen and presidential candidates, the support of commuters and taxi drivers and contributors across the country, the largess of local corporations who donated food, paint and 50 sheets with which to make banners
the protesters liken themselves to prisoners or slaves and the blacks of south africa. nothing, they say, will ever be the same
we have been accepting bowing down for 124 years, maybe longer,'' said student leader jerry covell. ``we want to take control of our lives and our futures.''
president lincoln chartered the school 124 years ago. it later was named after thomas hopkins gallaudet, a pioneer in deaf education. the nation's only liberal arts school for the deaf, it is described again and again as an intellectual mecca; its presidency, the loftiest post to which a deaf person could aspire
so, it's not hard to understand the resentment created by the appointment of a hearing, non-signing president _ particularly when there were two deaf finalists for the job, including the university's own dean of arts and sciences
deaf people own businesses. we have deaf lawyers and deaf dentists. we have deaf stockbrokers and deaf millionaires. the only thing we've never had is a deaf president of this college,'' said angel ramos, 38, a math professor and doctoral candidate at gallaudet. ``we'll never be telephone operators. but there's no reason we cannot have a deaf president here.''
the gallaudet presidency was last open in 1983, and the board of trustees chose jerry lee _ another hearing person, but one who knew sign language and who had been part of the campus community for several years
there was no uprising then, nor in 1969 when edward merrill began his 14-year tenure as president. students did complain that he didn't know sign language and they asked him to learn. now they want far more
we were never given opportunities to manage schools before 1980,'' said john kubis, 62, a math professor at gallaudet since 1957. ``in 1983, there were a few qualified deaf candidates but they only had a few years of administrative experience. now we have deaf people who are as much if not more experienced as dr. zinser.''
deaf people have been slowly emerging from their isolation since the rehabilitation act of 1973, which barred discrimination against the handicapped in federally funded programs or activities
the process has been speeded by a proliferation of professional, impartial interpreters. ``during the early days, interpreters were very few and far between,'' kubis said. ``they talked down to the deaf. instead of being our tools to communicate, they would tell us what they thought we should say and censor the dialogue.''
the deaf community was ripe for rebellion for other reasons as well _ the advent of closed captioning on television, telephone access through telecommunications devices for the deaf and computers through which deaf people can communicate with anyone
protesters claimed only a partial victory when zinser withdrew friday. they say a deaf president has yet to be named. they also want a majority of deaf people on the 20-member board of trustees that runs the university. now, only four members are deaf
but the demonstrators said events at gallaudet had already brought irrevocable changes
there's no way things will ever be the same again,'' said ramos, a protest leader. ``deaf people throughout the world have finally learned what other minority groups have learned _ that if you stick together and walk together, you will succeed. finally, after 124 years, the deaf community has taken charge of their own destiny, and we're mighty proud of it.''
american and french telecommunications satellites sent into space by europe's ariane 3 rocket were prepared saturday to move into permanent orbits on their own power
the european space agency also announced plans for two more launches in may
technicians said france's telecom 1c and the american spacenet iiir-geostar, which includes facilities for the associated press, were thrust into a geographically stationary orbit friday night about 20 minutes after liftoff from this south american jungle base
officials called the launch perfect
arianespace, the space agency's commercial arm, said saturday two more launches were planned for may, one a demonstration flight of the more powerful ariane 4 rocket. arianespace is now the west's only active commercial satellite launcher with america's space-shuttle program grounded
the ariane 3 rocket ignited normally four minutes after blastoff, officials said. ignition was the cause of failed ariane launches in september 1982, september 1985 and may 1986
the last failure, the 18th launch, left the rocket grounded for more than a year
technicians said friday's satellites obtained an altitute of 22,554 miles
the french satellite is to begin moving into its definitive geostationary orbit sunday, 37 hours after the launch, after igniting its own engine, arianespace said
spacenet iiir-geostar is to start moving into a permanent orbit about 90 hours after the liftoff, the company said
gte spacenet, the european firm's first american client, has used the ariane to launch five satellites, losing one in a september 1985 failure
jerry waylan, gte spacenet chief, said this was the first american telecommunications satellite to be launched in two years
the satellite, with an expected lifetime of 10 years, weighed 2,674 pounds before liftoff and 1,562 pounds in orbit
two transponders on spacenet iii purchased by ap are to provide the new york-based news cooperative with domestic satellite delivery services
the french telecom ic, replacing one that broke down jan. 15, is to be used for telephones, radio and television transmissions and military communications
arianespace said it has orders for 41 more satellite launchings, valued at $2.29 billion
two months into the trial of lyndon larouche comes evidence supporting the political extremist's claim that he was the target of plots by the fbi, the cia and even lt. col. oliver north
now, even some defense lawyers who had dismissed larouche's allegations of a conspiracy theory as one of his many bizarre claims are taking notice. larouche has also said britain's queen elizabeth condones drug trafficking and that one way to help the u.s. economy is to populate mars
the trial of larouche, six aides, and five of his political organizations on fraud and conspiracy charges was halted friday so that defense attorneys could search government files, including those of the white house and vice president george bush, for any evidence suggesting infiltration of larouche groups
prosecutors have insisted that talk of fbi, cia and other government infiltration in recently declassified documents is just that _ talk _ and that the subject is irrelevant to charges that larouche and followers conspired to stymie a grand jury investigation into alleged fraud by fund-raisers during his 1984 presidential campaign
but, at least for now, larouche has turned the tables on the government, which has been ordered to search thousands of files belonging to the fbi, cia, the national security council and bush
assistant u.s. attorney john markham on monday is to update u.s. district judge robert e. keeton on the status of the search. the judge will decide whether to resume testimony tuesday or wait until the search is completed
larouche lawyers last week received a copy of a memo from retired air force maj. gen. richard secord to north, two principals in the iran-contra affair, in which secord says retired army sgt. major fred lewis had met with the fbi and ``other agency reps'' and has ``collected info against larouche.''
the defense then demanded fbi files mentioning lewis. after first refusing to do so, the fbi declassified parts of a document in which lewis and two texas lawmen who had worked as government informants say the fbi and cia asked them to infiltrate larouche groups
lewis and the lawmen were involved in two texas companies reportedly used by the pentagon and cia for covert activities. markham insists they are lying about infiltrating larouche groups
but the mere existence of the fbi document and the secord-north memo, discovered months after markham had said searches of government records were complete, was enough to persuade the judge to halt testimony and order new searches
it also was enough to convert michael reilly, attorney for larouche's central political organization, the national caucus of labor committees. reilly had told the jury in his opening statement that larouche's infiltration claim was misguided paranoia
this is a fundamental change in my defense strategy,'' reilly said. ``i should have had this 18 months ago and i have a right to have it before i pursue this case.''
another defense attorney, william moffitt, says his legal strategy may be affected by the document searches
in his opening statement, markham referred to an entry in a notebook seized from moffitt's client, larouche aide jeffrey steinberg, as evidence larouche and aides conspired to obstruct the grand jury investigation
the aug. 23, 1986, entry is attributed to ryan quade emerson, who at the time had recently returned to the larouche organization. five days earlier, according to documents recently surrendered to defense lawyers, an fbi agent interviewed emerson and asked him to rejoin the larouche organization
the prosecutor's task will be to convince keeton that references to fbi and cia infiltration of larouche groups are unsubstantiated and irrelevant to the case
the defense lawyers, who concede the material may not be directly relevant, say it nevertheless supports their argument that larouche and his followers are longtime government targets and victims of entrapment
ironically, larouche missed the week of his trial he would have enjoyed the most. with court permission, he went to west germany for cataract surgery last week and is not expected back for several weeks. up 16th graf pvs, people with</note>
several lawmakers have criticized a group of congressional aides for meeting secretly with palestinian leader yasser arafat in january, only weeks after congress voted to close palestine liberation organization offices in the united states
the secret, two-hour meeting, which took place in baghdad, iraq, became publicly known last week. it was arranged by the national council on u.s.-arab relations, the group that paid for the congressional aides' eight-day trip to iraq on jan. 11-19
the meeting, described as an open exchange between arafat and the aides, was held shortly after congress passed controversial legislation shutting down two plo offices in the united states on the grounds they represent a terrorist organization. arafat is head of the plo
it was very foolish, very wrong,'' rep. larry smith, d-fla., said of the aides' meeting. ``he (arafat) is not going to change his positions because a capitol hill staffer meets with him.''
rep. robert g. torricelli, d-n.j., said he was upset when he learned an aide attended the baghdad meeting with arafat
she acted independently, and i had no knowledge of this meeting nor would i have approved it, and i remain very disturbed about it.'' the staffer no longer works for torricelli, but left for personal reasons unrelated to the meeting
but another lawmaker was unfazed by his aide's attendance at the meeting
rep. edward feighan, d-ohio, said his assistant ``was not on any official trip and he was traveling in a personal capacity.''
michael van dusen, staff director of the house foreign affairs subcommittee on europe and the middle east, said seeing arafat was ``extremely unwise when as a matter of law american officials are not supposed to negotiate with the plo. ... i wouldn't do it.''
u.s. policy _ set by congress _ prohibits officials in the executive branch from negotiating with arafat or members of the plo until the group recognizes israel's right to exist
the policy does not apply to congress, and a few lawmakers as well as members of their staff have met openly with arafat in the past
while the congressional group did not violate the law, members of congress and key staff people on capitol hill said that, in view of u.s. policy, it was unwise to hold discussions with arafat, particularly if a lawmaker had not authorized the talks
ronald w. cathell, the executive director of u.s.-arab council, said he would not release the names of the staffers who attended the arafat meeting or traveled to iraq for fear they would be subjected to reprisals for going to the meeting
the council, which seeks to promote understanding between americans and arabs, receives its money from grants and private and corporate contributions
several staffers contacted about the meeting refused to talk about it and would not provide the names of their companions
people with knowledge of the free trip confirmed that those who went to iraq worked for sens. mark hatfield, r-ore.; john heinz, r-pa.; j. bennett johnston, d-la., david karnes, r-neb; and reps. feighan; torricelli; helen bentley, r-md.; douglas bereuter, r-neb.; william clay, d-mo.; james inhofe, r-okla., and robert lagomarsino, r-calif
bereuter's spokeswoman, carol lawrence, said the congressman's aide resigned before the trip, but now works at the pentagon
a state department official, speaking on condition on anonymity, said all but one of the staffers on the iraq trip went to the meeting with arafat
cathell said the original agenda did not include seeing arafat. once the group arrived in baghdad, the council learned the plo leader was in town and broached the possibility of a meeting with the congressional aides
the staffers were never pressured to attend the meeting, which cathell said was designed to give them ``information they could relate to their bosses.'' the staffers were told, ``it's totally up to you,'' he said
one aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the group was given less than an hour's notice that a face-to-face meeting with arafat had been fixed
torricelli complained the u.s. embassy in baghdad failed to advise his aide about u.s. policy prohibiting official negotiations with the plo. cathell said the embassy simply told the group its own people couldn't attend the meeting because of u.s. policy
but a state department official, refusing to be identified by name, said the u.s. ambassador had tried to dissuade the americans from meeting with arafat
cathell said the meeting was constructive, and gave the staffers ``a unique chance to find out firsthand where the palestinian stood.'' the aides, he said, were ``candid and forthright'' with arafat
the baghdad meeting came a few months after congress voted to close both the plo's office at the united nations in new york, and a palestine information office in washington
lawmakers took the action, which has provoked widespread criticism from civil libertarians and u.n. members, on the grounds that the plo supports terrorism
rep. george w. crockett jr., d-mich., has introduced legislation to repeal the closings
federal investigators have concluded their four-day hearing into the cause of a continental jet crash that killed 28 people, but their findings probably won't be released until sometime around the accident's first anniversary in november
we have not eliminated any issue'' in the suspected cause of the nov. 15 crash of flight 1713, board of inquiry chairman joseph t. nall said friday after investigators heard the final testimony in the national transportation safety board hearings
flight 1713, bound for boise, idaho, began rocking violently moments after taking off from stapleton international airport during a snowstorm. it flipped over on its back and crashed on the runway, breaking into three pieces
fifty-four of the 82 people on board survived. some of those survivors were among the 33 witnesses who testified at the hearing
the ntsb investigators were looking into flight characteristics of the dc-9-10 aircraft, especially in snow and ice conditions; air traffic control; cold weather operations by continental; turbulence; and continental's pilot training, pilot selection and crew pairing
i anticipate our board will determine a probable cause and contributing causes to the crash'' by november, nall said
the pilot and co-pilot, capt. frank zvonek, 43, and first officer lee bruecher, 26, both were killed in the crash. bruecher was at the controls
the brief flying time in the dc-9 by both pilots has been one area of study by the investigation
zvonek had 12,135 total hours flying time, with 33 hours as a dc-9 captain. bruecher had a total of 3,186 hours, with 12 hours as a dc-9 first officer
at friday's hearings, richard hillman, continental vice president for flight operations, said that since the crash, the carrier had adopted a federal aviation administration bulletin recommendation that the co-pilot not be allowed to make takeoffs or landings until he or she had 100 hours in that type of aircraft
the hearings also delved into continental's use of a flight simulator in pilot training that is based on the dc-9-30 _ a different model of dc-9 from the ``dash 10'' flown by zvonek and bruecher
the main difference between the two dc-9 models is the ``dash 30'' has wing slats to improve the wing's lift. the dash 10 is an older model with a wing design considered more susceptiable to loss of lift from ice buildup
james e. madsen, continental's assistant chief dc-9 pilot at denver, minimized handling difference between the dash 10 and dash 30s in his testimony
a dc-9 is a dc-9. there are some differences they (pilots) should be aware of,'' madsen said
early theories of what caused flight 1713 to roll violently and crash seconds after liftoff included ice buildup on the wings, turbulence from a jumbo jet that had just landed on a parallel runway 1,600 feet away, and pilot error
continental's de-icing procedures at stapleton also came under scrutiny. flight 1713 waited between 24 and 27 minutes for takeoff after it had been de-iced
survivors offered conflicting testimony on the amount of snow and ice buildup on the wings
i wondered at one point, `is that ice?' but i decided it was just wet,'' said dr. fred helpenstall of nampa, idaho, who suffered broken ribs in the crash
airman greg wadsworth of mountain home air force base in idaho said he had a clear view of the wing before takeoff
it was like the snow was starting to pile up (on the wings). i was very concerned but i said it under my breath,'' he testified
other testimony attributed flight 1713's delay between de-icing and takeoff on miscommunciation in the control tower and between the tower and aircraft
ntsb investigators refused to speculate on any of the suspected causes
our minds are still open. we will make no final conclusion until the time we make our final report,'' nall said
the snowstorm that battered the plains spread snow across central minnesota into northern wisconsin and upper michigan on saturday, but it was weakening with wind not blowing as strongly as the day before
snowfall amounts across central and northeastern minnesota ranged from 6 to 12 inches and northern wisconsin got from 3 to 8 inches
up to 6 inches of snow was expected over michigan's upper peninsula while freezing rain and sleet moved across northern lower michigan
during the morning, wind in minnesota gusted from 25 to more than 50 mph but by afternoon the peak gusts were down to about 40 mph
wind gusts in wisconsin were clocked at from 20 to 30 mph at times
gusty wind also blew around the west side of the storm system, with gusts of 55 mph at mitchell, s.d., during the morning. gusts to 35 to 45 mph were reported across the eastern dakotas into eastern and central nebraska, western and northern kansas into northwestern missouri and western iowa
temperatures were in the single digits across the northern plains, combining with the wind to produce wind chill factors as low as 30 below zero during the afternoon
showers and a few thunderstorms were scattered ahead of a cold front that extended from southeastern wisconsin into the lower mississippi valley, accompanied by brief heavy rain, small hail and gusty wind across northeastern louisiana into west-central mississippi
the heaviest rainfall reported during the six hours up to 1 p.m. est was 0.53 of an inch at texarkana, ark
the heaviest snow during the same period was 6 inches at marquette, mich
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 6 degrees at yellowstone national park in wyoming to 85 at mcallen, texas. the low for the day was 20 degres below zero at west yellowstone, mont
for sunday, snow showers were forecast across the great lakes region with rain changing to snow over the eastern great lakes and northern new england. showers were forecast from the upper ohio valley into central and southern new england. scattered showers also were forecast over the middle and southern atlantic coast region
highs in the teens and 20s were predicted across the northern plains, the upper mississippi valley and upper great lakes region; in the 60s from the central pacific coast over western and central texas and the central gulf coast to the middle atlantic coast; in the 70s over the southern california coast, desert southwest, the southern tip of texas and northern florida and the southern atlantic coast; in the low 80s over the southern half of florida; and in the 30s, 40s or 50s across most of the rest of the nation. update with lebanese report of casualties from raid, organizers saying 100,000 sted 200,000 at peace now demonstration, details.</note>
hundreds of palestinian policemen in the occupied territories resigned saturday to protest israeli treatment of palestinians, prompting fears that other arab employees of the government also would quit
israel radio said close to 450 of the roughly 1,000 arab police officers in the occupied west bank and gaza strip have quit their jobs in the past two days and more resignations are expected
israeli and palestinian officials said at least 330 had resigned and the resignations would take effect monday
israeli bullets and beatings have killed 87 palestinians in anti-occupation unrest since dec. 8
the resignations began friday, one day after underground leaders of the disturbances in the occupied territories called on the arab policemen to resign immediately. some officers reported that their lives had been threatened
israeli warplanes, meanwhile, struck at guerrilla targets east of the port town of sidon in southern lebanon, the army command said
israel television reported that at least eight people were killed in the air raid, israel's second this year against palestinian targets in south lebanon. sidon police said at least one guerrilla was killed and eight were wounded
in the west bank, israeli soldiers shot and seriously wounded a palestinian from the village of bani naim, near hebron, after he threw a hand grenade at them, the army command said. the grenade did not explode
at nur el-shams, near tulkarem, a 50-year-old woman was wounded when prison service employees opened fire after their bus was stoned
thousands of israeli peace now demonstrators gathered in tel aviv to urge prime minister yitzhak shamir to support a u.s. peace initiative that would allow limited self-rule for the arabs in the occupied lands
peace now organizers estimated the crowd at 100,000. a reporter for the daily yediot ahronot put the figure at 70,000. police refused to give an estimate
israel's right-wing factions have called for a counter-demonstration in the same place on sunday evening, a few hours before shamir leaves for a visit to washington to discuss the plan
the continuing unrest in the occupied territories appears to be putting a severe strain on israel's defense forces
the weekend edition of yediot ahronot, the country's largest newspaper, carried at least four ads offering security-related jobs
one ad sought recruits for a new police anti-terror unit. another asked for arab-speaking officers holding the rank of captain or major for ``special work involving contact with the local population.''
other ads offered jobs to arabic language translators along israel's northern border and civilian guards to protect the israeli-egyptian border
the mass resignation of palestinian police officers will add a new strain and could be the harbinger of larger and more serious defections to come
bethlehem mayor elias freij said the mass resignations ``will vastly affect the process of the courts in the west bank, and it is a precedent for many more civil servants to resign.''
about 18,000 palestinians work for the military government in the west bank and gaza strip
national police spokesman adi gonen warned that the resignations would hurt the palestinians themselves
the (arab) police were not used for intelligence purposes, to put down protests or for anything political,'' said gonen. ``if they quit, we will have to reduce police activities and that will affect the quality of palestinian life.''
last week, 40 arab tax collectors in the gaza strip left their jobs after palestinian protesters threatened their lives
the resignations indicated the growing loss of control by israel over the occupied territories and deprived it of a potent symbol of cooperation and coexistence with the palestinians
a survey by the associated press indicated that most of the 250 policemen in the southern part of the west bank have handed in their resignations
arab police at the ramallah station said all 50 policemen were quitting. freij said that all 50 policemen in his district had resigned. the arab-run palestine press service put the figure in hebron at at least 68
mordechai bareket, police spokesman for the southern section of the occupied west bank, said ``over 100 policemen'' handed in their resignations over the past two days
israel radio reported that 100 policemen in gaza and 30 in the northern district of the west bank also said they were leaving the force
police spokesmen said they were trying to persuade the palestinian police officers to change their minds
we are talking to each one of them individually and looking into each of their problems,'' said chaim alter, commander of the northern west bank police district
the order to resign was issued thursday by the national united command of the uprising
mustafa adani, who resigned friday, said his life had been threatened twice
earlier this week, a policeman from the aqbat jaber refugee camp near jericho was killed
the company that operates the federally owned fernald uranium-processing plant violates its own regulations and puts its workers' health at risk, a new government report concludes
the report says the u.s. department of energy, which owns the plant, and westinghouse materials co. of ohio, the private contractor that runs it, should work harder to eliminate potential worker health hazards at the facility's feed materials production center
the 37-year-old plant, 18 miles northwest of cincinnati, processes uranium for use in the government's nuclear weapons
the national institute for occupational safety and health, part of the u.s. department of health and human services, issued the preliminary report last week on the basis of a december inspection conducted at the request of labor unions at the plant
its final report is not due out for three more months, but westinghouse says it has already responded to the institute's findings by making some rule changes at the plant
the report said plant employees sometimes leave portable air-breathing equipment lying out in areas containing loose and radioactively contaminated dust, which could get into the respirators and ultimately into workers' lungs
given the fact that many surfaces in the plants where we made measurements are radiologically contaminated, it is imperative that workers store their respirators in a clean location when not in use. this practice should prevent inadvertent ingestion of radiation-contaminated materials,'' wrote the industrial hygienists who prepared the report
many surfaces in the plant are contaminated with radioactive substances from the plant's years of service and require cleanup, the federal hygienists said
they said they found westinghouse technicians who violated company regulations and created a potential health hazard by smoking, eating and drinking while handling and counting radiological samples
surely, such a practice needs to stop immediately,'' the investigators wrote
they also urged improving workplace ventilation in some areas of the plant. and they recommended that the department of energy improve its supervision of worker health and safety by assigning a health physicist to the plant
the investigators lauded westinghouse, however, for improving worker health and safety since taking over operation of the plant in january 1986 from the previous contractor, national lead of ohio
westinghouse spokesman pete kelley said the report made no major criticisms of his company
westinghouse has responded to the federal report by banning smoking, eating and drinking in the radiological sampling area, kelley said. leaving respirators in potentially contaminated areas is a violation of westinghouse policies, he added
the spokesman also noted that westinghouse has increased the staff of health physicists since it took over the plant's operation
a confident george bush predicted saturday that victory in the illinois primary election tuesday would ``cinch the republican nomination'' for him
campaigning in the heavily republican northwest chicago suburbs, the vice president preached gop unity and all but ignored his rival candidates, kansas sen. bob dole and former tv evangelist pat robertson
i want to be your president,'' bush said to a cheering crowd at st. viator high school. ``i do not want to do it by tearing some other republican, by weakening the party that needs to be together.''
bush so far has won 705 of the 1,139 delegates needed to win the gop nomination
dole and robertson also campaigned in illinois saturday, with dole conceding, ``we're hanging by our fingernails.''
bush, appearing with his wife, barbara, illinois gov. james r. thompson and pilot chuck yeager, began his day with a breakfast appearance before the barrington area chamber of commerce, before speaking to a partisan audience of about 600 at mchenry county college
you give me this vote on tuesday and it seems to me i will cinch the republican nomination,'' bush said
the vice president was buoyed by results of a chicago tribune poll published its sunday editions. the poll of 504 republicans showed bush ahead of dole 62 percent to 28 percent among those likely to vote tuesday
robertson was a distant third with 6 percent
the survey, conducted in the past week, had a margin of error of plus or minus five percentage points
bush has rejected dole's bid for a face-to-face debate in illinois
on saturday, he talked mostly about what he would do if he captures the white house
on the deficit, we've got to whip it,'' he said, promising not to raise taxes to do it
it is public enemy no. 1. the answer to the deficit is simple, hold the line on taxes. you're not paying too little in taxes, we're spending too much in congress,'' he said
libyan leader col. moammar gadhafi stood before a cheering crowd saturday and tore up a list of names of libyans banned from travel abroad and ordered their passports returned, the libyan news agency jana reported
gadhafi was quoted as telling a mass gathering in front of the passport office in the capital, tripoli, that ``there must be no citizen jailed or banned from traveling abroad ... in the society of freedom.''
the jana report, monitored in rome, did not say how many names were on the list gadhafi destoyred. it said destruction of the list and the return of the passports were another step in the ``festival of freedom'' that began when gadhafi ``stormed the prison, demolishing it and liberating the prisoners.''
earlier this month, gadhafi used a bulldozer to knock down the wall at a prison in tripoli to release prisoners as part of an amnesty he declared. jana said 400 prisoners were freed
it also said 130 foreigners of various nationalities were released from prison last monday
in london, the foreign office said james abra, a 59-year-old british engineer employed by the british electronics firm plessey company, would be freed sunday. abra has been serving a life sentence for alleged spying
he was arrested june 20, 1985, at the tripoli airport
murray m. ``buddy'' weiss, a former editor of the international herald tribune, died of cardiac arrest saturday at arlington hospital in this washington suburb, his wife said. he was 64
weiss, who was working for the u.s. information agency at the time of his death, had suffered a stroke friday while playing tennis, said fred farris, the u.s. editor for the herald tribune
the new york native served as the editor of the paris-based newspaper from its creation in 1966 until february 1979, said his wife, margaret sunde weiss of falls church, va
weiss had received his undergraduate degree from new york university and a graduate degree from new york university, and during world war ii, he served with the 8th and 9th army air force from 1942-45, she said
in 1946, he joined the new york herald tribune as a copy boy and moved up the ranks during the next 20 years, eventually becoming managing editor, the job he held when the paper folded in 1966, she said
at one point during his tenure there, he took off six months to work for the new york times, where he helped plan that newspaper's west coast edition, mrs. weiss said
after the new york herald tribune closed and before becoming editor of the international herald tribune, he spent six months as assistant publisher for the boston herald and the boston traveler
when he left the international herald tribune, he returned to the united states and became editor of the advocate in stamford, conn., until 1981, when he became managing editor of parade magazine. he left parade in december 1983 and joined usia the next month, she said
at usia, he was in charge of the news file that is distributed to all u.s. embassies and diplomatic missions around the world, farris said
in addition to his wife, weiss is survived by a daughter, brenna weiss of new york city, son dieter weiss of marietta, ga., two grandsons and two sisters, phyllis weiss golden of east orange, n.j. and natalie weiss davis of remsenburg, n.y
a car with a device stored in the trunk containing mildly radioactive material was stolen, and the thieves could be harmed if they tampered with the devide, federal officials said saturday
the car, which was stolen thursday night, had a measuring device containing cesium-137 and americium-241, said karl abraham, a spokesman for the nuclear regulatory commission in philadelphia
abraham said the material was inside a 30-inch-high yellow plastic case bearing a ``radioactive'' label and a federal department of transportation sticker
it's perfectly safe to pick up and carry the case around,'' abraham said. ``the radioactive sources are not all that powerful.''
the substances were part of a moisture density gauge that measures the compaction and moisture content of materials used in constructing roads, abraham said. the car is owned by an employee of soils engineering services co. in whippany
a person ``would have to tamper with it and take the radioactive sources out of a safe container and carry them in one's hands for several hours before there would be the possibility of radioactive injuries,'' said abraham. endorsement</head>
sen. paul simon, facing the pivotal battle of his presidential campaign, accused democratic rival michael dukakis on saturday of trying to buy the illinois primary with tv commericials
the simon campaign, already cash-poor, also was buffeted by the results of a new poll showing the illinois senator's support slipping in his home state just three days before the election
he also lost key newspaper endorsements _ to dukakis in the chicago sun-times and to tennessee sen. albert gore jr. in the chicago tribune
still, simon pressed on, enlisting three congressional allies from industrial states with pending primaries to push his theme that the post-super tuesday campaign marked the start of a second phase in the nominating process
simon attacked the massachusetts governor for a new television advertising assault that simon's campaign views as a swipe at their candidate
you ought to win an election _ not buy an election,'' simon said at a news conference at de paul university
the dukakis ads do not name simon but criticize his strategy of remaining in the race until the democratic convention in july in hopes of being the consensus candidate in a brokered nomination
simon said he will not respond with his own television commercials
whatever decision the people of illinois make, i urge that you not sell your heritage for a 30-second commercial,'' simon said. ``the question illinois voters must ask themselves is not who has the slick commercials, but who can best represent us in the presidency.''
u.s. rep. stephen solarz, campaigning for simon in chicago, said the illinois primary would be either ``the political equivalent of custer's last stand or the battle of gettysburg'' for simon
i trust and hope that for paul simon the illinois primary on tuesday will be the political equivalent of the battle of gettysburg, marking the turning point in the campaign leading to his ultimate nomination at the (democratic) convention,'' solarz, d-n.y., said
but the sunday editions of the chicago tribune brought bad news for the simon campaign. simon shrugged off the paper's endorsement of gore, but the poll results showed further erosion in his support among registered democratic voters
in the poll of 501 democrats, 35 percent supported simon, 30 percent favored illinois' other favorite son, jesse jackson, and 18 percent liked dukakis
the results made the race essentially a dead heat between simon and jackson because the poll, conducted march 9 and 10, has an error margin of plus or minus 5 percentage points
otto von habsburg, ex-pretender to the austrian throne, made a triumphant return saturday to the former imperial hofburg palace, from which his ancestors ruled a vast empire for centuries
the son of the last austrian emperor, karl i, von habsburg was greeted with cheers and a standing ovation by about 1,600 people crowded into a main hall
uniformed students threw their caps into the air and a brass band played as von habsburg entered the hall
von habsburg, 75, made the appearance to mark the 50th anniversary of the annexation of austria by nazi germany and addressed the crowd as president of the international pan-european union
the habsburg family ruled much of central europe for more than 600 years. the monarchy was abolished in 1918 at the end of world war i. otto von habsburg was barred from austria until 1961 when he renounced his claim to the non-existent throne
most members of the pan-european union in austria and parts of west germany are elderly monarchists. one of their declared goals is the unification of western and eastern europe without the soviet union
von habsburg's eldest son, karl, is head of the union's austrian branch and welcomed guests to the palace gathering
speakers condemned the nazi rule of austria and referred to van habsburg as ``royal highness.''
none of the speakers mentioned president kurt waldheim, who has come under increasing pressure to resign because of allegations about his past while serving in the german army in the balkans during world war ii
in his speech, von habsburg said, ``the past shows that diversity can only be preserved in unity. a good example for that was the old austria, that community of danube peoples, in which many nations were united economically and politically.''
von habsburg holds a west german passport. he is still a subject of controversy between austrian conservatives and socialistts
a u.s. military team flew to vietnam saturday to discuss the southeast asian nation's accounting of americans listed as missing in action from the vietnam war, a u.s. official said
the regularly scheduled talks in hanoi follow vietnam's repatriation on march 2 of what it believed were the remains of 17 american mias
it was the largest turnover in two years and the fourth largest since the war ended in april 1975 with a communist victory over u.s.-backed south vietnam. the united states lists nearly 1,800 americans as missing in vietnam during the war
ross petzing, a spokesman at the u.s. embassy in bangkok, said the team is composed of six experts from the joint casualty resolution center and the army central identification laboratory, both based in hawaii
the team is presenting cases on americans missing from the war in indochina for vietnamese investigation,'' petzing said
he said the talks with foreign ministry officials, scheduled to extend through tuesday, would be the fourth round of technical discussions since vietnam agreed last august to resume cooperation on the issue
as part of the agreement, a u.s. medical team visited vietnam earlier this month to study how private american assistance could help war-disabled vietnamese
a 73-year-old woman was found alive and apparently unharmed saturday after spending as many as four nights locked in her car trunk by an alleged kidnapper, state police said
martha bushnell of arkville was rescued from the trunk of her compact car shortly before 9:30 a.m., about three hours after a 33-year-old woman was arrested on a charge of kidnapping her
police believe bushnell had been in the trunk since tuesday night, with no food or water and with overnight temperatures dipping below freezing, said state police sgt. al dorer in middletown
she was lucid and coherent when she was found and did not appear to be injured, but she was admitted to st. luke's hospital in newburgh, police said. ``she was in pretty good condition, considering her ordeal,'' said dorer. the hospital would not release details on her status saturday evening
investigators were questioning her to determine what had happened, according to state police sgt. bob parlett in ithaca. details of the incident were still sketchy saturday, and police would not speculate on a motive
police had initiated a statewide search for bushnell after her car was seen parked on a newburgh street wednesday morning, said dorer. two girls had heard cries for help from the car and had flagged down a taxi driver to help. the driver called police, but when they arrived the car was gone, dorer said
parlett said bushnell, who lives alone, had last been seen around noon tuesday at the valkyrian motel in fleischmanns, where she works part-time
at 6:30 a.m. saturday, authorities arrested jamesetta marie strong, 33, of otego, after acquaintances reported seeing her driving the bushnell car in the newburgh area, parlett said
police found the car later saturday morning in the parking lot of a knitting mill, dorer said
when they popped the trunk, there she was,'' dorer said. ``the first words out of her mouth were `thank you.'''
strong was sent to otsego county jail without bail after being arraigned on a charge of first-degree kidnapping, parlett said
yunis khalis, the chief of the seven-party afghan opposition alliance, resigned saturday for health reasons, an alliance statement said
it gave no further details and did not announce a replacement
the statment said the hezbi islami party, which khalis heads, will remain in the alliance and did not say if khalis also resigned as party leader
his resignation came less than a week after another rebel leader quit the alliance over plans to form an interim afghan government when soviet troops withdraw from the country
but sibghatullah mojaddedi, head of the national liberation front, rejoined the alliance three days after resigning
khalis, a moslem clergyman, was born in 1919 in the village of gandumak in the afghan province of nangarhar. he was elected to head the alliance in october 1987. most of the alliance members have headquarters in pakistan
recent developments within the alliance coincide with united nations-sponsored talks in geneva between pakistan and afghanistan's marxist government to end the afghan war and and pave the way for the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 soviet military personnel
the soviets intervened in december 1979 to help the government battle the anti-communist guerrillas
the rebels are suported by the united states, china and pakistan
vice president george bush would defeat massachusetts gov. michael dukakis if the presidential election were held today, according to a newsweek poll released saturday
but a growing number of people think bush should disclose more about the iran-contra affair, the poll showed
seventy-four percent of the respondents said they are pleased with the field of candidates now running and would not like to see an undeclared candidate enter the race, the survey showed
republican bush would get 49 percent of the vote to democrat dukakis' 43 percent if the general election were held today, the survey indicated
for the poll, the gallup organization interviewed 755 voters by telephone thursday and friday. the margin of error was plus or minus four percentage points
bush would win 55 percent to 37 percent if matched against democratic sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, while the vice president would win 58 percent to 35 percent if jesse jackson were the democratic nominee, the poll said
in a race between dukakis and republican sen. bob dole of kansas, dukakis got 45 percent and dole 44 percent, within the poll's margin of error. dole would defeat gore, 53 percent to 34 percent; and defeat jackson 58 percent to 32 percent, the poll showed
according to the survey, 50 percent of the respondents said bush should tell the public more about the role he played in the sales of arms to iran and the diversion of profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels, and 42 percent said he had done enough explaining
a newsweek poll taken in january showed respondents split evenly at 44 percent on the issue
bush got higher marks for being ``strong and forceful'' in this survey than he did in polls taken by the magazine two months ago and in october 1987. in the post-super tuesday poll, 46 percent of the respondents agreed with that description of the vice president, compared with 36 percent in the two previous polls
five buses used to transport workers at a nuclear power plant were set afire saturday night, two days after the government said construction could resume there, the ansa news agency said
the italian agency said the buses were burned inside the compound of the montalto di castro nuclear plant and were owned by the central nuclear consortium, which is building the facility 50 miles north of rome
strong socialist party opposition to resuming construction at the plant was one factor that led to the resignation of christian democrat premier giovanni goria friday night
goria, leader of the coalition government since august, resigned twice before, the last time in february, but agreed to stay on to help pass the national budget. the budget was passed thursday and goria had been expected to resign next week. politicial leaders said he decided to quit immediately because of the controversy over construction at the plant here
the government announced a moratorium on construction at the plant last november after voters in a non-binding referendum expressed their disapproval of nuclear power facilities
on thursday the government said construction could resume at the plant, which already has cost italy $5 billion
a huge chemical fire emitting potentially dangerous fumes forced the evacuation of about 500 residents for a time saturday as it destroyed a huge warehouse and set fire to two homes
ten people including seven firefighters were injured in the fire at the werco chemical warehouse complex, authorities said
the evacuees were allowed to return home later in the day but were instructed to boil drinking water into sunday, said lynn behringer, spokeswoman for the will county emergency services and disaster agency
strong winds blew smoke and sparks directly into the downtown area of rockdale, a town of about 2,000 residents southwest of chicago, and exploding chemicals punctuated the flames
it looked like the fourth of july,'' said mrs. behringer. ``considering the magnitude of this fire and the number of homes so close, we are very lucky.'' of the two homes set ablaze, one was heavily damaged
the warehouse complex, which covered several square blocks, stored some 60 kinds of chemicals for various businesses
village president donald b. gould said police began evacuating residents about 5 a.m. because of the potential danger from the fumes, although the identity of the full range of chemicals was not known. the evacuation area eventually covered two square miles, officials said
after the evacuation order was lifted, residents were told to boil drinking water because of low water pressure from the firefighting
the cause of the fire and the dollar loss were not immediately determined
seven firefighters and three other people were treated and released at hospitals in joliet and morris, spokesmen said
the sandinista government announced saturday it has formally agreed to hold the first cease-fire talks inside nicaragua with rebel leaders
it said the talks will be held march 21-23 in the southern frontier post of sapoa, 90 miles south of managua
president daniel ortega ordered local civilian and military authorities in the area ``to lend all facilities to the delegation of the counterrevolution'' to enter and leave the country freely at the pena blanca border crossing, according to a statement issued by his office
the statement said the government would assume all responsibility for the security of the rebel delegation during the negotiations and cross-border traffic would not be affected
adolfo calero, the top political leader of the nicaraguan resistance, is expected to head the delegation from the rebels, known as contras. nicaraguan resistance is an umbrella organization of rebel group
ortega previously announced that his brother, defense minister humberto ortega, would lead the government delegation
the sapoa meeting also will be the first between the two sides without a mediator
calero told the associated press recently that the sapoa talks would take place with ``an open agenda.'' he said joao baena soares, secretary general of the organization of american states, and roman catholic cardinal miguel obando y bravo would attend as witnesses
obando y bravo, the archbishop of managua, mediated previous talks held in the dominican republic and guatemala
calero said a representative of nicaragua's internal opposition also would be invited to attend. a contra representative in miami, who spoke with the condition he not be identified, told ap saturday the nicaraguan resistance still was insisting that a domestic opponent of the sandinistas be present at the talks as an observer
ortega's statement did not mention that demand
both sides had tentatively agreed to meet in sapoa for three days of direct negotiations beginning march 9. ortega canceled that schedule after the rebels said they would not attend without preliminary discussions
ortega dismissed obando y bravo as mediator on march 2 after the cardinal proposed an agenda that included discussion of internal politics
the contras previously had insisted on the presence of obando y bravo, a frequent critic of the left-wing government
contra spokesmen also insisted ortega's government agree to discuss the political points outlined by obando y bravo during the last cease-fire talks held feb. 18 in guatemala
the cardinal's plan would have required the sandinistas to grant amnesty to political prisoners, restore full press freedom, open talks with internal opposition political parties and review the military draft law
the sandinistas have refused to discuss internal political issues with the contras, saying the only purpose of the talks is to work out a cease-fire in accordance with the regional peace plan signed aug. 7 by the presidents of the five central american countries
roger guevara, secretary of the nicaraguan democratic coordinate, a coalition of opposition political parties and business and labor groups, said his organization would send a representative to the talks but as a participant, not as an observer
in a broadcast over the rebels' radio liberacion, guevara said ``in spite of the fact there does not exist an official invitation, the coordinate is ready to assist in this reunion.''
obando y bravo told local reporters saturday he was willing to attend as a witness. ``i would like these talks to advance so that they redound to the benefit of the nicaraguan people,'' he said
jesse jackson won the democratic precinct caucuses saturday in his native south carolina, giving his campaign a push just before a pivotal primary in illinois, the state he has adopted as his home
jackson jumped to an early lead and held it, receiving his only competition from a bloc of uncommitted party members, whose numbers lagged far behind those of his supporters. protest</head> robert blake among celebrities, corrects spelling of kasem, sted casem; note that detainees bused to tonopah before being released. pickup 9th graf pvs, `authorities took...</note>
more than 1,100 anti-nuclear protesters, including actress teri garr, actor robert blake, disc jockey casey kasem and activist daniel ellsberg were arrested saturday at the nation's nuclear testing grounds
nye county authorities estimated the crowd of protesters at 3,000, well below the 5,000 to 10,000 organizers predicted would come to the remote site 65 miles northwest of las vegas
saturday's demonstration, dubbed ``reclaim the test site,'' was part of a 10-day protest at the site through march 20. by late afternoon the number of arrests had reached 1,136 and continued to grow, said department of energy spokesman chris west
protesters climbed barbed wire fences surrounding the 1,350-square-mile site, began walking across the desolate desert and were arrested by waiting authorities. some 300 officers from the nevada highway patrol, nye county sheriff's office and department of energy security were on hand
miss garr, blake, ellsberg and kasem were arrested when they stepped across a cattle guard on the road leading to the main entrance of the desert site
the crowd cheered as each group of protesters stepped across the guard
miss garr was asked if she thought joining the protest would hurt her movie career. ``i hope not,'' she said. ``i don't think you have to be a fanatic to think nuclear weapons are going to annihilate the earth.''
those arrested were placed in two large enclosures, then bused to tonopah and released, west said. all were cited for misdemeanor trespass. authorities no longer prosecute misdemeanor arrests for trespassing
authorities took extra precautions for the rally, building an 8-foot chain-link enclosure topped with barbed wire to hold detainees
americans for nuclear testing held a counterdemonstration saturday, but organizer peggy konold said she expected her group to be far outnumbered by the anti-nuclear protesters
protests at the site have been common in recent years. jesse cocks, an organizer with the american peace test, said her organization counted 2,547 trespassing arrests in 1987
with 38 percent of the state's 1,788 precincts reporting, jackson won 3,455 county convention delegates for 48 percent, followed by uncommitted with 1,643 delegates for 23 percent
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. was in third place with 1,434 delegates for 20 percent
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, missouri rep. richard gephardt and illinois sen. paul simon all trailed with support measured in single digits
the outcome of the precinct caucuses will affect how 44 of the state's delegates to the democratic national convention will be allocated
before saturday's caucuses jackson already had won 400.55 national convention delegates, second only to dukakis, who had 460.5
divine, the outlandish 375-pound cult film star, was eulogized for his talent, gentle manner and individuality during funeral services saturday that attracted hundreds of fans, friends and colleagues
he was a friend, business partner, co-conspirator and actor who could say the words i wrote better than anybody,'' said john waters, who directed divine in such cult classics as ``pink flamingoes,'' ``polyester,'' ``lust in the dust,'' and the just-released ``hairspray.''
how many people at age 42 love their job as much as he did? he was happy, talented, successful, and a true original,'' water told mourners, some with rainbow-hued hair and others in suits and ties, at a funeral home in this baltimore suburb
divine, a lutherville, md., native whose real name was harris glenn milstead, died monday in his bed at the hollywood regency plaza hotel in los angeles. the los angeles county coroner's officer determined he died of an enlarged heart due to obesity. the friday before his death a doctor had said divine was in perfect health except for his weight, which had been a problem for the actor all his life
divine was known mostly for his outrageous roles as loud and foul-mouthed women in waters' films, although he also played a male sidney greenstreet-type character in the 1985 film ``trouble in mind.''
the rev. leland higginbotham, pastor of the calvary baptist church to which the milstead family belonged, described divine's youth as an ``agonizing period'' during which the budding actor ``took a painful and circuitous road to find himself and his talents.''
divine's popularity had grown with ``hairspray,'' a relatively mainstream film that was attracting more traditional movie audiences. waters said divine was thrilled with the success, noting that ``people who had hassled him in high school were asking for his autograph.''
flowers were sent by such entertainers as whoopi goldberg, elton john, and the cast of fox television's ``married ... with children,'' the program on which he was scheduled to appear the day after his death. update with 2-3 minute glitch on tv program; picks up 10th graf pvs bgng, `a poll'</note>
kansas sen. bob dole, saying ``the issues are more important than the odds,'' went on television for 30 minutes saturday in an effort to reverse the decline in his presidential prospects
standing in front of a portrait of abraham lincoln, dole said, ``i know i'm the underdog in this race. the issues are more important than the odds. ... i didn't expect this job to be handed to me in the first place.''
dole spoke from alumni hall at knox college which was the site of the fifth of the seven debates in 1858 between lincoln and stephen douglas during their campaign for the senate. dole's address was televised in illinois
vice president george bush, who has refused to respond to a dole challenge for a one-on-one debate before the illinois primary on tuesday, was the featured speaker at a dinner on the campus shortly after the dole program aired
dole spoke as a new survey said bush was the choice of 62 percent of likely republican primary voters. only 28 percent named dole as their choice
it just seems to me we should have had a debate,'' said dole. ``my opponent is less than 100 yards away as i speak.''
actually, bush was not scheduled to arrive until after dole left
nothing has ever come easy for bob,'' said his wife, elizabeth. ``his only inheritance was the love of his parents.''
ladies and gentlemen, you're going to be voting tuesday and we want you to know more about bob dole's life,'' she said, introducing a 14-minute segment from a biographical sketch filmed for showing to dole campaign meetings
but her remarks were never seen by wgn viewers because of a technical problem that cut off the live picture for about two to three minutes, said raymond kirk, the master controller for the tv station
the station froze the last live shot of dole and kept it on the screen while viewers also heard his voice
then the station switched to the biographical sketch, bypassing mrs. dole's introduction. the program concluded without further problems
a poll published in the sunday edition of the chicago tribune said the vice president was the choice of 62 percent of republicans likely to vote in tuesday's primary. dole was named by 28 percent and pat robertson by 6 percent
the survey of 504 likely gop voters was conducted wednesday and thursday
during campaign appearances on friday, dole conceded he was ``hanging by our fingernails.''
the senator, who took a drubbing on super tuesday this past week, losing 16 of 16 primaries to bush, needed a victory in illinois to maintain any faint hope that he can stage a comeback in the presidential race
bush, campaigning in northwest chicago suburbs, predicted saturday that victory in the illinois primary election tuesday would ``cinch the republican nomination'' for him
the vice president preached gop unity and all but ignored dole and robertson
i want to be your president,'' bush said to a cheering crowd at st. viator high school. ``i do not want to do it by tearing some other republican, by weakening the party that needs to be together.''
the latest associated press delegate count gave bush 705 and dole 163. a total of 1,139 delegate votes would be needed at the gop convention in new orleans next august to win the presidential nomination
larry mccarthy, communications director for the dole campaign, said $100,000 was spent to purchase one half-hour on chicago television station wgn and additional time slots sunday and monday on other stations around the state. he said the amount also covered the production costs
campaign manager william e. brock said the broadcast would be repeated sunday on other stations around the state
brock also said that contrary to earlier statements from campaign officials, other dole commercials were running in illinois
earlier in the week, the campaign had said that all commercials in a total buy of $500,000 had been pulled off the air
brock said some were pulled off, but others _ biographical spots portraying dole as a strong leader _ were continuing to run. he said some commercials were dropped when it was decided to use part of the media budget for the half hour program
we need to somehow capture the attention of the illinois voters,'' said dole, who has repeatedly challenged bush to a one-on-one debate. the vice president brushed off the challenge, saying he already has participated in seven debates and called them ``cruel and unusual punishment.''
the only encouragement dole could get from the tribune poll was the response when republicans were asked if they agreed with the statement that it was ``important for the republicans that bob dole does well in illinois so that the republican presidential campaign continues.'' a total of 56 percent said they agreed, while 30 percent said they disagreed
other findings strongly favored bush
when people were asked which candidate they considered ``tough, a strong leader,'' 45 percent named bush and 32 percent dole
jim and tammy bakker's ptl-owned five-level house will be put on the auction block on april 12, with the minimum price set at $995,000
the money will go to help the ptl ministry based in nearby fort mill pay its debts
dave huneycutt of lake wylie realtors said he's had about 55 inquiries about the house since the auction notice appeared tuesday. they include ``doctors, lawyers, well-known sports promoters and very successful independent business people,'' he said
the 10,226-square-foot house was built in 1976 and enlarged four times after ptl bought it in 1981 as a parsonage for the bakkers and their two children
the master bedroom has his and hers bathroom suites, connected by a sunken whirlpool tub. the tub is flanked by a glass-enclosed rock garden. faucet handles are in the shape of long-neck swans
the bakkers apparently shared a 600-square-foot carpeted clothes closet that adjoined her dressing room. large mirrors abound _ in the music room, the exercise room, the bathrooms and other areas
the house has a commercial kitchen with heavy-duty appliances, two additional kitchens and at least 25 closets. electronically controlled draperies and curtains are in most major rooms, including his study and the master bedroom
the massive house sits at the bottom of a steep hill and fronts lake wylie in one of tega cay's most exclusive sections
the grounds include a two-story playhouse that is heated and air-conditioned, a guardhouse, boardwalks to a white sandy beach at the water's edge, and a large dock where the bakkers once kept their 58-foot houseboat and small power cruiser
the bakkers left the home last june, three months after bakker admitted to a 1980 sexual encounter with church secretary jessica hahn and resigned
the bakker home is one of 10 ptl properties that will be sold april 12 at the tega cay country club, according to auctioneer rodney robinson. councils</head>
the government placed colombia's 150,000-member armed forces on alert as voters prepare to vote sunday to elect mayors for the first time since independence from spain 169 years ago
the campaign to elect mayors in 1,008 municipalities has drawn violence from leftist guerrillas, drug traffickers and right-wing death squads. the election is the first real challenge to upper-class control of local government
until now colombia's mayors, with the exception of bogota, have been named by governors, who are appointed by the president. the president chose the mayor of bogota
in the election, colombians also will choose 10,543 councilmen, 421 state assembly representatives and 89 assemblymen from remote territories
national police were included in the military alert. all leaves and days off were canceled
broadcast reports said soldiers were patrolling cities and towns from the amazon jungle area in the south to the guajira desert region in the north
in the capital of bogota, a city of 6 million people, jeeps mounted with machine guns cruised streets and police stopped cars and searched them for guns and explosives
leftist guerrillas and right-wing death squads have killed scores of political activists in the last year
two months ago drug traffickers kidnapped bogota's leading mayoral candidate, andres pastrana, because he had spoken out for stronger action against the traffickers. police later freed pastrana, the son of former president misael pastrana
polls have indicated that pastrana, the only conservative party candidate, will win
the liberal party mayoral candidates in bogota are bernardo ossa, who was president virgilio barco's emissary for talks with leftist guerrillas; juan caicedo, former president of colombia's federation of businessmen, and jorge eastman, a former cabinet minister
newspaper polls indicate that the leading contenders among lower-class voters are two women
one, maria eugenia rojas, running as an independent, is the daughter of a 1950s military dictator, gustavo rojas pinilla
the other woman is clara lopez, an independent supported by the patriotic union party, which was formed three years ago by leftist guerrillas
the patriotic union's president, bernardo jaramillo ossa, predicted his party will win 25 mayoral posts
in a broadcast interview saturday with the colombian radio chain rcn, he called upon his leftist coalition party ``to overcome fear and threats'' and go to the polls
right-wing death squads have killed 520 members of the party since it was formed in 1985 with the help of colombia's estimated 10,000 leftist guerrillas
the government of former president belisario betancur, in an effort to negotiate peace, allowed the rebels to form the party. betancur's government also agreed to election of mayors, a goal of colombia's leftists
leftist guerrillas claimed responsibility saturday for detonating two car bombs in a trendy shopping and restaurant area
the peace of the rich has ended, the war of the poor has begun,'' said a communique issued by the farabundo marti national liberation front, an alliance of five leftist guerrilla groups that has been fighting to overthrow el salvador's u.s.-backed government for the past eight years
two car bombs went off friday night in the pink zone, a fashionable neighborhood of sidewalk cafes and restaurants. two people were injured
the statement said the blasts targeted ``those who daily plan the repressive campaign against campesinos, those who fly the helicopters and planes, the diplomats, marines of the u.s. embassy, and the demagogues who design electoral campaigns.''
the campaigns mentioned referred to legislative and municipal elections scheduled for march 20
these individuals have never felt the consequences of misery and exploitation and, being parasites, much less have felt the ravages of the dirty war they impose on the humble people. with this action we intend to make them feel, if only a little, this war they direct comfortably from afar,'' said the communique
an anonymous caller told the radio station ysu where to find the communique, and a reporter for the station picked it up
one of the bombs exploded just a few feet from where leftist guerrillas killed 13 people, among them six americans, in a machine gun attack in june 1985
a 12-year-old boy and a middle-aged man were slightly wounded in the first explosion friday. the other bomb exploded about five minutes later in a parking lot behind a pizza hut restaurant, causing no injuries
an armed forces spokesman consulted by the associated press said explosives experts were studying the vehicles' remains
the conservative daily la prensa grafica on saturday had attributed the blasts to the farabundo marti national liberation front
the object of these actions ... is to demonstrate that the terrorists continue attacking the citizenry in an effort to disrupt the elections,'' said the paper
one blast destroyed three vehicles and shattered windows
it occurred in front of a restaurant that adjoined the cafe where four off-duty u.s. marines and two american businessmen were killed along with seven salvadorans in 1985. leftist guerrillas claimed responsibility for that attack
gallaudet university's embattled board of trustees planned to meet sunday to discuss picking a new president for the school for the deaf just days after massive student protests prompted the hearing person chosen for that post to resign
students at the nation's only liberal arts school for the deaf said saturday they hoped the meeting will bring about their demand for the nation's first deaf university president
the university was shut down for five days last week by student protests after elisabeth a. zinser _ who can hear and does not know sign language _ was appointed by the board last sunday over two deaf candidates
faced with student outrage, zinser stepped down early friday. ``my decision to resign was reached with great difficulty as i came to understand how deeply some see the social stature of deaf persons reflected in the presidency of this university,'' she said in a statement
the two deaf candidates who were bypassed last week are being reconsidered for the position. they are harvey j. corson, 44, superintendent of the louisiana school for the deaf in baton rouge and a gallaudet board member; and i. king jordan, 45, dean of gallaudet's college of arts and sciences. both are gallaudet graduates
students in the deaf president now committee last night asked for mediation with the board to resolve the students demands:
that a deaf president be appointed from the two finalists; that board chairwoman jane bassett spilman resign from the board of trustees effective immediately; that the bylaws of the board of trustees be amended to reflect a majority of deaf voting members, to be achieved within a specific period of time; and that no reprisals be taken at any time against any student, faculty or staff member of gallaudet university.''
gallaudet has never had a deaf president in its 124-year history. the college was founded by congress in 1864, and became a university by an act of congress in 1986
the federally supported institution receives 75 percent of its budget from congress
romare bearden, a pre-eminent american artist whose collages fashioned stories about the dignity of black people and southern living, died saturday. he was 75
bearden died about 1 a.m. at new york hospital of complications from bone cancer, diagnosed two years ago, and a stroke suffered last month, said his manager of 13 years, june kelly
works by bearden, who was awarded the national medal of arts by president reagan last june, fetched prices at sotheby's up to $56,000, among the highest prices paid for works by black artists in the united states
bearden's work ranged from political cartoons published in 1934 to water colors and eventually the collages. he had one-man shows at the museum of modern art and several top galleries
he was a lover of jazz who did sets and costumes for the alvin ailey dance theater, and murals for the baltimore and pittsburgh transit systems
i think certainly that he's one of the great masters of the 20th century, especially over the last 40 years,'' said lowery sims, associate curator of 20th century art at the metropolitan museum of art
sims said bearden's work in collages ``raised it to such a fine art it's hard to think of any other artist who is so closely associated with that medium.''
sims, who compared his use of form and color to that of henri matisse, said bearden's work had an unparalleled ability ``to provide us with a heroic depiction of even the most mundane aspects of american black life.''
i think that he was trying to make us conscious of the richness of part of the black heritage we wouldn't think ordinarily of,'' sims said. ``i think he made us aware that we are a very important part of american culture.''
in the book, ``the art of romare bearden,'' by john a. williams, bearden said, ``i work out of a response and need to redefine the image of man in the terms of the negro experience i know best.''
ralph ellison, author of ``invisible man'' and a friend from the 1930s, said that in the artist's work, ``restlessness was not frivolous, it was the discovery of the self, of the paintings, of the design.''
bearden, who was born in charlotte, n.c., grew up in harlem and in pittsburgh. he attended boston university and new york university, majoring in mathematics and planning to become a doctor. he started drawing in college and cartoons published in the afro american, a weekly, led to his career in art
he gained prominence in the 1940s after his work was included in a show by black artists in washington in 1943
he is survived by his wife, nanette. a memorial service was being planned for later in the month. both busloads of nebraska children now home, sted one, adds new wisconsin snowfall figures, other detail. no pickup.</note>
a major snowstorm that dumped up to 7 feet of snow shut down travel in the upper midwest saturday and whipped up 15-foot waves on lake superior, while crews worked to reopen highways across the plains where hundreds of people had been snowbound for two days
it's a little better than yesterday but not much,'' said roberta welsh, nebraska state patrol dispatcher at scottsbluff
a south dakota woman was killed saturday when her car skidded and rolled over on an icy interstate, the state highway patrol said
high school basketball fans spent the night stuck in a minnesota arena after a regional playoff, and two busloads of nebraska schoolchildren snowbound at isolated farms got to go home
up to 7 feet of snow stranded skiers on terry peak in south dakota's black hills and 15-foot drifts were reported near badlands national park. in the hard-hit nebraska panhandle, 31 inches of snow was reported at chadron, with 10-foot drifts at crawford
the cheyenne county, neb., sheriff's department worked through the night and all day saturday to reach people believed stranded in vehicles in the sidney area, said dispatcher harlan sage
we'll be lucky if we don't find someone out in the country ... dead possibly,'' said kimball ambulance director jim o'brien and kimball county sheriff john thacker jr. they said the storm was the worst to hit western nebraska in at least 18 years
an elderly couple from springview, neb., were rescued saturday by a relative on a snowmobile after spending the night stuck in their pickup, said keya paha county sheriff gary sell
blowing snow kept visibility down to about one-quarter of a mile around o'neill, neb., forcing the town to cancel its annual st. patrick's day celebration, said holt county sheriff's dispatcher arlene fox
more than a foot of snow fell saturday in sections of northern and central minnesota, and it was whipped up by 50 mph wind that closed the duluth airport for six hours. waves estimated at 15 feet topped some seawalls along lake superior, the national weather service said
hundreds of hutchinson high school girls' basketball fans, including the school band, were stranded overnight in mankato, minn., by snow and zero visibility after a victory in regional playoffs. the seven busloads of fans stayed in mankato state university's arena while the team got motel rooms. the motel said they checked out saturday morning
up to 10 inches of wet snow was dumped on northern wisconsin, miring countless vehicles on highways near lake superior
it looks like everybody's on an ego trip, wanting to see how far they can go'' before their cars get stuck, said police capt. jerry moe at superior, wis., just across the lake from duluth
snow also fell across northern michigan. ``we're getting a blizzard,'' said state police sgt. larry brown at st. ignace at the southeastern tip of the upper peninsula
on terry peak in the black hills, skiers had been snowbound since thursday, and terry peak lodge manager bob ekeren said 7 feet of snow had fallen by saturday. ``we're out of bread and meat and potatoes. we're making soup.''
there's three, four feet of snow on top of cars. we can't even find them,'' ekeren said at the lodge, at an elevation of 6,700 feet
crews in wyoming, nebraska and south dakota worked saturday to reopen roads that had been closed by drifting snow and zero visibility, some since thursday
more than 200 miles of interstate 80 across wyoming and into western nebraska reopened saturday and north-south i-25 was reopened in wyoming. but many other roads in eastern wyoming remained closed, the highway patrol said
the reopening of i-80 allowed travel for the first time since thursday out of kimball, neb., where some 700 people had been holed up by saturday in motels, private homes and the kimball county courthouse. ``we're getting some people down the road,'' said carl farmer of the sheriff's office
conditions in kimball were ``a tad better. we can see across the street but we've got a long ways to go,'' said a woman who answered the phone at the kimball civil defense office saturday morning
a 200-mile section of i-94 in north dakota, closed friday afternoon, was reopened saturday. parts of a 265-mile section of i-90 in south dakota were reopened but a 75-mile section between kadoka and ellsworth air force base remained closed, with 15-foot drifts in the kadoka area, said highway patrol lt. ed assman
residents of rapid city, s.d., began digging out under bright sunshine but some people were stranded in their homes with drifts up to the second floor
the storm caused the south dakota democratic party to postpone a statewide caucus called for saturday, when the party was to decide how to apportion 15 of the state's national convention delegates. the caucus was rescheduled for the following saturday
two busloads of children who had been stranded in isolated farmhouses in western nebraska since thursday got home safely saturday afternoon. the 21 children were being driven home from school when the sudden blizzard caught the drivers by surprise
road crews reached driver sharon grubbs and her riders, ages 7 to 13, saturday at the farm of jack and karen holt, about 17 miles from harrisburg. all the children left the farmhouse and ms. grubbs said she probably would try to drive the school bus home saturday night
mrs. holt and her visitors were without electricity from thursday night to saturday morning
driver linda barrett and her 13 passengers were able to leave agnes wynne's farm when roads were cleared saturday
a neighbor on a snowmobile took buffalo meat, eggs and bread to the wynne farm saturday morning because food was running short, mrs. barrett said
the de beers diamond firm has announced the discovery of an egg-sized, 599-carat diamond and said it is currently the world's largest uncut diamond with an estimated cut value of $30 million
officials of the south african company said the white diamond, dubbed ``the big rock,'' was found at a mine near pretoria in july 1986, but its discovery was kept secret to all but a handful of de beers executives
de beers' chairman julian thompson announced the find at the firm's 100th anniversary banquet in kimberly friday night
it's a perfect blue-white color,'' said south african gem expert gaby tolkowski, who will cut and polish the stone
there have been larger raw diamonds uncovered previously, but they were cut into smaller gems
the 1988 guinness book of world records recorded the cullinan diamond as the world's largest uncut diamond ever found. it was discovered in 1905 near pretoria and weighed 3,106 carats, or more than 1.25 pounds
the cullinan was cut into 105 stones, including the 530.2-carat star of africa, the world's largest known cut diamond, according to guinness. the star of africa is the centerpiece of the british royal scepter
in its cut form, the ``big rock'' is expected to be about 350 carats and sell for an estimated $30 million, the company said
debeers is the world's largest diamond company and controls an estimated 80 percent of the world's diamond production through its central selling organization in london. holt farm, driver expected to leave. picks up 7th graf, `power at...'.</note>
two busloads of children who had been snowbound at farms for two nights finally made it home saturday when snowplows cleared the roads
the 21 children and two bus drivers had taken refuge at the two homes during a raging snowstorm thursday afternoon, and had passed the time playing games and listening to a battery-operated radio. at one farm, electrical power was off for more than a day and meals were cooked on a campstove
drivers linda barrett and sharon grubbs were taking children home from the banner county school in harrisburg when the heavy snow and winds gusting to 55 mph enveloped their buses, reducing visibility to zero
the storm hit a little faster than we thought,'' said ms. grubbs, who was in radio contact with mrs. barrett when they decided to find shelter rather than continue
ms. grubbs and her eight children wound up at the farm of jack and karen holt, about 17 miles west of harrisburg. one of the maintenance workers who cleared the roads saturday was the father of two of the stranded children, mrs. holt said
all the children left saturday, including one who had to wait until her parents, stranded elsewhere by the storm, made it home. ms. grubbs said she would probably drive the school bus home saturday night
power at the holt farm was out from thursday night until about 7:30 a.m. saturday. it was about 38 degrees in the house before the heat came back on
we're all so thankful for the heat,'' said mrs. holt. ``we're fed and warm and wonderful.'' power was lost again about 2 p.m., but the house was staying warm, she said
the two women used a camping stove to cook meals as the children, ages 7 to 13, huddled under blankets. the three boys and five girls played games and listened to a battery-operated radio, mrs. holt said
they've been super for us,'' said ms. grubbs, a 10-year veteran bus driver. ``they've cooperated so well.''
mrs. barrett and her 13 passengers waited out the storm at agnes wynne's farm, about 20 miles from harrisburg. a snowplow cleared the road about 3 p.m. saturday, mrs. wynne said
mrs. wynne, who lives alone, said having so many children on hand ``was a little trying. but they were a good bunch of kids.'' worries that she wouldn't have enough food were eased when a a neighbor brought over buffalo meat, eggs and bread on his snowmobile. fire chief quote, detail on mop-up, fire breaks being built. picks up 8th graf pvs, `about 265,000. subs last 3 grafs, bgng, `elsewhere, a...', with 3 grafs to update with val verde county fire also brought under control. no pickup.</note>
a major brush fire that destroyed tens of thousands of acres of west texas prairie land appeared under control late saturday afternoon, officials said
for parts of friday and saturday, the fire seriously threatened the towns of albany and moran in shackelford county and baird in northern callahan county, but three tanker airplanes helped contain it by dropping fire-retardant chemicals
at least 265,000 acres were burned, and officials said the dry, windy weather continued to pose a danger that the fire could rekindle
sam logan, public information officer for the texas forest service, said the grass fires that ravaged much of shackelford county and parts of callahan and throckmorton counties since thursday were under control and the forest service was beginning its mop-up operation
that'll take about two days,'' logan said. but he added, ``we'll continue to keep an eye on it, because with the strong winds and low humidity, just a spark could start it up all over again.''
most of the fires appeared to be interior ones that appear likely to burn themselves out where they were, officials said
we've pretty well got fire guards around the complete fire. tonight, we're going to just more or less be running a patrol and mop-up operation,'' said baird fire chief pat mckennon. ``we will have forest service crews out and some local fire units out, just more or less patrolling.''
national guardsmen and other military personnel used heavy equipment such as bulldozer and scrapers to build fire breaks
the idea is to get the grass down real short so that if a fire jumps a street it doesn't ignite,'' said airman 1st class william cross from dyess air force base in abilene
the fire killed livestock, burned trailer homes and oilfield equipment and closed roads across parts of an area 60 miles long and 25 miles wide, officials said
about 265,000 acres of rangeland had burned in shackelford county alone, or roughly half the county, said joe fox of the texas forest service. albany, a town of about 2,500, is the county seat. smaller acreages were burned in the other two affected counties, officials said
at a 3,000-acre ranch south of albany, workers moved about 100 head of cattle away from the blaze while a u.s. forest service crew, with three bulldozers, fought flames earlier saturday that had rekindled in a pasture
it looks worse at night because that's when you can see the flames. during the day, the smoke covers everything,'' said wanda sims, a part-owner of the dyer-sims ranch. ``the night before last, it looked like hot lava moving down the hills.''
volunteer firefighter phillip rodriguez said he and hundreds of other workers stopped the flames just inside the city limits of baird, a town of about 1,700 people, about 7 a.m. saturday
when it was dark, all you could see was orange rolling down the hills,'' said rodriguez
smoke is drifting across baird. it is like we are having a big wienie roast out here,'' said callahan county sheriff's officer jan davis
some homes were evacuated friday night in the hannersville section of baird and authorities set up a command post, but no dwellings were lost in the community 21 miles east of abilene, said ms. davis. residents returned to their homes saturday
but in albany, 25 miles north, the fire consumed trailers and oilfield equipment, and its relentless march eastward earlier in the day saturday, fanned by strong winds, had worried authorities
there's plenty of damage to rangeland, oilfield equipment _ including storage tanks _ and some trailer houses,'' said albany mayor wayne hogan. ``we are still trying to get it under wraps after three days. but it seems to be under better control than this time yesterday
but if the wind changes, which it can do real sudden, we're in trouble again,'' he said
in moran, a town of about 340 people 16 miles southeast of albany, morris snyder jr. gazed with neighbors through a smoky haze at a long bluff a few miles away, pointing toward a line of flames
this is the worst anyone living here has seen,'' he had said, before the situation was reported under control. ``it's the worst anyone can remember.''
federal officials, at the request of texas emergency management officials, approved aid to help reimburse the state for expenses in fighting the blaze, which began thursday from a trash fire
murry fly, a spokesman for the texas forest service in lufkin, said crews arriving from around the state gave tired forest service crews, volunteers and national guardsmen the chance to rest
numerous firefighters, among hundreds battling the blaze, have suffered injuries from smoke inhalation and minor burns, said tom millwee of the division of emergncy management
an aircraft tanker containing 2,000 gallons of fire retardant chemical arrived saturday from the u.s. forest service in fort smith, ark., said millwee
`we are trying to survey the burned area from the air because you still can't drive through most of it,'' said hogan, the albany mayor. ``we lit backfires last night to protect rural houses just west of the city limits to stop the flames, advancing from the west and northwest.''
elsewhere, another range fire in val verde county, about 300 miles to the southwest, consumed about 60,000 acres before it was brought under control
mike scott, a spokesman with the governor's office of emergency management, said saturday night that national guard troops sent to the area had been released
there is still apparently some fires down there, but it's minor,'' scott said. inserts 1 graf after 25th graf, bgng: the ad xxx to include washington post-abc poll; picks up 26th graf pvs, bgng: after campaigning...</note>
jesse jackson easily won the democratic precinct caucuses saturday in his native south carolina, while sen. bob dole went on illinois television for a half-hour plea for republican votes in a state where he said he is the underdog
jackson took a commanding lead in the caucuses and maintained a better than 2-1 margin over the uncommitted, who represented the second-largest bloc of delegates being elected to county conventions in south carolina
with 78 percent of the precincts reporting, jackson was winning 53 percent of the delegates to the county conventions, while the uncommitted trailed with 20 percent. tennessee sen. albert gore was in third place with 19 percent and other candidates were far behind
dole, who spoke while standing before a portrait of abraham lincoln on the site where lincoln and stephen douglas held one of their famous debates, told illinois voters, ``i know i'm the underdog in this race
the issues are more important than the odds,'' dole said. ``i didn't expect this job to be handed to me in the first place.''
the kansas senator, who earlier acknowledged that his presidential campaign is ``hanging by our fingernails,'' invested $100,000 in the broadcast in an attempt to stop the momentum of gop front-runner, vice president george bush
a chicago tribune poll published in sunday editions said bush was far ahead of dole while homestate sen. paul simon was leading the democratic field, followed closely by jackson
the newspaper also endorsed gore in the democratic contest, passing over native simon and jackson, who has made illinois his adoptive home state
i dare george bush to debate bob dole,'' dole told a news conference. in originating his broadcast from knox college in galesburg, he had picked the time and site to conform to bush's appearance at the same location, he said
gore, whose success in southern primaries on march 8 catapulted him into contention in the democratic race, was counting on another boost from south carolina
we have worked very hard in this state and i think we have an opportunity to extremely well here,'' gore said during an appearance in columbia, s.c
but favored to get a majority of the 44 delegates at stake in south carolina was jackson, a native of greenville
jackson trailed massachusetts gov. dukakis by 58 in the latest associated press delegate count. strong showings in south carolina, where he was born, and illinois, which he now calls home, could propel jackson into the delegate lead in the democratic race
appearing at a meeting of the south carolina education association, jackson said, ``i'm delighted to be home again. you taught me. you can have somebody in the white house that you taught.''
rival rep. richard gephardt of missouri has the support of former govs. robert mcnair and richard riley, and is a strong backer of legislation to limit textile imports, an important issue in south carolina
gore said he too supported the legislation
bush crushed his republican opponents in the south carolina gop primary last saturday
simon was banking on illinois voters in tuesday's primary to give their home state senator enough support to keep him in the race
dukakis, jackson and gephardt made forays saturday into michigan, where democrats hold caucuses march 26
jackson addressed the graduation at michigan state unversity, recalling the tumult of the civil rights movement and calling on graduates to work for more than material wants
a generation of young americans died, sacrificed to keep america better and make america strong,'' he said. ``your generation must resist the dangerous trend of surrendering to the war of the opiate and the war of selfishness and the war of conceit and use your strength to take the torch another lap in this great struggle.''
dukakis visited the 250-worker olofsson corp. plant, which makes exotic, computer-controlled machines, and said the united states needs to re-invest in its industrial base
dukakis, seeking michigan union support against stiff competition from gephardt and jackson, said he plans to target his message to working people, teachers, homemakers and professionals
in illinois dukakis began airing a new commercial that appeared to be a veiled attack on simon who has been saying he thought the democratic nominee would be chosen at a brokered convention
the ad did not name simon, but said some people want to return to ``the days when you didn't really pick the presidential nominee. they say you must turn over the power to them to use at a brokered convention ... on tuesday you can pick the next president. mike dukakis is running for president in every state in america.''
a washington post-abc news poll published sunday showed simon supported by 39 percent of the 540 likely democratic voters interviewed on thursday and friday. jackson had 32 percent in the poll, followed by dukakis with 15 percent, gephardt with 5 percent and gore with 3 percent. the poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 7 percentage points
after campaigning in the city's ``greektown'' region on friday night, dukakis stopped saturday at an italian bakery on the city's west side to help bake bread. he offered a modest goal for illinois
if we can get some share of the delegates, i think it would be great,'' he said
bush has repeatedly rejected dole's debate challenges
that ploy has been used before,'' he said. ``debates are cruel and unusual punishment. we've already had seven of them.''
republican candidate pat robertson also was in illinois and insisted he did not need a victory in the state to remain the race
it looks strong for me in the west,'' he said. if he loses the fight for the gop nomination, said robertson ``i'll dust myself off and be right back in it in 1992.''
in the gop race, bush has 705 delegates, while dole was a distant second with 163. robertson has 17
meanwhile, a newsweek poll released saturday showed that bush would beat dukakis, gore or jackson if the presidential election were held today. the telephone survey of 755 voters thursday and friday had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points. the poll also indicated that dukakis would beat dole, but only by 1 percentage point _ within the survey's margin of error. dole would beat either gore or jackson, according to the survey
a bomb exploded saturday near a polling booth in dhaka, killing one person and wounding three as bangladeshis cast ballots in nine districts where voting had been postponed because of earlier violence
police said borhanuddin ahmed, 25, was killed in the explosion in downtown dhaka
at least 13 people were killed and more than 300 were wounded in violence during the parliamentary elections held on march 3, and the government stopped and rescheduled the voting in 125 districts. elections were held in nine districts saturday, but no results were reported
the major opposition parties boycotted the elections
president hussain muhammad ershad's jatiya party won 245 seats in the 300-member parliament in the march 3 balloting, according to results announced by the government. it said a coalition of 73 smaller groups and parties won 15 seats and independent candidates won 15
ershad's party plans to celebrate its victory with prayer meetings on march 16. opposition parties have called for protest rallies on march 24, the sixth anniversary of the bloodless coup that brought gen. ershad to power
leading the opposition campaign are sheik hasina and khaleda zia who have demanded that ershad resign. buser still ahead of redington, third team dropping out saturday. pickup 4th graf, bgng, `redington, who...' subs last five grafs, bgng, `nayokpuk, who...', with mushers reaching galena, updated positions of foreign and non-alaskan teams in last 2 grafs pvs.</note>
the 70-year-old founder of the iditarod trail sled dog race surrendered the lead saturday after setting the pace for more than 400 miles, and the leaders raced down the frozen yukon river
joe redington lost the lead to martin buser, who left galena with his dogs about an hour ahead of redington. they were still about an hour apart when they reached nulato, 52 miles downstream and 400 miles from the finish in nome
the race started in anchorage on march 5. the first musher to nome will collect $30,000 of a $150,000 purse; the next 19 finishers will split the rest. three of the 52 teams that started the race have dropped out, including one saturday
redington, who founded the race in 1973, has never won, although he has competed in all but two iditarods
redington had a 4{-hour lead when he left ruby on friday evening but buser, who moved to alaska from switzerland in 1979, made up time during the night. redington dropped one dog in galena, leaving him with just nine. buser also dropped one, but still had 14 in harness
i tried to travel with joe redington from cripple, but he disappeared in a hurry,'' said veteran herbie nayokpuk. ``i never saw him again. he has the dogs. if he gets those dogs running to nome, he's going to be a hard one to beat.''
rick swenson of two rivers and susan butcher of manley, the only mushers ever to win the marathon race more than once, arrived in galena about an hour before buser left. swenson, a four-time winner, and butcher, who won the last two races in record time, each had 13 dogs
nayokpuk, who had been near the lead throughout, checked in at galena at midmorning, and by afternoon, 10 mushers had reached there
don't write off anybody that's three or six hours off the pace right now,'' said one of them, jerry austin of st. michael. ``we're just inching our way up. we're steadily gaining on them.''
jacques philip, of thomery, france, led the foreign mushers in 15th place. horst maas, of lenz, austria, was in 25th; peter thomann of tagish in canada's yukon territory, was 31st; ian mackenzie of bruce mines, ontario, 41st; brian carver of melbourne, australia, 46th; and lesley anne monk of worsthorne, england, 48th
american mushers from outside alaska were paced by robin jacobson of minnetonka, minn., in 19th place. john patten of grand marais, minn., was 27th; frank teasley, jackson, wyo., 28th; terry adkins, mikado, mich., 29th; dan mceachen, snowmass village, colo., 32nd; and stan ferguson, philadelphia, 47th
the reagan administration created a new, permanent pentagon division to carry out covert paramilitary operations after the failure of the 1980 attempt to rescue american hostages in iran, according to a book to be released in april
the lack of coordination that led to the failure in desert one during the carter administration prompted the new administration to establish snow bird, to be run by a group of men in the army's new special operations division, says u.s. news &amp; world report senior editor steven emerson
the division was created following a decision by the new reagan administration to make permanent the counterterrorism, aviation and special-operations units assembled for the iran rescue mission,'' emerson says in excerpts of his book, ``secret warriors: inside the covert military operations of the reagan era,'' which were printed in this week's magazine
among other findings in the book, which emerson wrote based what he says was a year-long investigation and hundreds of interviews and thousands of documents obtained under the freedom of information act:
_in 1985, u.s. intelligence identified the precise location of the house where five of the six american hostages were being held in lebanon. identified as ``building 18,'' the site was reconstructed by u.s. intelligence agents as part of a portable mini-model used by u.s. officials to prepare a rescue operation. a detailed military rescue mission was planned by the pentagon's counterterrorist units in 1986, but it was scrapped when the iran-contra affair began to unfold
_u.s. officials negotiated with the palestine liberation organization and libyan intermediaries to obtain the hostages' release, according to classified portions of private notebooks of marine lt. col. oliver north, a national security council aide who was a central figure in the iran-contra affair. one plan, which later collapsed, called for covert payments of a total of $10 million to sheik fadlallah, the leader of the hezbollah organization holding the hostages and hussein massawi, the leader of the islamic amal militia. at u.s. request, the plo actually transferred some money to fadlallah to get the hostages out, but nothing happened, according to the book
_nsc sources said the man behind the kidnapping of the hostages was a shiite named immad mughniye. however, north said that mughniye's wife, whose relative was being held in a kuwaiti prison for terrorism, was running the show. ``ollie said mughniye wasn't going to get any sex until his (wife's relative) was released,'' says emerson
_intra-pentagon rivalry between counterterrorist organizations prevented the pentagon from participating in the search for kidnapped cia beirut station chief william buckley, who was later killed
_over several years, emerson says, the cia _ despite laws to the contrary _ exploited the secret pentagon units to carry out covert operations in central america to further the cause of the contra rebels fighting the sandinista government in nicaragua
burma's top rebel leaders called saturday for a political settlement of the 40-year-old insurgency and greater autonomy for the country's ethnic minorities
although the rebel's national democratic front operates in a region awash in opium and heroin production, the leaders denied involvement in drug trafficking. they have been accused of dealing in drugs to finance their war
democratic front leaders, in a meeting with journalists in this thai-burmese border town, called on the united states and other countries to cut support for the regime of president ne win
chiefs of the coalition of 10 guerrilla organizations claimed aircraft provided to ne win by the united states to fight the narcotics trade were being used in military operations against the insurgents
coalition chairman saw mah reh said the group wanted to ``present its case to the outside world'' and counter government claims that the insurgency would be crushed within two years
he called for peace negotiations to be conducted on neutral ground with an impartial mediator. three countries have expressed interest in the mediation role, he said, but he did not identify them or elaborate
the ndp does not want war and desires to end the civil conflict as soon as feasible,'' he said, calling for a democratic, multi-party system to replace ne win who has presided over one-party rule since 1962
the insurgency began shortly after burma became independent from britain in 1948. ethnic minorities said the original british concept of a federal union was changed by central government leaders
ethnic minority groups represented saturday were the mon, kachin, wa, palaung, pa-o, karenni, arakanese, lahu and shan
the leaders claimed a rigorous anti-narcotics policy had been laid down and opium eradication is being pursued
they said u.s.-provided helicopters were being used to ferry troops and ammunition to the battlefield and for medical evacuation. they also said chemical herbicides provided by the united states were causing illness among humans and killing livestock
washington has provided aircraft and herbicides to allow the burmese government to spray border areas where opium is grown
knowledgeable western narcotics sources say that some of the rebel groups probably are not involved in narcotics trafficking, but others are instrumental in the flow of opium that is used to produce heroin
the burmese communist party, which also is battling the government, is regarded by western diplomats as a major drug trafficker. the democratic front leaders said their ooperations with the communists were limited to ``military matters.''
the front claims it has 35,000 guerrillas and they control about half of the country. western military analysts say burma has more than 250,000 personnel in its military services, police forces and militias. tour</head>
hollywood's fabled ``rat pack,'' frank sinatra, dean martin and sammy davis jr., arrived here by private jetliner saturday night on the eve of a nostalgic north american tour
their sold-out show sunday at the oakland coliseum arena is the first of 40 performances that the stars will perform through oct. 1. promoters are billing it perhaps the last chance to see them together in concert
it's all about music, three good friends genuinely enjoying themselves on stage together,'' said mort viner, martin's manager and coproducer of the tour, last week. ``they'll probably be having more fun than the audience.''
sinatra, 72, martin, 70, and davis, 62, first performed together in las vegas in 1960. they went on to make three movies: ``ocean's 11,'' ``sergeants three,'' and ``robin and the seven hoods.''
among the other cities slated to be visited during the tour are chicago, minneapolis, pittsburgh, cleveland, washington, new york, los angeles, houston, atlanta, miami, philadelphia and boston
