thousands of armenians marched to city hall on saturday, carrying flags and chanting in a show of solidarity with a soviet republic involved in a territorial dispute on the other side of the globe
mounted police kept watch as the demonstrators gathered in pershing square before winding through downtown, singing and chanting and carrying signs and banners. police estimated the crowd at 5,000 people
saturday's protests in california were triggered by rioting that began late last month in the soviet union. armenians in the port town of sumgait, in the republic of azerbaijan, demanded that the region of nagorno-karabakh be united with the republic of armenia. nagorno-karabakh, populated largely by armenians, is currently a part of azerbaijan
soviet police and militia have moved into the region to calm tensions in the adjacent republics in the soviet union's southwest corner. some reports claim 32 people have died while others put the death toll much higher
we want to show our solidarity with our people and the protests taking place in soviet armenia,'' said lorig titizian, executive director of the armenian national committee western region, which organized the demonstration
the procession to city hall was led by about 15 black-robed armenian priests walking beneath a sign that read, ``no brotherhood without justice.''
we are marching to express our unity with armenians living both in karabakh and in armenia and in america,'' said the rev. arsag chatchadourian
harold ezell, western regional commissioner of the immigration and naturalization service, was one of the few speakers to address the crowd in english
i believe that in the state of california, where we have a first-generation armenian as governor ... we should do everything we can to support our friends,'' ezell said, referring to gov. george deukmejian
attorney general edwin meese iii and his friend, e. bob wallach, jointly briefed then-israeli prime minister shimon peres in october 1985 about the status of plans for a $1 billion iraqi pipeline project, the washington post said in sunday's editions
the newspaper said memos written by wallach and reviewed by the post described peres as enthusiastic and ``intensely'' interested in the project when briefed on it at an israeli embassy reception
wallach, in the memos, said he had given up hope of getting enough time to brief peres, when meese walked up to them and came to his rescue, according to the post
wallach said he had been expecting to meet with peres on the afternoon of his oct. 16, 1985 arrival here to discuss the pipeline project. peres' plane, however, arrived 90 minutes late and peres went directly to the reception
almost 1,000 guests were waiting, ``a mob scene,'' wrote wallach, but he waited for a break and managed to get to peres and introduce himself, the post said
he (peres) literally dragged me off into a corner at that moment and began discussing the project intensely,'' wallach said. but then a crush of people built up, led by then-israeli ambassador meir rosenne, who wanted peres to meet various members of congress. at that point, wallach said he gave up and peres asked him to wait around until after the reception
fortunately, as that time approached, my friend (wallach's usual phrase for meese) arrived and there was a three-way discussion which took approximately 10 minutes,'' the post quoted wallach as saying. ``he (peres) is very quick and we went right to the point and he was agreeable in all respects. it wasn't the kind of briefing i would have preferred, but it seemed to have been effective.''
wallach said peres later invited him to meet again in new york a few days later, and wallach said he did so, accompanied by a staffer from the national security council who had been assigned to expedite the pipeline plans and its construction by the bechtel group of san francisco
according to a memo composed by wallach on oct. 20, 1985, the meeting at the israeli embassy here was more of a ``briefing'' than a chat
independent counsel james c. mckay is investigating meese's role in the pipeline maneuvering to determine whether meese might have violated any laws in concert with wallach, swiss financier bruce rappaport, or anyone else
the pipeline was never built. boosters</head>
nasa plans to recommend to congress that a $1.2 billion, government-owned plant be built to make new booster rockets for the space shuttle, an idea blasted by a senator from utah where the boosters are now constructed by morton thiokol inc., according to a published report sunday
i suspect that this is one of those crazy ideas that was dreamed up by some empire-building bureaucrat,'' sen. jake garn, r-utah, was quoted by the washington post as saying. ``in this current budgetary climate, we shouldn't even be considering this kind of nonsense.''
the plan, which calls for a contractor to operate the booster-building plant, would end morton thiokol's monopoly on the booster manufacturing. the boosters are now built at a plant in wasatch, utah
the newspaper cited an unidentified industry source as saying that garn has been threatening to hold up space station funding if the plan isn't blocked
thiokol has dominated the solid rocket industry since 1973, when it first won the shuttle rocket contract, but the plan by the national aeronautics and space administration would give other firms an opportunity to get into the business
after the space station, this is the biggest initiative we've got going,'' said russ bardos, director of nasa solid propulsion systems. ``whoever wins this will be the biggest (rocket) propellant producer in the country.''
the proposal already has aroused the interest of four rival companies, the post said, identifying them as united technologies corp., aerojet general corp.; atlantic research corp. and hercules inc
a florida air national guard f-16 fighter crashed friday in woods, causing its cannon shells to explode, but the pilot parachuted 2,000 feet to safety, officials said
lt. col. levis deweese of jacksonville told officials the engine of the $14 million fighting falcon stopped. when he couldn't restart it, deweese said, he steered the plane to an unpopulated area and bailed out
deweese, 50, suffered minor injuries
the crash occurred about 10 a.m. two miles south of callahan, said lt. col. durham searcy, with the air national guard at jacksonville international airport
the crash touched off a small brush fire. the plane, with the 125th fighter group, was armed with 20mm cannon rounds, and the fire and crash caused them to explode, said lt. col. reubin owens, on-scene commander
deweese was returning from a training mission over the atlantic ocean
democrat brian moss on friday declared his candidacy for the u.s. senate against incumbent sen. orrin hatch _ the man who defeated moss' father for the seat in 1976
the 43-year-old son of former three-term sen. frank moss made his announcement during a spirited student assembly at granite high school, where his grandfather was the first principal
moss, who holds a degree in economics, is a travel agent and part-owner and manager of several sandwich shops. although his republican opponent is leading 2-1 in recent polls on his bid for a third term, moss said utah senatorial races are sometimes unpredictable, citing his father's surprise defeat 12 years ago by hatch
moss said if elected he would use the office of senator to attract more industry to the state and to eliminate foreign trade barriers now preventing local farmers and industries from selling products abroad. he also would like foreign economic competitors to pay for more of their own military defense
moss denounced president reagan's ``trickle-down economics,'' saying, ``you do not start building from the roof, you start from the foundation.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis predicted friday he will ``get my share of delegates'' in the illinois primary next week against favorite sons paul simon and jesse jackson
if mike dukakis won, it would be a turning point,'' dukakis told a news conference
he said he expects to ``get my share of delegates'' and to prove ``that i can appeal to people all over the country.''
polls indicate dukakis trails far behind simon and jackson among illinois democrats
the dukakis campaign began airing a new advertisement that addressed the prospect of a brokered convention, a theory put forth in part by simon's fading campaign
some people would like to turn back the clock, to go back to the days when the voters didn't really pick their presidential nominee,'' the narrator says on the ad
they say you must turn over that power to them, to use at a brokered convention. but you don't have to do that. on tuesday you can pick the next president. mike dukakis is running for president in every state in america, for a better economic future for every american. you decide. does illinois pick the next president?'' the ad says
at a speech at the university of illinois at chicago, dukakis drew parallels between his campaign and that of john f. kennedy 28 years ago
today, as in 1960, we are fighting for the future of america. here in the midwest, the battle has been joined. here in the midwest, the battle must be won and the old ways, as john kennedy said 28 years ago, the old ways simply will not do.''
the president of the alabama naacp and 13 other black lawmakers asked a judge friday to dismiss trespassing charges stemming from their bid to remove the confederate battle flag from the capitol dome
defense attorneys invoked claims of legislative immunity from such misdemeanor charges and said state historians, not republican gov. guy hunt, had jurisdiction to order any arrests while the capitol is being renovated
prosecutors did not comment on the defense claims at the brief hearing before district judge craig miller, who withheld a ruling pending the filing of further briefs
thomas reed, a lawmaker and state president of the national association for the advancement of colored people, vowed for weeks to remove the flag on feb. 2 after the legislature opened. the feat would require climbing an 8-foot chain-link fence, entering the locked building, climbing an inner stairwell to the white dome and taking the banner off a staff
hunt had said anyone who made such an attempt would be arrested
minutes after the legislature's opening gavel, state police pulled down reed and others as they made at least symbolic efforts to scale the fence. they nevergot near the building and the flag still flies atop the capitol dome
each lawmaker was charged with second-degree criminal trespassing and released from the county jail on $300 bond. conviction on the misdemeanor count carries a maximum penalty of three months in jail and a $500 fine
defense attorney fred gray said the legislators cannot be prosecuted for their attempt to climb the fence because the alabama constitution provides immunity from arrest to lawmakers while the legislature is in session
the trespassing charges should be dropped because no entry was made and the capitol is public property, he said
gray also told miller that hunt did not have the power to order the arrests because the capitol is under the control of the alabama historical commission while it is being renovated
the naacp says the flag is a racist symbol of oppression and slavery. hunt, who has said the legislature must decide whether to remove the flag, has said many view the banner as a historical symbol of the old south
despite gray's arguments, hunt is standing by his decision to have the lawmakers arrested, said his press secretary, terry abbott
our legal research showed that the governor is actually in charge of very distinct parts of the capitol,'' abbott said. ``most parts of the capitol, excluding the floor controlled by the legislature ... did fall to the governor.''
in another case friday involving the confederate flag, three bus drivers in durham, n.c., said they were fired and at least a dozen students were sent home after they arrived at school wearing the flags
when some of the chewing juniuor high school students and drivers later gathered at a store near the school, police set up a roadblock, but they would not say why
alesia keith, 22, who has driven a school bus for the durham county schools for three years, said she had the confederate flag tucked into her back pocket friday as a show of pride, not of racism. one of the drivers fired was black
this is southern pride day,'' ms. keith said. ``they can take my job and my money, but they can't take my pride.''
schools spokeswoman alisa terry said the students were dismissed for the day because their clothing was considered disruptive
administrators are meeting and will discuss with parents what kind of long-term action will be taken,'' she said
she also said no final decision had been made on the status of the three bus drivers, although they, too, were sent home for the day
a group of dissidents announced friday the formation of a small, independent ``university'' with western teaching methods to give students an alternative to state-supported soviet higher education
lev timofeyev, a former political prisoner who heads the unofficial group press club glasnost, said establishment of the school has not been approved by officials, but he said formal permission was unnecessary
the enrollment will be limited to 70 students. they will begin english-language training april 1, and an academic year that will begin in october, timofeyev said
the organizers plan to hold classes in apartments and will not charge tuition, timofeyev said. organizers hope to compensate the faculty with donations from the west
he said the roughly 50 students registered in moscow and 19 in leningrad will be taught by dissidents who have advanced degrees in physics, mathematics, language, literature and theology
but the school, called moscow independent university, also hopes to use western books and have instruction by western professors, either on videotape or in person, he said
a member of the group, valery soifer, said it already had agreements for assistance from long island university in new york, hebrew university in jerusalem and several french universities
timofeyev is to act as the school's president
glasnost is soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's policy of greater openness on selected subjects
former prime minister pierre elliott trudeau may not have had grounds for imposing the war measures act in october 1970 to deal with quebec separatists, according to the diary of a late cabinet minister
the sweeping powers given police by the act led to the arrests and detention of more than 460 civilians in quebec. only 62 were ever charged and 18 were convicted
trudeau justified his action by saying an insurrection was taking place in quebec, a predominantly french-speaking province, and police lacked the power to suppress it
a diary left by former transport minister don jamieson, who died in 1986, said two days after trudeau acted, the cabinet was told police had no evidence of an insurrection _ no firearms, ammunition or explosives
portions of the diary were published friday by the toronto magazine saturday night
jamieson's notations marked the first time in 18 years the official version of events was questioned by a person who was in the government at the time
trudeau, stopped on a street by a reporter and asked about jamieson's conclusions, said, ``look, i don't want to talk to the media for god's sake. read your history.''
the october crisis began when guerrillas of the quebec liberation front kidnapped british trade commissioner james cross and quebec labor minister pierre laporte. cross was freed after two months but laporte was killed
jamieson wrote that in his view, trudeau used the war measures act to assert federal power, not halt an insurrection
i am satisfied that from the very moment when cross was abducted the prime minister saw the incident as an issue on which we (the liberal party government) would stand or fall and through which he might very well be able to assert the federal position in a dramatic manner,'' jamieson wrote
truedeau retired in 1984 and an election returned the conservative party to take over the federal government
the separatist movement subsided in quebec after voters rejected a 1980 referendum on the issue
at least half of the 600 jobless miners who crossed the andes on foot last week to grow coca will be relocated by the save the children organization, it was announced friday
the miners, many with their families, arrived in the tropical town of chulumani 50 miles east of la paz over the weekend and said they would grow coca leaves unless the government provided them with jobs
bruce harris, director in bolivia of the westport, conn.-based save the children aid program, said arrangements have been made for at least 300 of the miners and their families to relocate in the town of circuata, 30 miles east of chulumani, where they will be encouraged to cultivate coffee, citrus plants and bananas
he said circuata residents have agreed to make land available, the government will assist with building houses and save the children will provide seeds, technical assistence and credits
the humid area around chululmani has been an important coca-leaf producing zone for generations. a paste is made from the leaves and then refined into cocaine
since 1985, more than 21,000 employees in the mining work force of 27,000 have lost their jobs as the government closed 14 of 21 government-owned mines because of the collapse of the tin market and deficits by the state mining company
the government has provided temporary jobs for 6,000 unemployed miners with funds provided by the united nations and some european governments
other jobless miners are living in tent cities on the outskirts of la paz or have gone to tropical zones to farm. coca leaves are a major cash product in this impoverished country with a population of 6.4 million
the reason for our presence in chulumani is very simple: we are demanding from the government a solution to our problem,'' augusto leon, the leader of a group of miners, said last week. ``all options for finding jobs are closed to us. we have nowhere to live ... so we have adopted this political decision.''
angola is seeking direct talks with south africa on peace in southern africa because the united states has lost credibility as a mediator, angola's industry minister, pedro de castro van-dunem, said friday
he told a news conference in lisbon that his marxist government has received signals that some south african officials were considering the possibility of direct negotiations
the minister said angola wanted to talk directly to south africa because the united states lost impartiality as mediator in the conflict by supplying the angolan rebel movement unita with arms and by welcoming guerrilla leader jonas savimbi in washington ``like a head of state.''
angola says 9,000 south african soldiers are in southern angola to support unita _ the national union for the total independence of angola
unita has fought since 1975 to force angola's government to share power
the soviet union and cuba support the angolan government
defense minister magnus malan of south africa has said his government would consider making a direct deal with moscow on ending the war in angola if a non-aligned government was established in luanda
swedish tv said friday that non-jews expelled from the soviet union were issued visas to israel as a way of inflating official jewish emigration statistics while getting rid of dissidents
it interviewed baltic dissidents friday who said soviet authorities gave them visas to israel when they were expelled even though they were not jewish
swedish television said it knew of 47 cases in past months where non-jews were registered as jews in emigration documents and given visas to israel
janis barkans, a lithuanian nationalist who served six years in a soviet prison and was an activist before being expelled, told a tv reporter soviet authorities gave him an ultimatum after a demonstration in riga last summer
they told me that either i leave the country or i would go to prison again ... a jewish visa arrived automatically shortly afterward,'' he said
barkans said he was not jewish and had not asked for such a visa
i met many jews in jail. they had been put there only because they wanted to emigrate to their historical home country,'' barkans said
the television said at least 32 lithuanians and 15 estonians, all of them non-jews, were expelled on visas to israel. several came to sweden
according to statistics from the geneva-based intergovernmental committe for migration, 8,011 soviet jews left the communist country last year for permanent resettlement abroad, about eight times the annual rate of the previous five years. in 1986, only 943 jews were allowed to leave
it was not clear whether non-jews carrying visas for israel were included in those statistics
president blaise compaore of burkina faso outlined his government's new program friday and made it clear that he will give business and foreign interests a warmer welcome than his predecessor did
in a radio broadcast monitored in abidjan, compaore said that with burkina faso's ``limited resources, the state alone cannot pretend to do anything.''
compaore led the oct. 15 coup in which president thomas sankara was killed. it was the fifth coup in the poor west african nation of 7.5 million since burkina faso _ formerly upper volta _ won independence from france in 1960. both men were army captains and compaore was a close aide of sankara's
sankara had antagonized business people and western governments and creditors with his policies and statements attacking western imperialism
compaore said friday his government will work with national, foreign and private sectors, an apparent reference to his efforts to improve government relations with national trade unions, commercial interests and foreign neigbors
the new program, published later friday in the official daily sidwaya newspaper, pledged to continue some economic reforms begun under sankara
the program called for a ``reinforcement of industrial production and the rehabilitation of factories that are underused or currently dormant.''
the plan pledged to ``enlarge and reinforce democracy.'' its most striking change was abolition of sankara's feared revolutionary defense committees in favor of smaller organizations with a social and cultural focus. the organizations would be separate groups of rural peasants, blue collar workers, youth, civil servants, women and the elderly
compaore avoided offending elements sympathetic to sankara. without directly naming sankara, he noted his speech borrowed ideas from the political program sankara laid out in a 1983 speech made shortly after taking power
compaore's foreign relations program was more moderate than the radical policies of sankara, which criticized france's africa policy and its involvement in chad. the sankara program troubled many of burkina faso's neighbors, whose relations with libyan leader moammar gadhafi have been strained
compaore said his program was drawn up after a review of the four years of sankara's government. he offered no direct criticism of sankara and only briefly referred to his seizure of power as a ``rectification process.''
compaore also pledged to continue the government crackdown on corruption and laziness begun when sankara took power in 1983
the united states has begun testing two types of single-use syringes to help stop the spread of aids and hepatitis transmitted by contaminated needles, an american official said friday
alan woods, administrator of the u.s. agency for international development, announced the disposible syringe tests at an international conference of doctors and health experts
woods declined to say how much money the united states was spending on developing the syringes, but he said they could be on the market by the end of the year
unlike other disposible syringes already in use, neither of the two new types can be reused, woods said
he said they are being tested by the program for appropriate technology in health, a seattle-based company, under contract to the government. woods did not provide details on the tests at the conference on immunization and children's health
woods said several other countries also are testing pre-filled, single-use syringes, including france and switzerland
when they are ready, we will have to flood the market with these devices,'' said dr. william foege, director of the task force for child survival, the conference sponsor
we will have to find some way of subsidizing the cost to get them to developing countries because they'll be too expensive at first. and we'll have to find some way to get the old syringes off the market,'' said foege, former director of the centers for disease control in atlanta, ga
contaminated needles are responsible for the spread of a number of diseases in developing countries and are a particular threat to young children receiving vaccine injections
needles contaminated with the hiv virus are believed to be a major method of transmitting aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, the fatal disease that attacks the body's immune system leaving it vulnerable to cancers and other diseases
aids can be transmitted by sex, intravenous drug use, blood transfusion and from infected pregnant mothers to fetuses
three-quarters of those carrying the aids virus will develop either the fatal disease or an aids-related condition within six years of infection, university of california scientists reported friday
researchers from uc-san francisco said their three-year study made important advances in tracking the progression of the virus but found little to encourage hope for long-term survival among those infected with it
what we saw was that the number of those showing no effects from hiv (aids virus) infection is very small,'' said andrew moss, ucsf associate professor of epidemiology and international health.``this means that if you are infected with the aids virus, you will almost certainly go on to get aids.''
the findings were published in saturday's british medical journal
the study was the first to base the prediction of progression to aids or aids-related complex, called arc, on microscopic changes in patients' blood, the researchers said
the author of an earlier study on the topic said the new report apparently provides important information for infected people trying to decide whether to take immediate risks with anti-viral drugs or wait for advances in treatment
the big question still is, `will everybody at some point progress (from the virus to aids) ... or is there a chance that some people will be able to ride it out for 15 years?''' said paul o'malley, director of the city public health department's aids research project
as each year progresses we know more, but we still can't fully answer it,'' said o'malley
o'malley's study, released in february 1987, found that of 104 men infected with the aids virus, 15 percent developed aids within five years, 22 percent developed the disease within six years and 33 percent had it within seven years. in addition, many of the patients who did not have full-blown aids after six years suffered from arc
the national centers for disease control has estimated that 20 percent to 30 percent of the 1 million to 1.5 million americans infected with the aids virus will develop the disease by the end of 1991
the cdc reported this week that 55,167 cases of aids in the united states have been reported since june 1981; 30,932 of those people have died
researchers at ucsf followed 288 men with the virus for three years and used five ``markers'' in the blood to estimate how many would contract aids or arc after another three years. the markers included measurements of proteins and cells
twenty-two percent of study participants developed aids during the three-year period and 19 percent developed arc, a milder form of the disease that can develop into aids
an additional 24 percent had laboratory abnormalities that the researchers found to be highly predictive of aids or arc
extrapolating from the evidence, the scientists said an additional 10 percent would develop aids or arc within six years, for a total of 75 percent
even the men who had not developed aids or arc after three years showed clear signs of progression toward a worsened condition in their blood markers, the study found
the researchers described their six-year estimates as conservative, saying the actual rate of progression may be much higher
hiv infection is much more serious than we thought in the early days,'' moss said. ``it may take eight or nine years, but eventually the infected person will probably get aids.''
a man who escaped from a michigan prison in 1984 and started a secret new life in ontario pleaded guilty friday to 58 armed robberies across canada
los angeles-born gilbert galvan, 30, was accused of obtaining cash and jewelry worth more than $1.8 million (u.s.) in the robberies
he was sentenced to 20 years in prison by an ontario provincial court judge in pembroke
galvan robbed banks in 14 canadian cities from halifax to vancouver, police said. the peterborough examiner said galvan became known as the ``flying bandit'' because he traveled to holdups on air canada, the national airline
he robbed one bank in peterborough on three separate occasions and once looted two banks in regina, saskatchewan, in less than an hour, according to police
they said he carried a loaded gun but never committed physical violence
police said galvan fled prison in st. joseph county, mich., on may 18, 1984, with eight years still to serve for embezzlement
he entered canada using the alias of robert lee whiteman and later was married, according to statements to the court
police said galvan's wife believed he was a computer salesman and was shocked _ and pregnant _ when they arrested him in pembroke last june in connection with a holdup in london, ontario
he was sentenced to 11 years for that robbery, and police then put together a case linking him with 58 additional bank and jewelry store robberies
his 20-year sentence will be served concurrently with the 11-year term
some loot was recovered, but police said galvan may have stashed money in banks in europe or the caribbean, where he often vacationed with his wife
police said galvan always had a gun, always wore a disguise, and usually passed a note to a teller
when he was arrested, police said galvan told officers he was only going to ``do a few more and then quit.''
the u.n. human rights commission ended its annual session friday after accepting an invitation from cuban president fidel castro to visit cuba to determine if abuses were taking place
u.n. spokesman jean-paul riviere said that 78 resolutions on human rights situations throughout the world were adopted during the six-week session. last year, the 43-nation panel adopted 61 measures
the resolutions denounced a wide range of violations, with emphasis on the situations in the israeli-occupied territories, southern africa, chile, iran and afghanistan. the mandates of special u.n. investigators were extended
the commission also took about 20 other decisions, including one late thursday accepting the castro government's invitation to send a delegation for an inquiry into allegations of rights abuses
that decision, drafted by four latin american countries, was approved without vote. it was the first time cuba agreed to admit foreign investigators. the delegation will visit cuba this summer and report its findings to the 1989 session of the commission
the united states subsequently withdrew a draft resolution calling for u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar to examine the rights situation in cuba and report to the commission
u.s. chief delegate armando valladares, a former cuban political prisoner, said the plan ``goes far beyond what we had originally asked. it is very important.''
an apparent stowaway was found dead friday in the cargo hold of a banana boat on which seven other men had hidden in hopes of getting into the country, authorities said
four of the stowaways were caught thursday, and three more came out of hiding and were caught trying to run away friday when a workman unloading colombian bananas from the freighter discovered the body, authorities said
a carton of bananas, apparently fallen from a stack, lay across the body
james wright, a spokesman for the metro-dade police, would not speculate on the cause of death and said an autopsy scheduled for saturday
joe livingston, who found the body, said it appeared the man had been hiding in a small floor space cleared by moving cartons aside
the seven stowaways were in immigration and naturalization service custody. george waldroup, an ins spokesman, said seven are believed to be colombian. the nationality of the dead man was not immediately known
the british-registered castaneda calls at the port of miami every 11 days, officials said. it arrived after a five-day voyage from santa maria, colombia
loma linda medical center said friday has accepted a fourth baby born with most of his brain missing and will keep it alive for up to a week in hopes that its organs can be used for transplant
the boy, identified only as baby d, was born at an unidentified southern california hospital thursday and transferred to loma linda university medical center, said anita rockwell, a spokeswoman for the center
baby d suffers from anencephaly, in which most of the brain is missing. the condition almost always leads to death within days or weeks. ``his parents want to donate their baby's organs when brain death occurs,'' rockwell said
dr. joyce peabody, loma linda chief of neonatology, said baby d was resting comfortably friday and receiving nutrition and water as needed. rockwell said the newborn will be cared for for a seven-day period that began thursday night
under loma linda policy, baby d will be placed on life support if needed to prevent damage to organs
if baby d is declared brain-dead within seven days, the hospital will give notice that his organs are available for transplant. if he isn't brain dead within seven days, he will be allowed to die
the time limit was developed to alleviate ethical concerns that doomed anencephalics not be kept alive indefinitely merely so their organs can be donated
rockwell said anonymity was requested by baby d's parents and officials of the hospital where he was born
baby d is the fourth anencephalic newborn accepted as a possible organ donor at the hospital
the first was stillborn dec. 23, thwarting her parents' desire to have her major organs donated. her corneas and heart valves were given to infants needing them
the second anencephalic was declared brain-dead feb. 18. attempts to donate his liver failed because potential recipients either weren't suitable matches or couldn't be operated on in time. he was disconnected from life-support feb. 20
most recently, a girl was transferred to loma linda after birth feb. 20. because she never met brain-death criteria within the seven-day limit, she was disconnected from a respirator and allowed to die on feb. 28. however, her eyes, corneas and heart valves were later donated to infants needing organs
loma linda gained worldwide attention in 1984 when dr. leonard bailey, frustrated at the lack of heart donors for babies, transplanted a baboon's heart into a girl known as baby fae. she died 20{ days later
bailey, whose baboon transplant was sharply criticized by many doctors, subsequently urged the use of anencephalics as donors of hearts and other organs
guests in three floors of london's grosvenor house hotel were evacuated friday night when fire broke out in an air conditioning unit, the management reported
hotel manager francis green said the unit was in the top floor of the 10-story hotel and the guests in the three floors below were evacuated
there was no panic and no one was injured,'' green said
the evacuated guests went to the hotel restaurant and bar on a lower floor until the fire was extinguished an hour after it started, he said
green said there was minimal damage to the rooms
andreas whittam smith, editor of the independent newspaper, appeared at a hearing in the old bailey central criminal court on friday over alleged possession of a secret document on the fight against terrorism
the hearing before judge aron owen was closed but whittam smith told reporters his newspaper was accused of having a document obtained in violation of the official secrets act
we shall argue against that most strongly,'' he said after the case was adjourned to next week
a story in his paper thursday described proposals in a ``draft confidential report'' on how information would be built up by the 12 european governments in a data base to keep track of extremists across frontiers
it said the british were unenthusiastic about the idea because of reluctance to endanger informants and surveillance methods
the interior ministers of the 12 governments involved are known as the trevi group, after the italian town where their first meeting was held in 1976
the story did not say how the document was obtained. a police order served on the independent to surrender the document said it concerned a meeting of the trevi group in brussels last january
press and public were excluded from the old bailey hearing at the request of government law officers
whittam smith said his daily's attorney, desmond brown, had argued that the 1911 official secrets act could not apply to a document obtained outside britain and one that was held by all 12 members in the trevi agreement
under the act, unauthorized release of government information is illegal
the independent story by its domestic affairs correspondent, sarah helm, said the killing of three irish republican army members by british security agents in gibraltar last monday ``is seen as firm proof that intercountry cooperation promoted by trevi is working.''
the leader of northern ireland's largest protestant paramilitary group resigned friday, four days after a foiled attempt on his life
the ulster defense association announced that it was ``mutually agreed'' that andy tyrie, 48, would step down as chairman, a post he has held since 1973. no successor was immediately named
on monday, a clandestine protestant group calling itself the loyalist people's reaction force claimed responsiblity for planting the bomb that tyrie found attached to his car
tyrie, considered a moderate in the british province's sectarian feuding, advocates independence for northern ireland under a power-sharing protestant-roman catholic administration
the ulster defense association, with an estimated 10,000 members, was established in 1971 as an umbrella group for protestant vigilante groups. it defines its main aim as preventing the unification of predominantly protestant northern ireland and the catholic-dominated irish republic to the south
although the organization is widely assumed to be armed, the british government has resisted calls by the catholic minority to outlaw it
tyrie became prominent in 1974 when he led hooded paramilitaries in support of worker strikes that destroyed a joint catholic-protestant administration set up by the british government
but later he came to embrace power-sharing as a way to end the province's two decades of conflict between protestants and catholics
tyrie was credited with unifying and imposing discipline on the ulster defense association and with ending random killings of catholics attributed to the organization
but he lost some influence because of his reluctance to throw the group's weight behind large street protests against the 1985 anglo-irish agreement. that pact gives the irish republic a consultative role in running northern ireland
his organization also was wracked by allegations that it was involved in extortion and racketeering, sometimes in league with its archenemy, the irish republican army. dissidents accused tyrie of failing to clamp down on the alleged abuses
under tyrie, the ulster defense association produced a blueprint for power-sharing that was hailed as a farsighted attempt to break the deadlock between catholics and protestants. john mcmichael, the group member largely responsible for the blueprint, was assassinated by the ira last december. ^eds: name salah salah is cq.</head>
salah salah, a leader of one of the factions in the palestine liberation organization, was detained by syrian troops stationed along the lebanese-syrian border, police sources said friday
the sources, speaking with the condition they not be identified, said salah was seized monday as his chauffeur-driven car arrived at the masnaa border post
they said salah's palestinian driver was released but salah was taken away and they had no information about his whereabouts
salah, 48, is a politburo member of george habash's marxist popular front for the liberation of palestine _ pflp. neither pflp nor plo officials would comment on the police report
salah had played an active role in gaining the release march 1 of two united nations relief officials, a swede and a norwegian, who had been kidnapped and held captive by moslem militants for 25 days
the police sources said they did not know if salah's detention was linked to his mediation to free the scandinavians
they said salah was en route to the pflp headquarters in damascus, the syrian capital, when he was seized by the soldiers
syria has 25,000 military personnel in northern and eastern lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate issued by the arab league because of the civil war between lebanese moslem and christian militias
damascus has supported rebels opposed to plo chief yasser arafat since 1983. the pflp has maintained good relations with the syrian government even after a reconciliation last year with arafat
argentina asked friday for a u.n. security council meeting on british military maneuvers under way near the disputed falkland islands, a spokesman for the argentine mission to the united nations said
ambassador marcelo e.r. delpech made the request at a meeting with the president of the council, yugoslav ambassador dragoslav pejic, according to the spokesman
the falklands are a british colony, but argentina maintains its claim to the islands 500 miles off the argentine coast based on settlers dating from the early 1880s
in 1982, argentine forces invaded and captured the islands, but they were defeated by a british task force in a 74-day war
argentina has denounced the british military exercises as a provocation and put its armed forces on alert
the organization of american states expressed concern and called on both countries to resume negotiations over the the islands, known in argentina as the malvinas
ricardo ernesto lagorio, a spokesman for argentina's u.n. mission, said the security council was expected to hold consultations next week to decide how to approach the issue. news digest: los angeles _ weird allergies, a0442</note>
