president reagan on friday froze millions of dollars in panamanian assets in the united states and again called on gen. manuel antonio noriega to step down as chief of the 15,000-member defense forces
reagan said he is prepared to take additional steps against panama's government if the economic sanctions do not force noriega from power
independent counsel lawrence e. walsh says the guilty plea and promise of cooperation from former national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane will help advance his investigation of the iran-contra affair
mcfarlane's plea ``furthers the work of the office of independent counsel because he has agreed to cooperate fully'' in the investigation, walsh said friday following the former national security adviser's arraignment in u.s. district court
mcfarlane pleaded guilty to four misdemeanor charges of withholding information from congress by falsely assuring lawmakers that members of his staff, specifically lt. col. oliver l. north, were not involved in private efforts to arm the nicaraguan rebels during a statutory ban on direct u.s. aid to the contras
