kansas sen. bob dole, acknowledging that ``we're hanging by our fingernails,'' announced friday he has purchased 30 minutes of television time tonight and he challenged bush to join him ``to discuss the issues.''
the vice president rejected a one-on-one debate with dole
the administration has reluctantly ordered the closing of the plo observer mission at the united nations because of a law secretary of state george p. shultz called ``one of the dumber things that congress has done lately.''
attorney general edwin meese iii gave the palestine liberation organization mission in new york until march 21 to close, saying the department would then go to federal court to enforce the anti-terrorism act of 1987
the 1947 treaty under which new york became u.n. headquarters obliges the united states to let all accredited missions operate, u.n. officials and the state department have said
the woman who resigned as head of gallaudet university after angry student protests says officials didn't foresee that having a deaf president would become ``a national civil rights matter.''
elisabeth ann zinser, who can hear and does not know sign language, said a week of outcry over her appointment at the school for the deaf made her see that deaf people as a group must ``take their place in society and this had become the time.''
i have responded to this extraordinary social movement of deaf people, not to the demands of the students and protesters,'' she said
the army barred worshipers from three mosques in gaza city on the moslem holy day in an attempt to keep order, but israeli soldiers wounded nine arabs in protests after prayer services in the occupied lands
